// SSA refcount inserter (Step 5 of the insert-where-needed pivot; Step 6 made it
// the SOLE owner of release insertion by retiring the pre-mem2reg InjectDrops).
//
// Runs per function on post-mem2reg Std-IR (block-argument / phi form) and
// materializes the MINIMAL incref/decref set from the persisted per-ValueId
// ownership classification (Step 1, threaded through mem2reg in Step 3) and
// the Std-IR per-value liveness pass (Step 4). Lowering emits NO refcount ops;
// this pass supplies every +1 and every −1 for value/local lifetimes (container
// FIELD decrefs stay the destructor's job — the "balancing invariant" below).
//
// TWO release domains, both placed at exact per-value last use (see
// `releaseKindAtLastUse`):
//   - MANAGED references → `mm_incref` / `mm_decref` (the main model below).
//   - GENERIC TYPE-PARAMETER values (a `var x T` in a function kept generic) →
//     `sys.dropTypeParam`, routing destruction through the `__layout`
//     descriptor's `destroyFunc`. These are NOT `valueManaged` (a type-parameter
//     is not drop-tracked), so they bypass the incref machinery entirely and are
//     only RELEASED (never acquired/incref'd) — the generic value is created
//     once and dropped once. Detected by the persisted per-VALUE `valueTypeParam`
//     bit (mem2reg promotes type-parameter locals to SSA, leaving no slot to key
//     off), which subsumes InjectDrops's slot-keyed `slotIsTypeParameter`.
// (InjectDrops also carried a raw-heap `sys.free` path keyed on `sys.globalAddr`,
// but globalAddr is a STATIC-data address, never a heap allocation — freeing it
// is always wrong, and InjectDrops never actually emitted one — so that domain
// was dropped, not ported. See the note in `insertRefcountsInFunction`.)
//
// =====================================================================
// The balancing invariant (stated, then held)
// =====================================================================
// For each managed SSA value V, the inserter-emitted LOCAL increfs equal its
// LOCAL decrefs on EVERY path. An incref that writes V into a heap container
// (field/payload/element store_indirect) is NOT local — it is balanced by the
// CONTAINER's destructor when the container's rc hits 0 (destructor synthesis,
// Step 2). The inserter never also places a local decref for those. A value
// returned/thrown transfers its +1 to the caller — its would-be last-use decref
// is replaced by that transfer (suppressed, not emitted).
//
// =====================================================================
// The model (verified against the C# golden's net behavior)
// =====================================================================
// A managed value V either OWNS a local +1 or it does not:
//
//   ACQUIRE (+1 at the def of V) for the classes that do NOT arrive owning a
//   transferable reference:
//     - freshRc0          (mm_alloc result, rc starts 0 → the first owner's +1)
//     - incomingOwner      (loaded alias / field-load / merged phi: a new local
//                           owning ref over the source's)
//     - selfReturnBorrow   (borrows a param's ref → a new owner must incref)
//   NO acquire for:
//     - callReturnRc1      (the call already transferred a +1 — consume it)
//     - borrowed           (a view; the collection owns it — never refcount)
//     - a PARAM value      (the caller owns the +1 — the callee borrows)
//
//   RELEASE (−1 at V's last use on each path) for every managed V EXCEPT:
//     - borrowed           (never owned a local ref)
//     - a PARAM value      (caller owns it)
//     - V returned/thrown  (the +1 transfers to the caller)
//     - V moved into a phi (the +1 transfers into the merged block-arg — the
//                           MOVE guard, F4: decref'ing both the edge value AND
//                           the phi is a double-free)
//
// HEAP-STORE incref (+1 before each store_indirect that stores a managed V):
//   ALWAYS — the container takes its own reference; balanced by the container
//   destructor, never by a local decref. Orthogonal to acquire/release.
//
// RETURN/THROW transfer:
//   - acquired classes (freshRc0/incomingOwner/selfReturnBorrow): the def-acquire
//     +1 is the reference handed to the caller — NO return-incref, suppress the
//     last-use decref.
//   - callReturnRc1: already holds the +1 — NO return-incref, suppress decref.
//   - a PARAM value returned: no acquire happened and the caller still owns its
//     own +1 → emit a RETURN-INCREF so the caller receives a fresh owned ref.
//
// =====================================================================
// Placement (what survives mem2reg; how last-use is found)
// =====================================================================
// mem2reg DISSOLVES promoted slot stores/loads — a promoted local has no
// storeSlot to hang a "decref-old-on-overwrite" on; old and new are distinct
// SSA ids, so the classic self-assign hazard (F7) is structurally absent. Only
// heap stores (store_indirect) survive, and those ALWAYS incref.
//
// Last use is found via Step-4 liveness:
//   - IN-BLOCK death: the body-op position i where V is live BEFORE op i but not
//     AFTER it, with V NOT live-out of the block. The decref goes right after i.
//   - EDGE death: V is live-out of B but dead entering successor S (V ∉ liveIn[S]).
//     The decref goes on the B→S edge. If S has multiple predecessors the edge is
//     critical and is SPLIT (a fresh edge block carries the decref) so V is not
//     released on a sibling path where it is still live.
//
// Loop hoisting (moving an invariant value's incref to the preheader / decref to
// the loop exits) is DEFERRED — per-iteration last-use placement is correct and
// total; hoisting is a code-quality optimization for a later pass (see the
// report). Per-value liveness over the full CFG (including back-edges and
// break/continue/throw exits) already makes per-iteration placement sound.

// Sentinel: "no value". ValueId is always >= 0, so i64.max never collides.
let REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE = i64.max

// ============================================================
// Entry point
// ============================================================

// The SSA refcount inserter — the sole owner of release insertion. Emits BOTH
// release domains: managed `mm_incref`/`mm_decref`, and generic type-parameter
// `sys.dropTypeParam` (for OWNED generic locals not moved into a container; see
// `releaseKindAtLastUse`). The user pipeline runs this.

// Debug helper: name an OwnershipClass for `--log=ir:trace` RC- diagnostics.
function ownershipClassName(cls OwnershipClass) returns String
	return match cls 'name'
		notManaged gives "notManaged"
		freshRc0 gives "freshRc0"
		callReturnRc1 gives "callReturnRc1"
		selfReturnBorrow gives "selfReturnBorrow"
		incomingOwner gives "incomingOwner"
		borrowed gives "borrowed"
	end 'name'
end 'ownershipClassName'

// Debug helper: name a ReleaseKind for `--log=ir:trace` RC- diagnostics.
function releaseKindName(kind ReleaseKind) returns String
	return match kind 'name'
		none gives "none"
		decref gives "decref"
		dropTypeParam gives "dropTypeParam"
		dropManaged gives "dropManaged"
	end 'name'
end 'releaseKindName'

export function insertRefcounts(module StdModule, funcParamConsumes FuncParamConsumesMap, funcReturnsConsumedArg FuncReturnsBorrowSet, funcReturnsBorrow FuncReturnsBorrowSet, funcReturnsReceiverInterior FuncReturnsBorrowSet, mmTrace bool = false) returns StdModule
	for func in module.functions 'eachFunc'
		insertRefcountsInFunction(func, module: module, funcParamConsumes: funcParamConsumes, funcReturnsConsumedArg: funcReturnsConsumedArg, funcReturnsBorrow: funcReturnsBorrow, funcReturnsReceiverInterior: funcReturnsReceiverInterior, includeManaged: true, mmTrace: mmTrace)
	end 'eachFunc'

	return module
end 'insertRefcounts'

// Type-parameter-only inserter: emits ONLY `sys.dropTypeParam` (the generic-
// local destruction the retired `InjectDrops` provided), skipping the managed
// `mm_incref`/`mm_decref` domain. The STDLIB pre-compile sandbox runs this so
// generic templates (Map/Array/Set methods) destroy their OWNED type-param
// locals that are NOT moved into container storage. Managed (non-type-param)
// refcounting for stdlib is supplied by the user pipeline post-inline; running
// the managed domain in this sandbox too over-acquires and leaks.
export function insertTypeParamDrops(module StdModule) returns StdModule
	// Type-param-only mode never reads the consume registries (consume is a
	// managed-domain concern); pass empty ones.
	let emptyConsumes = FuncParamConsumesMap.create()
	let emptyReturnsConsumed = FuncReturnsBorrowSet.create()
	let emptyReturnsBorrow = FuncReturnsBorrowSet.create()
	let emptyReturnsInterior = FuncReturnsBorrowSet.create()
	for func in module.functions 'eachFunc'
		insertRefcountsInFunction(func, module: module, funcParamConsumes: emptyConsumes, funcReturnsConsumedArg: emptyReturnsConsumed, funcReturnsBorrow: emptyReturnsBorrow, funcReturnsReceiverInterior: emptyReturnsInterior, includeManaged: false, mmTrace: false)
	end 'eachFunc'

	return module
end 'insertTypeParamDrops'

// ============================================================
// Per-function driver
// ============================================================

function insertRefcountsInFunction(func IrFunction, module StdModule, funcParamConsumes FuncParamConsumesMap, funcReturnsConsumedArg FuncReturnsBorrowSet, funcReturnsBorrow FuncReturnsBorrowSet, funcReturnsReceiverInterior FuncReturnsBorrowSet, includeManaged bool, mmTrace bool)
	if func.blockRefs.count() == 0 'empty'
		return
	end 'empty'

	// Fast path: a function with no value that needs a release op in an enabled
	// domain skips the whole pass (no CFG/liveness build). The managed domain is
	// gated by `includeManaged` (the stdlib sandbox runs type-param-only).
	//
	// There is deliberately NO raw-heap `sys.free` release domain: the only
	// `RawHeapAllocSet` candidate, `sys.globalAddr`, loads the address of a
	// STATIC data global (a string literal / module var / rdata descriptor — see
	// `StdSystemOp.globalAddr`), never a heap allocation. Freeing it would
	// `mrt_free` an .rdata/.data address (heap corruption). The legacy injector
	// carried the same globalAddr-as-heap scan but its slot-tracking never
	// actually selected such a value to free (zero `sys.free` emitted across a
	// whole self-host build), so the path was vacuous there; the liveness-precise
	// inserter WOULD free it at last use, so the domain is dropped entirely. Real
	// heap acquisition flows through `mrt_alloc` CALLs, which are managed
	// `callReturnRc1` values handled by the decref domain.
	if not funcNeedsReleaseInsertion(func, includeManaged: includeManaged) 'noRelease'
		return
	end 'noRelease'

	let firstBlockRef = try func.blockRefs.get(0) otherwise panic("insertRefcounts: blockRefs non-empty but get(0) failed")
	let entryBlock = try module.blocks.get(firstBlockRef) otherwise panic("insertRefcounts: firstBlockRef not in module.blocks")
	let entryBlockId = entryBlock.id
	let numBlocks = func.nextBlockId

	let cfg = buildCfg(func, module: module)
	let rpo = computeReversePostorder(entryBlockId, numBlocks: numBlocks, cfg: cfg)
	let domInfo = computeDominators(entryBlockId, numBlocks: numBlocks, cfg: cfg, rpo: rpo)
	let liveness = computeStdLiveness(module, func: func, cfg: cfg, rpo: rpo, funcReturnsBorrow: funcReturnsBorrow, funcReturnsReceiverInterior: funcReturnsReceiverInterior, funcParamConsumes: funcParamConsumes)

	let idRef = ValueIdRef.create(scanMaxValueId(func, module: module) + 1)

	// Param value ids: caller owns their +1 — never acquire/release locally.
	let paramValues = collectParamValues(module, entryBlock: entryBlock)

	// Values flowing into `ret` / `errorReturn` across the whole function: their
	// last-use decref is suppressed (transferred to the caller).
	let returnedValues = collectReturnedValues(func, module: module)

	// Addresses of module-level writable globals (`sys.global_addr @__data_*`):
	// a managed `store_indirect` through one of these is an ownership TRANSFER
	// into the long-lived global (its last-use decref is suppressed; see
	// `storeTargetsModuleGlobal`).
	let globalAddrValues = collectModuleGlobalAddrs(func, module: module)

	// Results of TRANSPARENT-WRAPPER calls (`Array.init`/`Vector.init` — a builtin
	// literal constructor whose body is `return Self{managed: arg}`, a no-alloc
	// reinterpret that ALIASES its managed argument). The result carries the SAME
	// heap object — and the SAME single +1 — as the wrapped argument, so it must be
	// treated as already-owning that +1 (no store-incref at a global transfer; see
	// `planManagedHeapStore`). See `collectTransparentWrapResults`.
	let transparentWrapResults = collectTransparentWrapResults(func, module: module, funcReturnsConsumedArg: funcReturnsConsumedArg)

	// Results of BORROW-RETURNING calls (`funcReturnsBorrow` — a callee whose return
	// is an interior borrow of a parameter, owning NO transferable +1: the element
	// loaders, `Array.get`/`Map.get`, and identity-passthroughs like
	// `FilePath.normalizeSeparators`/`resolveFileURL` that `return param` unchanged).
	// The lowering default classifies a direct-call result `callReturnRc1` (assumes a
	// transferred +1) — a LIE for these. `reclassifyBorrowReturnResults` repairs the
	// container-consumed and forwarded-through-wrapper uses, but DELIBERATELY leaves a
	// borrow result stored into a plain struct FIELD untouched (reclassifying broadly
	// regressed closure-env captures). So at a field-store transfer the value still
	// reads `callReturnRc1` and `transferValueAlreadyOwnsPlusOne` would wrongly skip
	// the store-incref → the field aliases a borrow with no +1 → freed when the source
	// drops (the `let path = FilePath from "x"` global UAF). This per-value set lets
	// the field-store transfer recognize a no-+1 borrow result and supply the incref,
	// WITHOUT the broad reclassification (closure captures are not borrow-call results,
	// so they are unaffected).
	let borrowReturningCallResults = collectBorrowReturningCallResults(func, module: module, funcReturnsBorrow: funcReturnsBorrow)

	// Implicit `__layout` descriptor ValueId for `sys.dropTypeParam`. Resolved
	// only when the function actually has a type-parameter value that will be
	// RELEASED (a non-returned type-param value) — see `resolveLayoutValueId` for
	// why the layout param op may be absent post-DCE and must sometimes be
	// re-materialized. `idRef` is passed so the re-materialized layout
	// `func.param` can mint a fresh id. Functions with no droppable type-param
	// value skip this (avoids re-adding a dead param op).
	var layoutValueId = RELEASE_NO_LAYOUT
	if func.hasImplicitLayoutParam and funcHasDroppableTypeParam(func, returnedValues: returnedValues) 'hasLayout'
		layoutValueId = resolveLayoutValueId(func, module: module, entryBlock: entryBlock, idRef: idRef)
	end 'hasLayout'

	// Slots whose address was captured into a closure env (`sys.stack_addr`). mem2reg
	// pinned them in memory; a managed value stored into one is owned by the SLOT (the
	// closure borrows it by reference) and released at scope exit, not at the SSA store.
	let addressTakenSlots = collectAddressTakenSlots(func, module: module)

	var ctx = RcContext.create(func, module: module, cfg: cfg, rpo: rpo, domInfo: domInfo, liveness: liveness, idRef: idRef, paramValues: paramValues, returnedValues: returnedValues, globalAddrValues: globalAddrValues, transparentWrapResults: transparentWrapResults, borrowReturningCallResults: borrowReturningCallResults, addressTakenSlots: addressTakenSlots, entryBlockId: entryBlockId, numBlocks: numBlocks, layoutValueId: layoutValueId, includeManaged: includeManaged, mmTrace: mmTrace, funcParamConsumes: funcParamConsumes, funcReturnsConsumedArg: funcReturnsConsumedArg)

	// Per-value acquire analysis for `incomingOwner` values (the conditional rule;
	// see `computeIncomingOwnerAcquire`). Must run BEFORE the acquire/release/phi
	// sweeps, which all consult `ctx.incomingOwnerAcquiresCached` so the +1, the
	// last-use decref, and the phi-edge reconciliation agree per value. Managed
	// domain only — type-param-only stdlib mode never increfs.
	if ctx.includeManaged 'computeAcquire'
		computeIncomingOwnerAcquire(ctx)
	end 'computeAcquire'

	// Order matters only in that all sweeps read the ORIGINAL op positions via
	// per-block planning, then apply edits bottom-up so earlier insertions don't
	// shift later positions. The incref / phi-reconciliation sweeps are MANAGED-
	// domain only (they emit `mm_incref`); the type-param domain never increfs (a
	// generic value is created once and dropped once). They are skipped when the
	// managed domain is off (stdlib type-param-only mode).
	if ctx.includeManaged 'managedIncrefs'
		planAcquireIncrefs(ctx)
		planHeapStoreIncrefs(ctx)
		planReturnIncrefs(ctx)
		planConsumedArgCopyIncrefs(ctx)
	end 'managedIncrefs'
	// Container takes its OWN ref on a BORROWED element moved into it (runs in BOTH
	// domains — a generic container body like `Set.init` is type-param-only). The
	// element is `borrowed` (structurally classified by the return-borrow analysis —
	// an iterator `.current()` view that owns no +1); the container's destructor
	// element-walk will decref it once, so a matching retain must run on store.
	planBorrowedElementContainerRetains(ctx)
	// A WRAPPER forwarding a BORROWED element as its OWN return value (`Map.get`
	// returns `values.get(...)`, the borrow from the leaf `Array.get`) must hand the
	// caller a genuinely-owned +1, not the borrow itself — else the caller (which
	// treats the result as `callReturnRc1`) consumes a +1 the borrow never owned and
	// double-frees once the source collection's teardown frees the element. Retain
	// the borrow before the return so the +1 transfers out cleanly. Runs in BOTH
	// domains: the element type is generic, so the retain is layout-routed.
	planReturnedBorrowRetains(ctx)
	// A TRANSPARENT WRAP (`Array.init`/`String.init`) of a value owning NO +1 must
	// take its own ref: the wrap result's destructor decrefs the wrapped pointer
	// exactly once, but a no-+1 arg (a `borrowed` field load — `String.toByteArray`
	// = `ByteArray.init(managed)` viewing self's inner MM) had nothing to transfer,
	// so the view's teardown stole the source's reference (the Subprocess
	// `buildArgvBlob` exePath inner-MM over-release). Managed domain only — the
	// wrapped value is a concrete managed pointer, incref'd directly.
	if ctx.includeManaged 'wrapRetains'
		planBorrowedWrapRetains(ctx)
	end 'wrapRetains'
	planLastUseDecrefs(ctx)
	planDeadDefDrops(ctx)
	// ADDRESS-TAKEN SLOT scope-exit drops: a managed value stored into a closure-
	// captured (address-taken) slot is owned by the SLOT; its SSA-store release was
	// suppressed (`moveIntoAddressTakenSlot`), so release the slot's content here at
	// each function return — AFTER every closure use in the body. Managed domain only.
	if ctx.includeManaged 'addressTakenDrops'
		planAddressTakenSlotDrops(ctx)
	end 'addressTakenDrops'
	if ctx.includeManaged 'managedPhi'
		// Phi-edge reconciliation reads predecessor terminator args, so it must be
		// planned BEFORE any edge splitting rewrites those terminators.
		planPhiEdgeIncrefs(ctx)
	end 'managedPhi'

	// mm-trace only: queue trace-only `mm_move` markers at ownership-move sites.
	// Pure instrumentation — never affects refcount correctness; gated on mmTrace
	// so untraced builds emit identical IR. Managed domain only (a move transfers a
	// managed +1).
	if ctx.mmTrace and ctx.includeManaged 'moveTraces'
		planMoveTraces(ctx)
	end 'moveTraces'

	applyPlans(ctx)

	// mm-trace only: append the scope-stack pop at each ret AFTER applyPlans so it
	// sits below every release/move at the terminator (the drop reads this frame;
	// the pop then restores the caller's). No-op untraced / non-managed domain.
	if ctx.mmTrace and ctx.includeManaged 'scopePops'
		emitScopePopsAtRets(ctx)
	end 'scopePops'

	// Edge-death decrefs are applied last because they may SPLIT critical edges
	// (adding blocks + rewriting terminators), which must not perturb the
	// position-based body-op plans above.
	applyEdgeReleases(ctx)

	// Per-ordinal layout-bit constants are materialized after EVERYTHING else —
	// both plan-applied and edge-built drop/retain calls reference them, and the
	// edge ones are only built inside `applyEdgeReleases`. See `flushOrdinalConsts`.
	flushOrdinalConsts(ctx)
end 'insertRefcountsInFunction'

// True iff this function has any value that needs a release op in an enabled
// domain:
//   - a managed value (decref) — only when `includeManaged`, and
//   - a generic type-parameter value (dropTypeParam) — always.
// Both are read from the persisted per-ValueId tables (populated by lowering +
// threaded through mem2reg). A function with no enabled-domain work skips the
// whole pass (no CFG/liveness build).
function funcNeedsReleaseInsertion(func IrFunction, includeManaged bool) returns bool
	if includeManaged 'checkManaged'
		var id = 0
		while id < func.valueManaged.count() 'eachManaged'
			if func.isValueManaged(id) 'managed'
				return true
			end 'managed'
			id = id + 1
		end 'eachManaged'
	end 'checkManaged'

	var tid = 0
	while tid < func.valueTypeParam.count() 'eachTypeParam'
		if func.isValueTypeParam(tid) 'typeParam'
			return true
		end 'typeParam'
		tid = tid + 1
	end 'eachTypeParam'

	return false
end 'funcNeedsReleaseInsertion'

// True iff the function has any type-parameter value that needs a layout-routed
// refcount op — either a RELEASE or a returned-borrow RETAIN.
// Mirrors `releaseKindAtLastUse`'s type-param domain: a type-param value is
// released unless RETURNED (the +1 transfers to the caller). Type-param params ARE
// released (the callee owns its generic-typed params — see the `releaseKindAtLastUse`
// note), so they count here. The ONE returned-type-param case that still needs the
// layout is a `borrowed` returned value (`Array.get`/`Map.get`'s element-get
// result): `planReturnedBorrowRetains` retains it via `__mm_retain_type_param`, so
// the layout must be available even though the value is returned, not released.
// Gates layout-param resolution / re-materialization so functions with no
// type-param cleanup don't gain a re-added dead layout `func.param`.
export function funcHasDroppableTypeParam(func IrFunction, returnedValues BoolArray) returns bool
	var id = 0
	while id < func.valueTypeParam.count() 'each'
		if func.isValueTypeParam(id) 'typeParam'
			let isReturned = try returnedValues.get(id) otherwise false
			if not isReturned 'droppable'
				return true
			end 'droppable'
			if returnedBorrowNeedsRetain(func, id: id) 'returnedBorrow'
				return true
			end 'returnedBorrow'
		end 'typeParam'
		id = id + 1
	end 'each'
	return false
end 'funcHasDroppableTypeParam'

// True iff type-param value `id` is a RETURNED `borrowed` value — a
// borrow-returning call result the return-borrow analysis marked `borrowed`
// because the enclosing function forwards it as its own return value. Such a value
// owns no +1 and must be retained before it is handed to the caller (see
// `planReturnedBorrowRetains`).
function returnedBorrowNeedsRetain(func IrFunction, id ValueId) returns bool
	return ownershipClassIsBorrowed(func.ownershipOfValue(id))
end 'returnedBorrowNeedsRetain'

// True iff an `OwnershipClass` is `borrowed` — the pure class test shared by the
// pre-context (`returnedBorrowNeedsRetain`, off `IrFunction`) and in-context
// (`classIsBorrowed`, off `RcContext`) borrow checks so the 6-arm enum match lives
// in one place.
function ownershipClassIsBorrowed(cls OwnershipClass) returns bool
	return match cls 'class'
		borrowed gives true
		freshRc0 gives false
		callReturnRc1 gives false
		selfReturnBorrow gives false
		incomingOwner gives false
		notManaged gives false
	end 'class'
end 'ownershipClassIsBorrowed'

// ============================================================
// Inserter context + insertion planning
// ============================================================

// A single planned body-op insertion: place `opIdx` into `block` at op-list
// position `pos`. `pos` is computed against the block's ORIGINAL op list; all
// plans for a block are applied in descending `pos` order so earlier inserts do
// not shift the indices of later ones.
type RcInsertion
	export var blockRef as BlockRef
	export var pos as NodeIndex
	export var opIdx as OpIndex

	static function create(blockRef BlockRef, pos NodeIndex, opIdx OpIndex) returns RcInsertion
		return Self{blockRef: blockRef, pos: pos, opIdx: opIdx}
	end 'create'
end 'RcInsertion'

typealias RcInsertionArray = Array with RcInsertion

// One planned edge refcount op on the edge fromBlock→toBlock. `isIncref`
// selects incref (phi-edge reconciliation — give a managed phi a clean +1 from
// an edge whose value carries none) vs a release (edge-death). The release form
// derives its exact op (decref / free / dropTypeParam) and null-guarding from
// the value's `ReleaseKind` at emission time via `buildReleaseOp`, so no flavor
// flag is stored here.
type RcEdgeRelease
	export var fromBlockId as BlockId
	export var toBlockId as BlockId
	export var valueId as ValueId
	export var isIncref as bool

	static function release(fromBlockId BlockId, toBlockId BlockId, valueId ValueId) returns RcEdgeRelease
		return Self{fromBlockId: fromBlockId, toBlockId: toBlockId, valueId: valueId, isIncref: false}
	end 'release'

	static function incref(fromBlockId BlockId, toBlockId BlockId, valueId ValueId) returns RcEdgeRelease
		return Self{fromBlockId: fromBlockId, toBlockId: toBlockId, valueId: valueId, isIncref: true}
	end 'incref'
end 'RcEdgeRelease'

typealias RcEdgeReleaseArray = Array with RcEdgeRelease

type RcContext
	export var func as IrFunction
	export var module as StdModule
	// CFG predecessors/successors drive edge-death + critical-edge splitting.
	export var cfg as CfgInfo
	// rpo / domInfo / entryBlockId / numBlocks are computed once and carried so
	// the deferred loop-hoisting pass (Step 9 follow-up) can consume them
	// without re-deriving — per-iteration last-use placement (the shipped path)
	// does not read them.
	export var rpo as RpoInfo
	export var domInfo as DomInfo
	export var liveness as StdLivenessInfo
	export var idRef as ValueIdRef
	export var paramValues as BoolArray
	export var returnedValues as BoolArray
	// ValueIds that are `sys.global_addr @__data_*` results — the addresses of
	// module-level writable globals. A managed `store_indirect` through one of
	// these is an ownership TRANSFER into the long-lived global (see
	// `storeTargetsModuleGlobal`).
	export var globalAddrValues as BoolArray
	// ValueIds that are the result of a TRANSPARENT-WRAPPER call (`Array.init`/
	// `Vector.init`) — a no-alloc reinterpret that ALIASES its managed argument
	// and so already owns that argument's +1. At a module-global transfer the
	// inserter must NOT add a store-incref for these (the +1 is already present);
	// the wrapped argument's own last-use decref is separately suppressed by the
	// MOVE guard (`opMovesValueIntoContainer`). See `collectTransparentWrapResults`.
	export var transparentWrapResults as BoolArray
	// ValueIds that are the result of a BORROW-RETURNING call (the callee's return is
	// an interior borrow of a parameter — `funcReturnsBorrow`). Such a result owns NO
	// transferable +1 despite the lowering default tagging it `callReturnRc1`, so a
	// store into a durable owner (struct field) must supply the owner's +1 (see
	// `transferValueAlreadyOwnsPlusOne`). Distinct from `transparentWrapResults`, which
	// DO carry the wrapped arg's +1. See `collectBorrowReturningCallResults`.
	export var borrowReturningCallResults as BoolArray
	// Slot ids (keyed BoolArray) whose ADDRESS was captured into a closure env (a
	// `sys.stack_addr` op took the slot's address). mem2reg pins these slots in memory
	// (does NOT promote them). A managed value stored into such a slot is owned by the
	// SLOT (the closure borrows it by reference), released at scope exit by
	// `planAddressTakenSlotDrops` — NOT at the SSA store. See `collectAddressTakenSlots`.
	export var addressTakenSlots as BoolArray
	export var entryBlockId as BlockId
	export var numBlocks as BlockId
	// Implicit `__layout` descriptor ValueId for `sys.dropTypeParam` emission;
	// `RELEASE_NO_LAYOUT` for non-generic functions. Single-layout model: a generic
	// function carries exactly one implicit layout slot (find-or-rematerialized up
	// front so a `dropTypeParam` has a LIVE layout operand even when DCE removed the
	// param op — see `resolveLayoutValueId`).
	export var layoutValueId as ValueId
	// When false (stdlib type-param-only mode), the managed `mm_incref`/
	// `mm_decref` domain is suppressed and only `sys.dropTypeParam` is emitted.
	export var includeManaged as bool
	// mm-trace on: emit trace-only `mm_move` markers at ownership-move sites
	// (return / container-or-global-or-field store / phi transfer) so the trace
	// shows where ownership transfers without a refcount op. No-op when false
	// (untraced builds emit no move markers — keeps the IR identical).
	export var mmTrace as bool
	// Per-ValueId acquire decision for `incomingOwner` values (computed once per
	// function by `computeIncomingOwnerAcquire`; see `incomingOwnerAcquiresCached`).
	// `true` ⇒ this loaded-alias value takes a local owning +1 at its def (paired
	// with a last-use decref); `false` ⇒ it is a pure pass-through borrow (net
	// zero, no local incref/decref). Other classes ignore this table. Indexed by
	// ValueId, sized to maxValueId+1; out-of-range / non-`incomingOwner` ⇒ false.
	export var incomingOwnerAcquire as BoolArray
	export var insertions as RcInsertionArray
	export var edgeReleases as RcEdgeReleaseArray
	// CONCEPT C — the structural consume registry computed by `analyzeParamConsumes`:
	// `funcParamConsumes[callee][i]` is true iff `callee` takes ownership of its
	// argument at position `i`. The inserter reads this (`calleeConsumesArg`) instead
	// of the retired callee-name allowlists. Empty in type-param-only mode.
	export var funcParamConsumes as FuncParamConsumesMap
	// CONCEPT C return-side companion: callee names whose RESULT owns the +1 of a
	// consumed arg (a transparent wrapper — `Array.init`/`Vector.init`). Read by
	// `collectTransparentWrapResults`. Empty in type-param-only mode.
	export var funcReturnsConsumedArg as FuncReturnsBorrowSet
	// Entry-block `constI64` ValueIds for per-arg layout-bit ordinals, minted
	// lazily by `ordinalConstId` (indexed by ordinal; `REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE` =
	// not yet minted). One const per ordinal serves every per-ordinal
	// drop/retain call in the function — the entry block dominates all uses.
	export var ordinalConstIds as ValueIdArray

	static function create(func IrFunction, module StdModule, cfg CfgInfo, rpo RpoInfo, domInfo DomInfo, liveness StdLivenessInfo, idRef ValueIdRef, paramValues BoolArray, returnedValues BoolArray, globalAddrValues BoolArray, transparentWrapResults BoolArray, borrowReturningCallResults BoolArray, addressTakenSlots BoolArray, entryBlockId BlockId, numBlocks BlockId, layoutValueId ValueId, includeManaged bool, mmTrace bool, funcParamConsumes FuncParamConsumesMap, funcReturnsConsumedArg FuncReturnsBorrowSet) returns RcContext
		return Self{
			func: func,
			module: module,
			cfg: cfg,
			rpo: rpo,
			domInfo: domInfo,
			liveness: liveness,
			idRef: idRef,
			paramValues: paramValues,
			returnedValues: returnedValues,
			globalAddrValues: globalAddrValues,
			transparentWrapResults: transparentWrapResults,
			borrowReturningCallResults: borrowReturningCallResults,
			addressTakenSlots: addressTakenSlots,
			entryBlockId: entryBlockId,
			numBlocks: numBlocks,
			layoutValueId: layoutValueId,
			includeManaged: includeManaged,
			mmTrace: mmTrace,
			incomingOwnerAcquire: BoolArray.create(),
			insertions: RcInsertionArray.create(),
			edgeReleases: RcEdgeReleaseArray.create(),
			funcParamConsumes: funcParamConsumes,
			funcReturnsConsumedArg: funcReturnsConsumedArg,
			ordinalConstIds: ValueIdArray.create()
		}
	end 'create'

	// The cached acquire decision for an `incomingOwner` value `id`. False for any
	// value not classified `incomingOwner` (other classes do not consult this
	// table) and for out-of-range ids. Populated by `computeIncomingOwnerAcquire`.
	export function incomingOwnerAcquiresCached(id ValueId) returns bool
		return try self.incomingOwnerAcquire.get(id) otherwise false
	end 'incomingOwnerAcquiresCached'

	export function isParam(id ValueId) returns bool
		return try self.paramValues.get(id) otherwise false
	end 'isParam'

	// True iff stack slot `slotId` had its address captured into a closure env (a
	// `sys.stack_addr slot_<slotId>` op). Such slots are mem2reg-pinned in memory; a
	// managed value stored into one is owned by the slot, released at scope exit.
	export function isAddressTakenSlot(slotId VarSlot) returns bool
		return try self.addressTakenSlots.get(slotId) otherwise false
	end 'isAddressTakenSlot'

	export function isReturned(id ValueId) returns bool
		return try self.returnedValues.get(id) otherwise false
	end 'isReturned'

	export function isManaged(id ValueId) returns bool
		return self.func.isValueManaged(id)
	end 'isManaged'

	export function classOf(id ValueId) returns OwnershipClass
		return self.func.ownershipOfValue(id)
	end 'classOf'

	// True iff `id` is a generic type-parameter value (released via
	// `sys.dropTypeParam`). A type-parameter is never `valueManaged`.
	export function isTypeParam(id ValueId) returns bool
		return self.func.isValueTypeParam(id)
	end 'isTypeParam'

	// True iff `id` is the result of a `sys.global_addr @__data_*` — the address
	// of a module-level writable global. A managed `store_indirect` through such
	// an address transfers ownership of the stored value into the long-lived
	// global (see `storeTargetsModuleGlobal`).
	export function isModuleGlobalAddr(id ValueId) returns bool
		return try self.globalAddrValues.get(id) otherwise false
	end 'isModuleGlobalAddr'

	// True iff `id` is the result of a transparent-wrapper call (`Array.init`/
	// `Vector.init`) that aliases its managed argument — the result already owns
	// the wrapped argument's +1 (see `transparentWrapResults`).
	export function isTransparentWrapResult(id ValueId) returns bool
		return try self.transparentWrapResults.get(id) otherwise false
	end 'isTransparentWrapResult'

	// True iff `id` is the result of a BORROW-RETURNING call — the callee's return is
	// an interior borrow of a parameter, so the result owns NO transferable +1 (see
	// `borrowReturningCallResults`). Used to deny the "already owns a +1" shortcut at a
	// durable-owner store so the owner supplies its own +1.
	export function isBorrowReturningCallResult(id ValueId) returns bool
		return try self.borrowReturningCallResults.get(id) otherwise false
	end 'isBorrowReturningCallResult'
end 'RcContext'

// The release op a value's lifetime end requires. The inserter decides WHERE
// (last-use placement); this selects WHICH op:
//   - decref         — a managed refcounted reference (`mm_decref`).
//   - dropTypeParam  — a generic type-parameter local (`sys.dropTypeParam`,
//                      routed through the function's `__layout` descriptor).
//   - none           — the value needs no release (param/borrowed/returned/etc.).
// (There is no `free` kind — see the note in `insertRefcountsInFunction`:
// `sys.globalAddr` is static data, never a heap allocation, so it is never
// freed; real heap is `mrt_alloc`-backed and handled as a managed decref.)
enum ReleaseKind
	none
	decref
	dropTypeParam
	// Owner-drop of a freshRc0 value that NEVER escaped (no acquire was emitted):
	// it lived its whole life at rc=0 as the sole owner, so its last use FREES it
	// directly via `stdlib.__mm_drop` (free at rc==0, else decref). This is the
	// redundant-incref/decref-pair elimination for provably-local allocations —
	// `let b = Box.create(...)` that is read locally and never stored/returned/
	// aliased emits just `__mm_alloc` + `__mm_drop`, not alloc+incref+decref.
	dropManaged
end 'ReleaseKind'

// CONCEPT A — the ONE answer to "does this managed SSA value hold a transferable
// local +1?". A single predicate (`plusOneOwnership`) over
// `(OwnershipClass, isManaged, isParam, incomingOwnerAcquiresCached)` that every
// +1-carrier site reads, replacing the four scattered per-class `match` switches
// (`shouldAcquire`, the `releaseKindAtLastUse` managed tail,
// `edgeValueCarriesPlusOne`, `transferValueAlreadyOwnsPlusOne`).
//
// The 3-state distinction is LOAD-BEARING — conflating it to a boolean regresses
// `callReturnRc1`:
//   - noPlusOne     — notManaged / borrowed / a param / a non-acquiring
//                     `incomingOwner`. No transferable +1. (A non-escaping
//                     `freshRc0` is ALSO noPlusOne — it owns its allocation at
//                     rc=0 but holds no SEPARATE transferable reference; its last
//                     use is a `dropManaged`, see `freshRc0ReleaseKind`.)
//   - acquiredAtDef — `freshRc0` that ESCAPES, `selfReturnBorrow`, or an acquiring
//                     `incomingOwner`. Takes its +1 at the def via `mm_incref`.
//   - arrivesOwning — `callReturnRc1`. Did NOT acquire at its def (it consumed the
//                     call's transferred +1) but DOES carry a transferable +1 at an
//                     edge and DOES decref at last use. "acquires at def" and
//                     "carries a +1 now" agree for every class EXCEPT this one — the
//                     enum keeps them distinct while sharing one class table.
enum PlusOneOwnership
	noPlusOne
	acquiredAtDef
	arrivesOwning
end 'PlusOneOwnership'

// CONCEPT B — the ONE answer to "where does this value's +1 go at its last use?".
// The single decision surface that DEFINES WHAT A MOVE IS, replacing the eight
// scattered move predicates with one enum + one op-keyed dispatcher
// (`opTransferDisposition`). Every consumer of "is this a transfer" funnels through
// it: the last-use decref suppression (`isInBlockDeathPoint`), the
// escape/acquire analysis (`opMovesValueIntoContainer` / `markOpTransferredOperands`),
// so "what counts as a transfer" is defined exactly once and cannot drift between
// the release sweep and the acquire analysis.
//
// The conservative invariant holds throughout: a MISSED move = double-free
// (catastrophic, not gate-caught); an OVER-suppression = leak (gate-caught,
// recoverable) — so when uncertain, bias toward a move.
//
// Two shapes (`returnTransfer`, `moveIntoPhi`) are NOT op-keyed — they live on a
// value-global returned-set and an edge's block-args — so they are checked at their
// natural sites (`isReturned`, `valueMovedIntoPhi`) but join this vocabulary so
// every reader sees the complete list of ways a +1 leaves local scope. The rest are
// derivable from a single (op, argId): the structural store targets and the
// callee-consume facts.
enum TransferDisposition
	// The +1 stays here → emit the local release (decref / dropTypeParam / dropManaged).
	localRelease
	// → ret / errorReturn (value-global, via `isReturned`). Listed for completeness;
	// recognized at the release sites, not by the op-keyed dispatcher.
	returnTransfer
	// → a successor block-arg phi (edge-keyed, via `valueMovedIntoPhi`). Listed for
	// completeness; recognized at the edge/terminator sites, not by the dispatcher.
	moveIntoPhi
	// → `store_indirect` through a module global (`@__data_*`).
	moveIntoGlobal
	// → a plain `store_indirect` into a NON-global heap struct field. The field
	// becomes owner-of-record (released by the container destructor). The acquire
	// analysis treats this as a transfer unconditionally; the release suppression
	// applies it ONLY when the store is the value's last use (the field-transfer
	// gate in `isInBlockDeathPoint` / `planManagedHeapStore`).
	moveIntoHeapField
	// → a generic container MUTATOR parameter that CONSUMES the element (a
	// type-parameter param at a non-self position — `Array.push`/`Map.set`/...).
	moveIntoContainerArg
	// → a runtime helper that re-homes the value into a container WITHOUT increfing
	// (`mrt_managed_list_*_value`, `__managed_mem_set` — the moved value is the last arg).
	moveIntoIntrinsicConsumer
	// → the wrapped argument (arg 0) of a TRANSPARENT-WRAPPER call (`Array.init`/
	// `Vector.init`) whose result aliases it.
	moveIntoTransparentWrap
	// → any store/box/call of a TYPE-PARAMETER value (conservative — the inserter
	// never increfs a type-param value, so any hand-off is a move).
	moveIntoTypeParamSink
	// → a `storeSlot` into an ADDRESS-TAKEN stack slot (a closure-captured variable's
	// slot, pinned in memory by mem2reg because a `stackAddr` took its address into a
	// closure env). The SLOT becomes owner-of-record: a managed value stored there
	// must NOT be dropped at the SSA store (the closure reads it BY REFERENCE through
	// the env, after this store), so the local release is suppressed and the value's
	// `+1` is released instead by `planAddressTakenSlotDrops` at the function's
	// scope-exit (after every closure use). Without this the captured `Box` is freed at
	// the store → the closure dereferences freed memory.
	moveIntoAddressTakenSlot
end 'TransferDisposition'

// Queue a body-op insertion at `pos` in `blockRef`'s op list.
function queueInsertion(ctx RcContext, blockRef BlockRef, pos NodeIndex, opIdx OpIndex)
	ctx.insertions.push(RcInsertion.create(blockRef, pos: pos, opIdx: opIdx))
end 'queueInsertion'

// ============================================================
// Param / returned-value collection
// ============================================================

// Collect (into a BoolArray keyed by ValueId) the result ids of `func.param`
// ops in the entry block. These are the callee's parameters — the caller owns
// their +1, so the inserter never acquires or releases them locally.
function collectParamValues(module StdModule, entryBlock IrBlock) returns BoolArray
	var params = BoolArray.create()
	for opIdx in entryBlock.opRefs 'eachOp'
		let op = try module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("collectParamValues: opIdx not in module.ops")
		match op 'dispatch'
			call(c) then markIfParamOp(c, params: params)
			arith then break 'dispatch'
			control then break 'dispatch'
			memory then break 'dispatch'
			system then break 'dispatch'
		end 'dispatch'
	end 'eachOp'
	return params
end 'collectParamValues'

function markIfParamOp(c StdCallOp, params BoolArray)
	match c 'check'
		param(resultId, _, _) then setBoolAt(params, id: resultId, value: true)
		ret to tailCall then break 'check'
		errorReturn then break 'check'
	end 'check'
end 'markIfParamOp'

// Find the post-mem2reg ValueId of the entry-block `func.param` op whose ABI
// index is `abiIndex`. Used to resolve the implicit `__layout` param's actual
// SSA ValueId (mem2reg re-mints param value ids, so the ABI index alone is not
// a usable ValueId — see the layout-derivation note in
// `insertRefcountsInFunction`). Panics if no such param op exists — a function
// flagged `hasImplicitLayoutParam` must carry a `func.param` for it.
function findParamValueIdByAbiIndex(module StdModule, entryBlock IrBlock, abiIndex VarSlot) returns ValueId
	for opIdx in entryBlock.opRefs 'eachOp'
		let op = try module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("findParamValueIdByAbiIndex: opIdx not in module.ops")
		let hit = matchParamByAbiIndex(op, abiIndex: abiIndex)
		if hit != REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE 'found'
			return hit
		end 'found'
	end 'eachOp'
	return REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
end 'findParamValueIdByAbiIndex'

// Resolve the implicit `__layout` descriptor's post-mem2reg ValueId for a
// generic function. The layout arrives as a calling-convention param; lowering
// emits a `func.param` for it (LowerMaxonToStd ~2805). But that op is DEAD when
// nothing in the body reads the descriptor (index-only generic helpers like
// `Array.swap`), so DCE removes it before the inserter runs — leaving the layout
// register value with no SSA def. We therefore:
//   1. look for a surviving layout `func.param` (the common case — any generic
//      body that does a `.get`/`.set`/dispatch keeps it live); else
//   2. RE-MATERIALIZE one: mint a fresh ValueId and insert a `func.param` at the
//      entry-block head (the layout register is ABI-reserved for the function
//      whether or not the body reads it, so re-adding the param op is sound). A
//      subsequent `sys.dropTypeParam` then has a live layout operand.
// Resolved ONCE per function up front (gated on `funcHasDroppableTypeParam`) and
// cached in `ctx.layoutValueId`, so the entry insert happens at most once and
// before the planning sweeps read the (now-stable) entry op list.
function resolveLayoutValueId(func IrFunction, module StdModule, entryBlock IrBlock, idRef ValueIdRef) returns ValueId
	let abiIndex = implicitLayoutValueIdOf(func)
	let existing = findParamValueIdByAbiIndex(module, entryBlock: entryBlock, abiIndex: abiIndex)
	if existing != REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE 'found'
		return existing
	end 'found'
	// Re-materialize. The fresh value id must not collide with any existing id;
	// `idRef` was seeded past the function's max value id.
	let freshId = allocValueId(idRef)
	let paramIdx = module.ops.count()
	module.ops.push(StdOp.call(StdCallOp.param(freshId, paramIndex: abiIndex, paramType: StdType.i64)))
	try entryBlock.opRefs.insert(0, value: paramIdx) otherwise panic("resolveLayoutValueId: opRefs.insert(0) failed re-materializing layout param for '{func.name}'")
	return freshId
end 'resolveLayoutValueId'

// The result ValueId of `op` iff it is a `func.param` with ABI index `abiIndex`,
// else `REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE`.
function matchParamByAbiIndex(op StdOp, abiIndex VarSlot) returns ValueId
	return match op 'dispatch'
		call(c) gives paramResultIfAbiIndex(c, abiIndex: abiIndex)
		arith gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		control gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		memory gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		system gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
	end 'dispatch'
end 'matchParamByAbiIndex'

function paramResultIfAbiIndex(c StdCallOp, abiIndex VarSlot) returns ValueId
	return match c 'check'
		param(resultId, paramIndex, _) gives(resultId if paramIndex == abiIndex else REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE)
		ret to tailCall gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		errorReturn gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
	end 'check'
end 'paramResultIfAbiIndex'

// Collect the ValueIds that flow into a `ret` / `errorReturn` terminator
// anywhere in the function. Their would-be last-use decref is suppressed (the
// +1 transfers to the caller).
function collectReturnedValues(func IrFunction, module StdModule) returns BoolArray
	var returned = BoolArray.create()
	for blockRef in func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("collectReturnedValues: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		if not block.hasTerminatorOp() 'noTerm'
			continue
		end 'noTerm'
		let term = try module.ops.get(block.terminatorIndex()) otherwise panic("collectReturnedValues: terminator not in module.ops")
		match term 'dispatch'
			call(c) then markIfReturnOp(c, returned: returned)
			arith then break 'dispatch'
			control then break 'dispatch'
			memory then break 'dispatch'
			system then break 'dispatch'
		end 'dispatch'
	end 'eachBlock'
	return returned
end 'collectReturnedValues'

function markIfReturnOp(c StdCallOp, returned BoolArray)
	match c 'check'
		ret(retValId) then setBoolAt(returned, id: retValId, value: true)
		errorReturn(retValId, _) then setBoolAt(returned, id: retValId, value: true)
		call to param then break 'check'
	end 'check'
end 'markIfReturnOp'

function setBoolAt(arr BoolArray, id ValueId, value bool)
	while arr.count() <= id 'grow'
		arr.push(false)
	end 'grow'
	try arr.set(id, value: value) otherwise panic("setBoolAt: set OOB after grow")
end 'setBoolAt'

// ============================================================
// Module-global address collection (ownership-transfer into a long-lived global)
// ============================================================

// The linker-symbol prefix `dataSymbolName` (LowerMaxonToStd) gives a
// module-level writable global: a `let`/`var` declared at module scope, backed
// by a slot in the .data section. A `sys.global_addr @__data_<name>` loads that
// slot's address; a `store_indirect` through it WRITES the global. The backends
// pattern-match the same prefix to pick the data-section relocation (see
// `relocKindForLabel`), so it is the canonical discriminator for a real module
// global vs. an .rdata/.istr/descriptor blob address (which `globalAddr` is also
// used for, but which are never written through).
let MODULE_GLOBAL_DATA_PREFIX = "__data_"

// Collect (into a BoolArray keyed by ValueId) the result ids of every
// `sys.global_addr @__data_*` op — the addresses of module-level writable
// globals. A `store_indirect` through one of these is an ownership TRANSFER of
// the stored managed value into the long-lived global (see
// `storeTargetsModuleGlobal` + the global-store MOVE in `planManagedHeapStore` /
// `opMovesValueIntoContainer`).
function collectModuleGlobalAddrs(func IrFunction, module StdModule) returns BoolArray
	var addrs = BoolArray.create()
	for blockRef in func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("collectModuleGlobalAddrs: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
			let op = try module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("collectModuleGlobalAddrs: opIdx not in module.ops")
			markIfModuleGlobalAddr(op, addrs: addrs)
		end 'eachOp'
	end 'eachBlock'
	return addrs
end 'collectModuleGlobalAddrs'

function markIfModuleGlobalAddr(op StdOp, addrs BoolArray)
	match op 'dispatch'
		system(s) then markIfModuleGlobalAddrSys(s, addrs: addrs)
		arith then break 'dispatch'
		control then break 'dispatch'
		call then break 'dispatch'
		memory then break 'dispatch'
	end 'dispatch'
end 'markIfModuleGlobalAddr'

function markIfModuleGlobalAddrSys(s StdSystemOp, addrs BoolArray)
	match s 'check'
		globalAddr(resultId, name) then markIfDataGlobal(resultId, name: name, addrs: addrs)
		memcpy to loadByte then break 'check'
		osExit to osWrite then break 'check'
		free then break 'check'
		osWriteErr to loadFramePtr then break 'check'
		loadIndirect then break 'check'
		funcAddr then break 'check'
		storeIndirect then break 'check'
		drop then break 'check'
		osAllocPages to osDirMkdir then break 'check'
		atomicInc to osLockRelease then break 'check'
		boxValue to dropTypeParam then break 'check'
	end 'check'
end 'markIfModuleGlobalAddrSys'

function markIfDataGlobal(resultId ValueId, name String, addrs BoolArray)
	if name.startsWith(MODULE_GLOBAL_DATA_PREFIX) 'isDataGlobal'
		setBoolAt(addrs, id: resultId, value: true)
	end 'isDataGlobal'
end 'markIfDataGlobal'

// ============================================================
// Transparent-wrapper call results (alias their managed argument)
// ============================================================

// The TRANSPARENT-WRAPPER constructors: a builtin literal `init` whose body is
// `return Self{managed: arg}` for a single-managed-field wrapper, i.e. a no-alloc
// REINTERPRET of its sole managed argument's pointer as the wrapper type. The
// result is the SAME heap object as the argument and carries the SAME +1 — there
// is no separate allocation and no incref of the argument inside the callee.
//
// This is distinct from a REAL wrapping constructor (`String.init`, which builds
// `String{managed: managed, isAsciiFlag: ...}` — a fresh struct with extra fields
// that takes its OWN +1 on `managed` via the field-store incref): those are NOT
// transparent (the caller's argument decref is still needed to balance the
// callee's field-store incref). Only the no-extra-field, no-alloc reinterprets
// belong here. Kept in sync with the stdlib `BuiltinArrayLiteral` implementors
// (`Array`, `Vector`) whose `init(managed)` is exactly `Self{managed: managed}`.
//
// Two consequences for the caller's refcount accounting (both required to balance
// the K-table-style `g = Array.init(__mm_alloc(...))` global initializer — without
// them the wrapped allocation is decref'd to rc=0 and FREED before the global
// store completes, leaving the global pointing at freed memory → the
// `Sha256.maxon:152` K-table iterator UAF / corrupted hash):
//   - the wrapped ARGUMENT's last-use decref is SUPPRESSED (`opMovesValueIntoContainer`
//     → `callTransparentlyWrapsArg` → the arg-0 `funcParamConsumes` bit): its +1
//     transfers through the call into the result.
//   - the RESULT is treated as already-owning that +1 (`isTransparentWrapResult` →
//     the `funcReturnsConsumedArg` set): a module-global transfer adds NO store-incref
//     for it (the +1 is already there).
// Both facts are now structural (`analyzeParamConsumes`), not a callee-name list:
// `funcReturnsConsumedArg` recognizes exactly the no-extra-field reinterprets
// (`Array.init`/`Vector.init`, where the result IS the param), and crucially NOT a
// real multi-field constructor (`String.init`, whose result is a distinct allocation
// that takes its own field-store incref on `managed`).

// Collect (into a BoolArray keyed by ValueId) the result ids of every
// transparent-wrapper call. The "is this callee a transparent wrapper" fact is the
// structural `funcReturnsConsumedArg` set (computed by `analyzeParamConsumes`); see
// `calleeIsTransparentWrap`.
function collectTransparentWrapResults(func IrFunction, module StdModule, funcReturnsConsumedArg FuncReturnsBorrowSet) returns BoolArray
	var results = BoolArray.create()
	for blockRef in func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("collectTransparentWrapResults: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
			let op = try module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("collectTransparentWrapResults: opIdx not in module.ops")
			markIfTransparentWrapResult(op, results: results, funcReturnsConsumedArg: funcReturnsConsumedArg)
		end 'eachOp'
	end 'eachBlock'
	return results
end 'collectTransparentWrapResults'

function markIfTransparentWrapResult(op StdOp, results BoolArray, funcReturnsConsumedArg FuncReturnsBorrowSet)
	match op 'dispatch'
		call(c) then markIfTransparentWrapCall(c, results: results, funcReturnsConsumedArg: funcReturnsConsumedArg)
		arith then break 'dispatch'
		control then break 'dispatch'
		memory then break 'dispatch'
		system then break 'dispatch'
	end 'dispatch'
end 'markIfTransparentWrapResult'

function markIfTransparentWrapCall(c StdCallOp, results BoolArray, funcReturnsConsumedArg FuncReturnsBorrowSet)
	match c 'check'
		call(resultId, callee, _) then markTransparentWrapIf(resultId, callee: callee, results: results, funcReturnsConsumedArg: funcReturnsConsumedArg)
		tryCall(resultId, callee, _, _) then markTransparentWrapIf(resultId, callee: callee, results: results, funcReturnsConsumedArg: funcReturnsConsumedArg)
		indirectCall to errorReturn then break 'check'
		ret then break 'check'
	end 'check'
end 'markIfTransparentWrapCall'

function markTransparentWrapIf(resultId ValueId, callee String, results BoolArray, funcReturnsConsumedArg FuncReturnsBorrowSet)
	if calleeIsTransparentWrap(callee, funcReturnsConsumedArg: funcReturnsConsumedArg) 'isWrap'
		setBoolAt(results, id: resultId, value: true)
	end 'isWrap'
end 'markTransparentWrapIf'

// CONCEPT C — is `callee` a transparent wrapper (its result owns a consumed arg's
// +1)? Read the structural `funcReturnsConsumedArg` set computed by
// `analyzeParamConsumes` — a callee that RETURNS A CONSUMED PARAMETER DIRECTLY (the
// no-extra-field, no-alloc reinterpret: `Array.init`/`Vector.init`'s
// `return Self{managed: arg}`, where the result IS the param's pointer). It
// deliberately EXCLUDES a real multi-field constructor (`String.init`'s
// `String{managed, isAsciiFlag}`), whose result is a distinct allocation that takes
// its own field-store incref on `managed` — so the caller's arg decref is still
// needed. This replaced the `calleeTransparentlyWrapsArg` 2-entry name list, which
// hard-coded `Array.init`/`Vector.init` by string.
function calleeIsTransparentWrap(callee String, funcReturnsConsumedArg FuncReturnsBorrowSet) returns bool
	return funcReturnsConsumedArg.contains(callee)
end 'calleeIsTransparentWrap'

// Collect (into a BoolArray keyed by ValueId) the result ids of every direct/try
// call to a BORROW-RETURNING callee (`funcReturnsBorrow`, the structural fixpoint
// computed by `analyzeReturnBorrows`). Mirrors `collectTransparentWrapResults` but
// reads the borrow set: such a result owns NO transferable +1 (it is an interior
// borrow of the callee's parameter), so a store into a durable owner must supply
// the owner's +1 (see `transferValueAlreadyOwnsPlusOne`).
function collectBorrowReturningCallResults(func IrFunction, module StdModule, funcReturnsBorrow FuncReturnsBorrowSet) returns BoolArray
	var results = BoolArray.create()
	for blockRef in func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("collectBorrowReturningCallResults: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
			let op = try module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("collectBorrowReturningCallResults: opIdx not in module.ops")
			markIfBorrowReturningResult(op, results: results, funcReturnsBorrow: funcReturnsBorrow)
		end 'eachOp'
	end 'eachBlock'
	return results
end 'collectBorrowReturningCallResults'

function markIfBorrowReturningResult(op StdOp, results BoolArray, funcReturnsBorrow FuncReturnsBorrowSet)
	match op 'dispatch'
		call(c) then markIfBorrowReturningCall(c, results: results, funcReturnsBorrow: funcReturnsBorrow)
		arith then break 'dispatch'
		control then break 'dispatch'
		memory then break 'dispatch'
		system then break 'dispatch'
	end 'dispatch'
end 'markIfBorrowReturningResult'

function markIfBorrowReturningCall(c StdCallOp, results BoolArray, funcReturnsBorrow FuncReturnsBorrowSet)
	match c 'check'
		call(resultId, callee, _) then markBorrowReturningIf(resultId, callee: callee, results: results, funcReturnsBorrow: funcReturnsBorrow)
		tryCall(resultId, callee, _, _) then markBorrowReturningIf(resultId, callee: callee, results: results, funcReturnsBorrow: funcReturnsBorrow)
		indirectCall to errorReturn then break 'check'
		ret then break 'check'
	end 'check'
end 'markIfBorrowReturningCall'

function markBorrowReturningIf(resultId ValueId, callee String, results BoolArray, funcReturnsBorrow FuncReturnsBorrowSet)
	if funcReturnsBorrow.contains(callee) 'isBorrow'
		setBoolAt(results, id: resultId, value: true)
	end 'isBorrow'
end 'markBorrowReturningIf'

// Collect (into a BoolArray keyed by slotId) every stack slot whose ADDRESS was
// captured by a `sys.stack_addr` op — the closure-captured variables' slots (mem2reg
// pins them in memory). A managed value stored into such a slot is owned by the slot
// (the closure reads it by reference) and released at scope exit, not at the SSA store.
function collectAddressTakenSlots(func IrFunction, module StdModule) returns BoolArray
	var slots = BoolArray.create()
	for blockRef in func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("collectAddressTakenSlots: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
			let op = try module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("collectAddressTakenSlots: opIdx not in module.ops")
			markIfStackAddrSlot(op, slots: slots)
		end 'eachOp'
	end 'eachBlock'
	return slots
end 'collectAddressTakenSlots'

function markIfStackAddrSlot(op StdOp, slots BoolArray)
	match op 'dispatch'
		system(s) then markIfStackAddrSysSlot(s, slots: slots)
		arith then break 'dispatch'
		control then break 'dispatch'
		call then break 'dispatch'
		memory then break 'dispatch'
	end 'dispatch'
end 'markIfStackAddrSlot'

function markIfStackAddrSysSlot(s StdSystemOp, slots BoolArray)
	match s 'check'
		globalAddr to memcpy then break 'check'
		stackAddr(_, slotId) then setBoolAt(slots, id: slotId, value: true)
		storeByte to dropTypeParam then break 'check'
	end 'check'
end 'markIfStackAddrSysSlot'

// ============================================================
// Acquire increfs (def-increfs)
// ============================================================

// Emit the acquire-incref for each managed value at its definition point. The
// def is a body op producing the value (its writeId), or a block-arg (a phi,
// handled separately by the edge reconciliation — phis acquire their +1 via the
// MOVE from the incoming edge value, not a def-incref here).
//
// Acquire fires for freshRc0 / incomingOwner / selfReturnBorrow; it is skipped
// for callReturnRc1 (consume the call's +1), borrowed (never owned), and params.
function planAcquireIncrefs(ctx RcContext)
	for blockRef in ctx.func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try ctx.module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("planAcquireIncrefs: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		var pos = 0
		for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
			planAcquireForOp(ctx, blockRef: blockRef, opIdx: opIdx, pos: pos)
			pos = pos + 1
		end 'eachOp'
	end 'eachBlock'
end 'planAcquireIncrefs'

function planAcquireForOp(ctx RcContext, blockRef BlockRef, opIdx OpIndex, pos NodeIndex)
	let op = try ctx.module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("planAcquireForOp: opIdx not in module.ops")
	let operands = extractStdOpOperands(op)
	let defBlock = try ctx.module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("planAcquireForOp: blockRef not in module.blocks")
	for defId in operands.writeIds 'eachDef'
		if shouldAcquire(ctx, id: defId) 'acquire'
			logTrace(LogCategory.ir, message: function() gives "RC-ACQUIRE func={ctx.func.name} val=%{defId} class={ownershipClassName(ctx.classOf(defId))}")
			let incIdx = buildIncrefOp(ctx.module, valueId: defId, idRef: ctx.idRef)
			// A `tryCall` result is NULL on the error edge (the throw ABI zeroes the
			// result register), so its def-acquire must NOT run in the tryCall block
			// (which executes on BOTH edges, before the error-flag branch) — that
			// would `incref(null)` on the throw path. `queueInsertionAtDefPoint` routes
			// it to the SUCCESS-block head (provably non-null) or, for a plain def,
			// immediately after the def op.
			queueInsertionAtDefPoint(ctx, defBlockRef: blockRef, defBlock: defBlock, pos: pos, defId: defId, opIdx: incIdx)
		end 'acquire'
	end 'eachDef'
end 'planAcquireForOp'

// Queue an inserted op (acquire / release / retain) at the SSA-correct point for a
// value DEFINED by the op at `pos` in `defBlockRef`/`defBlock`: at the START of the
// SUCCESS block when `defId` is a `tryCall` result (NULL on the error edge — the
// error-flag condBr's ELSE target is the first point it is provably non-null), else
// immediately after the def op (`pos + 1`), where a plain SSA value exists from that
// point on. The single placement policy shared by `planAcquireForOp` (acquire),
// `planReturnedBorrowRetains` (retain), and `planDeadDefDrops` (release).
function queueInsertionAtDefPoint(ctx RcContext, defBlockRef BlockRef, defBlock IrBlock, pos NodeIndex, defId ValueId, opIdx OpIndex)
	let successBlockId = tryCallResultSuccessBlock(ctx, block: defBlock, resultId: defId)
	if successBlockId != REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE 'tryResult'
		queueInsertion(ctx, blockRef: blockRefForId(ctx, blockId: successBlockId), pos: 0, opIdx: opIdx)
		return
	end 'tryResult'
	queueInsertion(ctx, blockRef: defBlockRef, pos: pos + 1, opIdx: opIdx)
end 'queueInsertionAtDefPoint'

// The BlockRef whose block has `id == blockId`. Panics if no block matches — a
// terminator targeting a non-existent block is a malformed CFG.
function blockRefForId(ctx RcContext, blockId BlockId) returns BlockRef
	for blockRef in ctx.func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try ctx.module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("blockRefForId: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		if block.id == blockId 'hit'
			return blockRef
		end 'hit'
	end 'eachBlock'
	panic("blockRefForId: no block with id {blockId} in func '{ctx.func.name}'")
end 'blockRefForId'

// ============================================================
// Conditional acquire analysis for `incomingOwner` values
// ============================================================
//
// An `incomingOwner` value V is a value LOADED from a slot/field/enum-payload — a
// COPY of a reference its SOURCE already owns. Whether V takes a local owning +1
// at its def is a per-value dataflow decision, NOT a class default (both blanket
// extremes were measured and BOTH regress: blanket-acquire over-acquires
// transient borrow-reads → leaks; blanket-no-acquire under-acquires source-dying
// borrows → UAF). The correct rule:
//
//   V ACQUIRES iff:
//     (a) V GAINS A NEW OWNER — it is RETURNED (`ret`/`errorReturn`: the +1 is
//         handed to the caller), or any of its uses MOVES/CONSUMES it into a
//         durable owner (a heap `store_indirect` of V, or a consuming-move call
//         the inserter would suppress the local decref for — container mutator,
//         transparent wrapper, managed-list inserter, module-global store). In
//         every such case the local last-use decref is suppressed (the +1
//         transfers away), so V MUST own a real +1 or the source's single
//         reference would be double-owned → double-free. OR
//     (b) V's SOURCE does not provably outlive V — the value V was loaded from
//         has its OWN ownership transferred away (it is itself returned, moved,
//         or consumed), so the source's single reference cannot be relied on to
//         keep V's pointee alive through V's uses. V must then hold its own +1.
//   Otherwise (pure pass-through borrow whose source stays live and owned through
//   all of V's uses) V does NOT acquire — net zero, no local incref/decref.
//
// A managed `incomingOwner` BLOCK-ARG (phi) ALWAYS acquires: it is a fresh owned
// value that receives a clean +1 on every incoming edge (via the MOVE from a +1-
// carrying edge or a phi-edge incref for a borrow/null edge), so it must be
// released at its own last use.
//
// The decision is cached per ValueId (`ctx.incomingOwnerAcquire`) and consulted
// by `shouldAcquire`, `releaseKindAtLastUse`, and `edgeValueCarriesPlusOne` so the
// +1, the last-use decref, and the phi reconciliation all agree.
function computeIncomingOwnerAcquire(ctx RcContext)
	let maxVal = ctx.liveness.maxValueId
	var id = 0
	while id <= maxVal 'init'
		ctx.incomingOwnerAcquire.push(false)
		id = id + 1
	end 'init'

	// (a)/(b) shared input: the set of values whose OWNERSHIP is transferred away
	// (returned or moved/consumed into a durable owner). Scanned once over all ops.
	let transferred = collectOwnershipTransferredValues(ctx, maxVal: maxVal)

	// Decide each managed `incomingOwner` body value.
	for blockRef in ctx.func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try ctx.module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("computeIncomingOwnerAcquire: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		markIncomingOwnerBlockArgs(ctx, block: block)
		for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
			let op = try ctx.module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("computeIncomingOwnerAcquire: opIdx not in module.ops")
			let operands = extractStdOpOperands(op)
			for defId in operands.writeIds 'eachDef'
				decideIncomingOwnerAcquire(ctx, id: defId, transferred: transferred)
			end 'eachDef'
		end 'eachOp'
	end 'eachBlock'
end 'computeIncomingOwnerAcquire'

// A managed `incomingOwner` block-arg (phi) always owns a +1 (the merged
// reference). Mark it so its last-use decref fires and it is treated as
// +1-carrying when it in turn feeds a downstream phi.
function markIncomingOwnerBlockArgs(ctx RcContext, block IrBlock)
	var argIdx = 0
	while argIdx < block.blockArgs.count() 'eachArg'
		let arg = try block.blockArgs.get(argIdx) otherwise panic("markIncomingOwnerBlockArgs: blockArgs.get({argIdx}) OOB")
		if ctx.isManaged(arg.valueId) and not ctx.isParam(arg.valueId) 'managed'
			if classIsIncomingOwner(ctx, id: arg.valueId) 'isIncoming'
				setBoolAt(ctx.incomingOwnerAcquire, id: arg.valueId, value: true)
			end 'isIncoming'
		end 'managed'
		argIdx = argIdx + 1
	end 'eachArg'
end 'markIncomingOwnerBlockArgs'

// Decide and cache the acquire bit for a single value `id`, if it is a managed,
// non-param `incomingOwner`. Non-`incomingOwner` ids are left false (other
// classes do not consult the cache).
function decideIncomingOwnerAcquire(ctx RcContext, id ValueId, transferred BoolArray)
	if not classIsIncomingOwner(ctx, id: id) 'notIncoming'
		return
	end 'notIncoming'
	if ctx.isParam(id) 'param'
		return
	end 'param'
	// (a) V's own ownership is transferred away (returned / moved / consumed).
	let selfTransferred = try transferred.get(id) otherwise false
	if selfTransferred 'gainsNewOwner'
		setBoolAt(ctx.incomingOwnerAcquire, id: id, value: true)
		return
	end 'gainsNewOwner'
	// (b) V's SOURCE does not provably outlive V: the value V was loaded from has
	// its own ownership transferred away (returned / moved / consumed), so its
	// single reference cannot keep V's pointee alive. V must own its own +1.
	let sourceRoot = incomingOwnerSourceRoot(ctx, id: id)
	if sourceRoot != REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE and sourceRoot != id 'haveSource'
		let sourceTransferred = try transferred.get(sourceRoot) otherwise false
		if sourceTransferred 'sourceTransferred'
			setBoolAt(ctx.incomingOwnerAcquire, id: id, value: true)
			return
		end 'sourceTransferred'
	end 'haveSource'
	// Pure pass-through borrow whose source stays live and owned — do not acquire.
end 'decideIncomingOwnerAcquire'

// True iff `id` is classified `incomingOwner` AND is a managed value (a
// non-managed loaded value is `notManaged` and never refcounted).
function classIsIncomingOwner(ctx RcContext, id ValueId) returns bool
	if not ctx.isManaged(id) 'notManaged'
		return false
	end 'notManaged'
	return match ctx.classOf(id) 'class'
		incomingOwner gives true
		freshRc0 gives false
		callReturnRc1 gives false
		selfReturnBorrow gives false
		borrowed gives false
		notManaged gives false
	end 'class'
end 'classIsIncomingOwner'

// The interior-borrow SOURCE ROOT of an `incomingOwner` value V: the base value
// V was loaded from, followed transitively up the borrow chain to its root (the
// containing object whose field/slot V copied). `REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE` if V was not
// produced by a tracked pointer-width load (no recorded base). Reuses the
// liveness pass's interior-borrow relation (`borrows`).
function incomingOwnerSourceRoot(ctx RcContext, id ValueId) returns ValueId
	if not ctx.liveness.borrows.isBorrow(id) 'noBase'
		return REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
	end 'noBase'
	return ctx.liveness.borrows.rootOf(id)
end 'incomingOwnerSourceRoot'

// Collect (keyed by ValueId) every value whose OWNERSHIP is transferred away from
// the local scope: it is RETURNED, or its last syntactic use MOVES/CONSUMES it
// into a durable owner. Such a value's +1 leaves the function (or is taken by a
// container), so neither it nor a borrow loaded from it can rely on a retained
// local reference. Scanned once over all ops; the per-value acquire decision then
// reads this set for both V itself (case a) and V's source root (case b).
function collectOwnershipTransferredValues(ctx RcContext, maxVal ValueId) returns BoolArray
	var transferred = BoolArray.create()
	var id = 0
	while id <= maxVal 'init'
		transferred.push(false)
		id = id + 1
	end 'init'

	// Returned values transfer their +1 to the caller.
	var rid = 0
	while rid <= maxVal 'eachReturned'
		let isReturned = try ctx.returnedValues.get(rid) otherwise false
		if isReturned 'isReturned'
			setBoolAt(transferred, id: rid, value: true)
		end 'isReturned'
		rid = rid + 1
	end 'eachReturned'

	// Moved/consumed values: any op that is a consuming move of one of its
	// operands (the same set the inserter suppresses the local decref for).
	for blockRef in ctx.func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try ctx.module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("collectOwnershipTransferredValues: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
			let op = try ctx.module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("collectOwnershipTransferredValues: opIdx not in module.ops")
			markOpTransferredOperands(ctx, op: op, transferred: transferred)
		end 'eachOp'
	end 'eachBlock'

	return transferred
end 'collectOwnershipTransferredValues'

// Mark every operand of `op` that this op MOVES/CONSUMES into a durable owner —
// the acquire-analysis view over the Concept B dispatcher (`opTransferDisposition`).
// Any op-keyed disposition OTHER than `localRelease` is a transfer: the structural
// store reasons (`moveIntoGlobal`/`moveIntoHeapField`/`moveIntoTypeParamSink`)
// subsume the former "plain heap `store_indirect`" check, and the callee-consume
// reasons (`moveIntoContainerArg`/`moveIntoIntrinsicConsumer`/`moveIntoTransparentWrap`)
// are the same callee facts the release sweep reads — so the acquire analysis and
// the release suppression cannot drift (the one-definition-of-move guarantee).
function markOpTransferredOperands(ctx RcContext, op StdOp, transferred BoolArray)
	let operands = extractStdOpOperands(op)
	for argId in operands.readIds 'eachArg'
		if opTransfersOperand(ctx, op: op, argId: argId) 'moved'
			setBoolAt(transferred, id: argId, value: true)
		end 'moved'
	end 'eachArg'
end 'markOpTransferredOperands'

// True iff the Concept B dispatcher reports ANY op-keyed transfer for `argId` at
// `op` — the full transfer set (every move reason, INCLUDING the plain heap-field
// store the narrower `opMovesValueIntoContainer` view excludes).
function opTransfersOperand(ctx RcContext, op StdOp, argId ValueId) returns bool
	return match opTransferDisposition(ctx, op: op, argId: argId) 'disp'
		localRelease gives false
		returnTransfer gives false
		moveIntoPhi gives false
		moveIntoGlobal gives true
		moveIntoHeapField gives true
		moveIntoContainerArg gives true
		moveIntoIntrinsicConsumer gives true
		moveIntoTransparentWrap gives true
		moveIntoTypeParamSink gives true
		moveIntoAddressTakenSlot gives true
	end 'disp'
end 'opTransfersOperand'

// CONCEPT A — the single source of truth for "+1-carrier". Returns the 3-state
// `PlusOneOwnership` for any SSA value; every +1-carrier site is a thin view over
// this (see the enum doc). Reads only the four inputs the design names:
// `(OwnershipClass, isManaged, isParam, incomingOwnerAcquiresCached)`.
//
// A non-managed value, a param (caller owns its +1), and a `borrowed` view all
// hold no transferable +1. A `freshRc0` carries a transferable +1 ONLY when it
// ESCAPES (`valueEscapes` — returned / moved into a container/global/field/phi);
// a provably-local `freshRc0` never acquired one (it lives at rc=0 and frees via
// `dropManaged`), so it is `noPlusOne` here. `selfReturnBorrow` always acquires.
// An `incomingOwner` carries a +1 iff the conditional acquire analysis decided so.
// `callReturnRc1` is the one class that `arrivesOwning` — it consumed the call's
// transferred +1 without a def-acquire.
function plusOneOwnership(ctx RcContext, id ValueId) returns PlusOneOwnership
	if not ctx.isManaged(id) 'notManaged'
		return PlusOneOwnership.noPlusOne
	end 'notManaged'
	if ctx.isParam(id) 'param'
		// A BORROWED param is caller-owned — no transferable local +1 (the caller
		// releases). But a CONSUMED param (Concept C) received the caller's +1 by
		// transfer (the caller's last-use decref was suppressed), so the callee owns
		// that +1. It ARRIVES owning — exactly like `callReturnRc1`: it does NOT acquire
		// at its def (the +1 came in with it, so `shouldAcquire` stays false — no
		// spurious incref at the `param` op) but it DOES carry a transferable +1 at an
		// edge and DOES decref at its last use. The downstream transfer-suppression
		// (`opTransferDisposition` for a forward-to-consumer / field / global / phi /
		// return) suppresses the release wherever the +1 is moved onward; where it is
		// NOT moved (the param's last use is a plain BORROW call, e.g.
		// `FilePath.create`'s `%path` flowing only into the non-consuming
		// `resolveFileURL`), the release fires and frees the param's owned reference
		// (otherwise a 1-per-call leak — the `Process.executablePath`/`FilePath` leak).
		return (PlusOneOwnership.arrivesOwning if valueIsConsumedParamOfCurrentFunc(ctx, valueId: id) else PlusOneOwnership.noPlusOne)
	end 'param'
	return match ctx.classOf(id) 'class'
		freshRc0 gives(PlusOneOwnership.acquiredAtDef if freshRc0NeedsAcquire(ctx, id: id) else PlusOneOwnership.noPlusOne)
		incomingOwner gives(PlusOneOwnership.acquiredAtDef if ctx.incomingOwnerAcquiresCached(id) else PlusOneOwnership.noPlusOne)
		selfReturnBorrow gives PlusOneOwnership.acquiredAtDef
		callReturnRc1 gives PlusOneOwnership.arrivesOwning
		borrowed gives PlusOneOwnership.noPlusOne
		notManaged gives PlusOneOwnership.noPlusOne
	end 'class'
end 'plusOneOwnership'

// View over Concept A: a value takes a local owning +1 at its DEFINITION (an
// `mm_incref` at the def) iff it is `acquiredAtDef`. `callReturnRc1`
// (`arrivesOwning`) does NOT acquire at its def — it consumed the call's +1 — so
// it is excluded here, the load-bearing distinction the 3-state enum preserves.
function shouldAcquire(ctx RcContext, id ValueId) returns bool
	return match plusOneOwnership(ctx, id: id) 'p1'
		acquiredAtDef gives true
		arrivesOwning gives false
		noPlusOne gives false
	end 'p1'
end 'shouldAcquire'

// Redundant-pair elimination: a freshRc0 value needs the +1 acquire ONLY if it
// ESCAPES its single local owner (returned/thrown, moved into a container/global/
// field, or moved into a phi). A provably-LOCAL allocation — read in place and
// never shared — lives at rc=0 and is freed by a `dropManaged` (free-at-rc-0) at
// last use, so emitting acquire+decref would be a redundant pair. Conservative:
// when `valueEscapes` cannot prove locality it returns true → acquire (the safe,
// pre-optimization behavior). The regression ladder + ownership/struct/set/vector
// suites guard against a missed escape edge (it would surface as a leak or UAF).
function freshRc0NeedsAcquire(ctx RcContext, id ValueId) returns bool
	return valueEscapes(ctx, id: id)
end 'freshRc0NeedsAcquire'

// True iff the managed value `id` escapes its def-local single-owner lifetime:
//   - returned/thrown (its +1 transfers to the caller),
//   - moved into a heap container / module global / struct field (the container
//     becomes owner-of-record), or
//   - moved into a releasable phi (the +1 flows into the merged block-arg).
// Scans every op that READS `id` and every block for a phi-move. Returns true
// (escapes → must acquire) on any unrecognized escape so the optimization only
// fires for provably-local values.
function valueEscapes(ctx RcContext, id ValueId) returns bool
	if ctx.isReturned(id) 'returned'
		return true
	end 'returned'
	for blockRef in ctx.func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try ctx.module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise continue
		// Body ops: any op-keyed transfer of `id` (Concept B) escapes it — a move into
		// a container / global / type-param sink, OR a plain `store_indirect` into a
		// non-global heap field. The field store is an escape REGARDLESS of liveness
		// (an escape need not be the LAST use — `s.f = x; ...use(x)...` still escaped):
		// the field holds `id`, so a `freshRc0` whose only escape is a field store must
		// ACQUIRE its +1 at def so the field-transfer branch can suppress the
		// store-incref and the field carries the acquired +1; without the acquire the
		// value arrives rc=0, the transfer suppresses the store-incref → field owns
		// rc=0 → UAF. `opTransfersOperand` is the SAME full transfer set the acquire
		// analysis (`markOpTransferredOperands`) reads, so escape and acquire agree.
		for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
			let op = try ctx.module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise continue
			if opTransfersOperand(ctx, op: op, argId: id) 'transferred'
				return true
			end 'transferred'
		end 'eachOp'
		// Terminator: a move of `id` into a successor's phi transfers its +1.
		if block.hasTerminatorOp() 'hasTerm'
			if valueMovedIntoAnyPhi(ctx, block: block, vid: id) 'phiMove'
				return true
			end 'phiMove'
		end 'hasTerm'
	end 'eachBlock'
	return false
end 'valueEscapes'

// ============================================================
// Heap-store increfs (container takes a ref — balanced by its destructor)
// + decref-of-the-OLD-value on an OVERWRITING store
// ============================================================

// For each `store_indirect` that stores a MANAGED value into a heap container
// field, two refcount adjustments may apply:
//
//   (1) INCREF-NEW (always): the container takes its own reference to the
//       stored value, balanced by the container's destructor (Step 2), NOT by
//       any local decref. Emitted BEFORE the store.
//
//   (2) DECREF-OLD (only on a provable OVERWRITE): if the field already held a
//       managed reference, that old reference's rc must drop or it leaks (the
//       copy-on-write / `String.append`-swaps-buffer pattern dense in stdlib).
//       Reconstructs the C# golden's field-store protocol — load-old, decref-old
//       — but ONLY when the store is proven to overwrite an already-initialized
//       field (see `storeIsFieldOverwrite`). The ordering with the incref-new is
//       SELF-ASSIGN-SAFE: load-old, incref-new, store-new, decref-old — for a
//       `x.f = x.f` the incref bumps rc before the decref drops it, so rc stays
//       > 0 throughout.
//
// WHY decref-old must be GATED to overwrites (the garbage-decref safety
// argument): `__mm_alloc` does NOT zero the user payload — only the 32-byte
// header. So on an INITIAL store into a freshly-allocated struct/container, the
// field slot holds reused SLAB GARBAGE, not null. Loading + decreffing that
// "old" value would decref a garbage pointer → CRASH. The discriminator
// therefore emits decref-old ONLY when a prior dominating `load_indirect` of the
// SAME field proves the field was read — and in well-formed Maxon a managed
// field cannot be read before it is initialized (the field-init checker), so a
// prior read proves a real value (or null, handled by the null-guard). A FALSE
// positive here is a crash; a false negative is only a (Step-9-catchable) leak.
// We therefore require the dominating-prior-load proof and bias toward NOT
// decreffing when uncertain.
function planHeapStoreIncrefs(ctx RcContext)
	for blockRef in ctx.func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try ctx.module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("planHeapStoreIncrefs: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		// Per-op-position liveness for the block: a module-global store is an
		// ownership MOVE (no incref) only when the stored value is DEAD after the
		// store; if the value lives past the store, the global needs its own +1
		// (incref-for-store), so the global-store skip must consult liveness.
		let liveAfter = computeBlockLiveAfter(ctx.module, block: block, liveness: ctx.liveness)
		var pos = 0
		for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
			planHeapStoreForOp(ctx, blockRef: blockRef, block: block, liveAfter: liveAfter, opIdx: opIdx, pos: pos)
			pos = pos + 1
		end 'eachOp'
	end 'eachBlock'
end 'planHeapStoreIncrefs'

function planHeapStoreForOp(ctx RcContext, blockRef BlockRef, block IrBlock, liveAfter StdLiveAfter, opIdx OpIndex, pos NodeIndex)
	let op = try ctx.module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("planHeapStoreForOp: opIdx not in module.ops")
	match op 'dispatch'
		system(s) then planHeapStoreForSys(ctx, blockRef: blockRef, block: block, liveAfter: liveAfter, s: s, pos: pos)
		arith then break 'dispatch'
		control then break 'dispatch'
		call then break 'dispatch'
		memory then break 'dispatch'
	end 'dispatch'
end 'planHeapStoreForOp'

function planHeapStoreForSys(ctx RcContext, blockRef BlockRef, block IrBlock, liveAfter StdLiveAfter, s StdSystemOp, pos NodeIndex)
	match s 'check'
		storeIndirect(addrId, offset, valueId, _, _) then planManagedHeapStore(ctx, blockRef: blockRef, block: block, liveAfter: liveAfter, addrId: addrId, offset: offset, valueId: valueId, pos: pos)
		globalAddr to loadByte then break 'check'
		osExit to osWrite then break 'check'
		free then break 'check'
		osWriteErr to loadFramePtr then break 'check'
		loadIndirect then break 'check'
		funcAddr then break 'check'
		drop then break 'check'
		osAllocPages to osDirMkdir then break 'check'
		atomicInc to osLockRelease then break 'check'
		boxValue to dropTypeParam then break 'check'
	end 'check'
end 'planHeapStoreForSys'

function planManagedHeapStore(ctx RcContext, blockRef BlockRef, block IrBlock, liveAfter StdLiveAfter, addrId ValueId, offset MachineWord, valueId ValueId, pos NodeIndex)
	if not ctx.isManaged(valueId) 'notManaged'
		return
	end 'notManaged'

	// MODULE-GLOBAL STORE that is the value's LAST USE = ownership TRANSFER into a
	// long-lived global. The global becomes the value's owner-of-record and must
	// hold EXACTLY one reference when the initializer finishes. That reference is
	// released at program exit by `patchMrtStartGlobalCleanup` (the self-hosted
	// `__maxon_global_cleanup`: a null-guarded decref of every managed module-global's
	// `@__data_*` slot, inserted into `mrt_start` before `osExit`), so the final
	// occupant is freed exactly once — never a 1-per-global leak, never a UAF.
	//
	// The net +1 the global must own is split between the def-acquire and this
	// store, exactly as `shouldAcquire` partitions the classes (alloc inits to
	// rc=0 — Step 2 — so every +1 is supplied by the inserter):
	//   - ACQUIRED classes (freshRc0 / incomingOwner / selfReturnBorrow): the
	//     def-acquire already gave the value its +1, which TRANSFERS into the
	//     global by the store — NO store-incref here.
	//   - NON-ACQUIRED classes (callReturnRc1 / borrowed): no def-acquire ran and
	//     the value arrives at rc=0 (callReturnRc1's "transferred +1" is rc=0 under
	//     alloc-at-0; a borrowed view is owned by its collection), so the global
	//     must SUPPLY its own +1 — emit the store-incref.
	// In BOTH cases the value's last-use decref is SUPPRESSED (the +1 stays in the
	// global — see `opStoresValueIntoModuleGlobal`), so the global ends at rc=1.
	//
	// DECREF-OLD on a global store releases the previous occupant of the slot so a
	// REASSIGNMENT (`g = newValue`) does not leak the displaced value. Unlike a
	// heap field (whose freshly-`mm_alloc`'d backing holds uninitialized slab
	// garbage on the FIRST store — see the garbage-decref hazard below), a module
	// global's `.data` slot is ZERO-INITIALIZED (every top-level var/let is
	// registered with `initialValue: 0` — Parser `finalizeTopLevelInitDecl`), so
	// the slot is provably NULL until the initializer's first store. The decref-old
	// is therefore emitted UNCONDITIONALLY (not gated on a dominating prior load),
	// null-guarded: on the initial store it loads null and no-ops; on a reassign it
	// loads the prior occupant and releases it. This reconstructs the C# golden's
	// global-store protocol (load-old / decref-old) without `__maxon_global_cleanup`.
	//
	// If the stored value is STILL LIVE after the store (`g = x; ...use(x)`), it
	// is NOT a transfer: the global takes its OWN +1 (the normal heap-store
	// incref-new below) and the local keeps its reference, released at its real
	// last use. The liveness check separates the two cases.
	if storeTargetsModuleGlobal(ctx, addrId: addrId) and not liveAfter.isLiveAfterBodyOp(pos, vid: valueId) 'globalTransfer'
		if not transferValueAlreadyOwnsPlusOne(ctx, valueId: valueId) 'needsStoreIncref'
			let gIncIdx = buildIncrefOp(ctx.module, valueId: valueId, idRef: ctx.idRef)
			queueInsertion(ctx, blockRef: blockRef, pos: pos, opIdx: gIncIdx)
		end 'needsStoreIncref'
		planDecrefOldField(ctx, blockRef: blockRef, addrId: addrId, offset: offset, pos: pos)
		return
	end 'globalTransfer'

	// NON-GLOBAL HEAP-FIELD TRANSFER — a managed value whose LAST USE is this store
	// into a (non-global, non-param) heap struct field MOVES its reference into the
	// field. The field becomes owner-of-record, released by the container's
	// destructor at rc→0 (`synthesizeOneStructDestructor` decref's each managed
	// field exactly once). This mirrors the `globalTransfer` branch: a value that
	// already OWNS a transferable +1 (`transferValueAlreadyOwnsPlusOne`) transfers it
	// WITHOUT a store-incref; a no-+1 value (a `borrowed` view) gets one. In BOTH
	// cases the value's last-use decref is SUPPRESSED (`isInBlockDeathPoint` via
	// `opStoresValueIntoNonGlobalHeapField`), so the +1 stays in the field.
	//
	// Without this, a value that arrives WITHOUT a separate local +1 — a
	// `callReturnRc1` (`Array.create()`, rc=1 arrival) or a `freshRc0` whose only
	// escape is this store — got the always-on store-incref (rc 0→1) AND its last-use
	// decref (rc 1→0) → FREED, leaving the field dangling (the Set/Map `init`
	// over-free: `Self{elements: elems, states: sts, ...}` then `insert` faults on a
	// freed `states`). The `incomingOwner` class was already correct (its acquire
	// analysis treats a field store as a transfer via `markOpTransferredOperands`);
	// this branch closes the same gap for the rc=0-arriving classes.
	//
	// DECREF-OLD stays gated on `storeIsFieldOverwrite` (NOT unconditional like the
	// global branch): a heap field's freshly-`mm_alloc`'d backing is slab garbage on
	// the FIRST store, so only a PROVABLE reassign (dominating prior load) releases a
	// real prior occupant; an init store leaves the garbage alone.
	if storeIsManagedFieldTransfer(ctx, liveAfter: liveAfter, addrId: addrId, valueId: valueId, pos: pos) 'fieldTransfer'
		logTrace(LogCategory.ir, message: function() gives "RC-FIELD-TRANSFER func={ctx.func.name} val=%{valueId} addr=%{addrId} class={ownershipClassName(ctx.classOf(valueId))} ownsPlusOne={transferValueAlreadyOwnsPlusOne(ctx, valueId: valueId)}")
		if not transferValueAlreadyOwnsPlusOne(ctx, valueId: valueId) 'fieldNeedsStoreIncref'
			let fIncIdx = buildIncrefOp(ctx.module, valueId: valueId, idRef: ctx.idRef)
			// A field store CAN be a `tryCall` result (`Self{managed: arr.slice(...)}`):
			// route the incref to the success block so the throw path never increfs null.
			let fSuccessBlockId = tryCallResultSuccessBlock(ctx, block: block, resultId: valueId)
			if fSuccessBlockId != REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE 'fTryStore'
				queueInsertion(ctx, blockRef: blockRefForId(ctx, blockId: fSuccessBlockId), pos: 0, opIdx: fIncIdx)
			end 'fTryStore'
			if fSuccessBlockId == REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE 'fNormalStore'
				queueInsertion(ctx, blockRef: blockRef, pos: pos, opIdx: fIncIdx)
			end 'fNormalStore'
		end 'fieldNeedsStoreIncref'
		if storeIsFieldOverwrite(ctx, storeBlock: block, addrId: addrId, offset: offset, storePos: pos) 'fieldOverwrite'
			planDecrefOldField(ctx, blockRef: blockRef, addrId: addrId, offset: offset, pos: pos)
		end 'fieldOverwrite'
		return
	end 'fieldTransfer'

	// (1) INCREF-NEW — the container takes a ref to the stored value regardless
	// of the value's own class (even a borrowed view, once stored, is owned by
	// the container and dropped by the container destructor). Incref BEFORE the
	// store so the ordering is incref-new / store-new (a self-store keeps
	// rc > 0 throughout).
	logTrace(LogCategory.ir, message: function() gives "RC-STORE-INCREF func={ctx.func.name} val=%{valueId} addr=%{addrId} off={offset} class={ownershipClassName(ctx.classOf(valueId))}")
	let incIdx = buildIncrefOp(ctx.module, valueId: valueId, idRef: ctx.idRef)
	// A `tryCall` result stored into a wrapper in the SAME block as the tryCall is
	// NULL on the error edge (the throw ABI zeroed it). The incref-new must run on
	// the SUCCESS edge only — placing it before the error-flag branch would
	// `incref(null)` on the throw path (the `arr.slice(...) otherwise ...` fault,
	// where `Array.slice` heap-stores its inner slice-MM tryCall result into the
	// returned wrapper). Route to the start of the success block; the store itself
	// writes null harmlessly on the error path (the wrapper is discarded there).
	let storeSuccessBlockId = tryCallResultSuccessBlock(ctx, block: block, resultId: valueId)
	if storeSuccessBlockId != REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE 'tryStore'
		queueInsertion(ctx, blockRef: blockRefForId(ctx, blockId: storeSuccessBlockId), pos: 0, opIdx: incIdx)
	end 'tryStore'
	if storeSuccessBlockId == REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE 'normalStore'
		queueInsertion(ctx, blockRef: blockRef, pos: pos, opIdx: incIdx)
	end 'normalStore'

	// (2) DECREF-OLD — only on a PROVABLE overwrite of an already-initialized
	// managed field. The discriminator (`storeIsFieldOverwrite`) requires a
	// dominating prior `load_indirect` of the SAME (addrId, offset), which proves
	// the field held a real value; an initial store (no prior read) is left alone
	// so we never decref slab garbage. See the safety argument above.
	if storeIsFieldOverwrite(ctx, storeBlock: block, addrId: addrId, offset: offset, storePos: pos) 'overwrite'
		planDecrefOldField(ctx, blockRef: blockRef, addrId: addrId, offset: offset, pos: pos)
	end 'overwrite'
end 'planManagedHeapStore'

// True iff the value transferred into a durable owner (a module global OR a
// non-global heap struct field) at this store ALREADY owns the +1 the owner must
// hold, so the transfer needs NO store-incref:
//   - an ACQUIRED class (freshRc0 / incomingOwner-acquiring / selfReturnBorrow) —
//     the def-acquire already gave it a +1 that transfers into the owner; or
//   - a `callReturnRc1` — the CALL handed back a live +1 (rc=1) the value already
//     OWNS without a def-acquire (the 3-state distinction: it `arrivesOwning`, not
//     `acquiredAtDef`). The call's +1 transfers straight into the owner, so NO
//     store-incref. This is exactly the `edgeValueCarriesPlusOne` "carries a +1"
//     predicate — the transfer must use that, NOT the narrower `shouldAcquire`
//     (acquire-at-def), or a `callReturnRc1`-returning builder fed to a global
//     (`var captured = Array.create()` in Log) takes a SECOND +1 on top of the
//     call's → the owner ends at rc=2 → a 1-per-owner leak; or
//   - a TRANSPARENT-WRAPPER result (`Array.init`/`Vector.init`) — it ALIASES its
//     wrapped argument and inherited that argument's def-acquire +1 (the wrapped
//     argument's own last-use decref is suppressed by the MOVE guard, so the +1
//     lives on in the aliasing result). Without this skip the owner would take a
//     SECOND +1 on the K-table object (a 1-per-owner over-retain leak) on top of
//     the inherited one — and, paired with the (now-suppressed) wrapped-arg decref,
//     the historical free-before-store ordering that corrupted the K-table.
// A genuine no-+1 value (a `borrowed` view) still needs the owner to supply its
// own +1. `edgeValueCarriesPlusOne` also excludes params (caller-owned), which a
// global initializer never stores directly (a field store CAN store a param — see
// the field-transfer branch's `not ctx.isParam` gate, which excludes it upstream).
function transferValueAlreadyOwnsPlusOne(ctx RcContext, valueId ValueId) returns bool
	// A BORROW-RETURNING call result owns NO +1 — the value it points at is owned by
	// the callee's parameter (the source collection / the identity-passthrough arg).
	// The lowering default tags it `callReturnRc1` (which `edgeValueCarriesPlusOne`
	// would treat as carrying a +1), but that is a LIE for a borrow result: storing it
	// into a durable owner without an incref leaves the owner aliasing a value whose
	// real +1 is dropped when the source goes away. Deny the shortcut so the durable
	// owner supplies its OWN +1. A transparent-wrapper result is NOT in this set (it
	// genuinely inherits the wrapped arg's +1), so its `isTransparentWrapResult`
	// OR-term below still grants ownership.
	if ctx.isBorrowReturningCallResult(valueId) 'borrowResult'
		return false
	end 'borrowResult'
	// A CONSUMED PARAMETER of the current function carries a transferable +1: the
	// CALLER transferred its reference into this callee (Concept C — the caller's
	// last-use decref is suppressed for a consumed arg). So when the callee stores
	// that param into a durable owner (a `Self{field: param}` / union-payload
	// constructor box), the param's +1 MOVES into the field — NO store-incref. The
	// general `param` arm of `edgeValueCarriesPlusOne` says noPlusOne (caller-owned),
	// which is right for a BORROWED param but WRONG for a consumed one — without this
	// the constructor double-counts: the field-store-incref (rc=2) on top of the
	// caller's moved-in +1, balanced by only ONE destructor decref → a 1-per-box leak
	// (the `Maybe.wrapped(Box)` / `Holder{b: Box}`-via-non-inlined-constructor leak).
	if valueIsConsumedParamOfCurrentFunc(ctx, valueId: valueId) 'consumedParam'
		return true
	end 'consumedParam'
	return edgeValueCarriesPlusOne(ctx, vid: valueId) or ctx.isTransparentWrapResult(valueId)
end 'transferValueAlreadyOwnsPlusOne'

// True iff `valueId` is a PARAMETER of the current function at a position the function
// CONSUMES (per the structural `funcParamConsumes` Concept-C bit). Such a param received
// a transferable +1 from the caller (the consumed-arg move), so a store of it into a
// durable owner is a MOVE of that +1, not a borrow-copy. Resolves the param's ABI index
// from the entry-block `param` op that defines `valueId`.
function valueIsConsumedParamOfCurrentFunc(ctx RcContext, valueId ValueId) returns bool
	if not ctx.isParam(valueId) 'notParam'
		return false
	end 'notParam'
	let abiIndex = paramAbiIndexOfValue(ctx, valueId: valueId)
	if abiIndex < 0 'noIndex'
		return false
	end 'noIndex'
	return paramConsumeBit(ctx.funcParamConsumes, callee: ctx.func.name, argIndex: abiIndex as NodeIndex)
end 'valueIsConsumedParamOfCurrentFunc'

// The ABI parameter index of the entry-block `param` op that defines `valueId`, or -1
// if `valueId` is not a param value. Mem2reg re-mints param value ids, so the index is
// recovered from the `param` op (which carries its ABI index) rather than assumed.
function paramAbiIndexOfValue(ctx RcContext, valueId ValueId) returns ParsedInt
	let entryBlock = try ctx.module.blocks.get(blockRefForId(ctx, blockId: ctx.entryBlockId)) otherwise return (-1)
	for opIdx in entryBlock.opRefs 'eachOp'
		let op = try ctx.module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("paramAbiIndexOfValue: opIdx not in module.ops")
		let idx = paramOpAbiIndexIfDefines(op, valueId: valueId)
		if idx >= 0 'found'
			return idx
		end 'found'
	end 'eachOp'
	return (-1)
end 'paramAbiIndexOfValue'

function paramOpAbiIndexIfDefines(op StdOp, valueId ValueId) returns ParsedInt
	return match op 'dispatch'
		call(c) gives paramCallAbiIndexIfDefines(c, valueId: valueId)
		arith gives(-1)
		control gives(-1)
		memory gives(-1)
		system gives(-1)
	end 'dispatch'
end 'paramOpAbiIndexIfDefines'

function paramCallAbiIndexIfDefines(c StdCallOp, valueId ValueId) returns ParsedInt
	return match c 'check'
		param(resultId, paramIndex, _) gives(paramIndex if resultId == valueId else (-1))
		ret to tailCall gives(-1)
		errorReturn gives(-1)
	end 'check'
end 'paramCallAbiIndexIfDefines'

// True iff a `store_indirect` whose base is `addrId` writes a module-level
// writable global (its base is a `sys.global_addr @__data_*` result). Such a
// store transfers ownership of the stored managed value into the long-lived
// global: the inserter never emits the value's last-use decref (the +1 stays in
// the global), supplies a store-incref only for the non-acquired classes, and
// releases the slot's previous occupant via a null-guarded decref-old. See
// `planManagedHeapStore`'s `globalTransfer` branch for the full accounting.
function storeTargetsModuleGlobal(ctx RcContext, addrId ValueId) returns bool
	return ctx.isModuleGlobalAddr(addrId)
end 'storeTargetsModuleGlobal'

// True iff this `store_indirect` of managed `valueId` into the NON-global heap
// field at `addrId` is the value's LAST USE — i.e. an ownership TRANSFER into the
// field. Mirrors the `globalTransfer` gate (`storeTargetsModuleGlobal and not
// liveAfter.isLiveAfterBodyOp`), restricted to the field case:
//   - `ctx.isManaged(valueId)` — only refcounted values transfer (the caller's
//     early `not ctx.isManaged return` already guarantees this, but the predicate
//     stays total so it is reusable);
//   - `not ctx.isParam(valueId)` — a param is caller-owned, has no local +1 and no
//     last-use decref, so storing it is a COPY (the field takes a fresh +1), never
//     a transfer;
//   - `not storeTargetsModuleGlobal` — a global store is the `globalTransfer`
//     branch's job (handled and `return`ed before this is reached);
//   - `not liveAfter.isLiveAfterBodyOp(pos, valueId)` — the store is the value's
//     LAST use. If the value is STILL LIVE afterward (`s.f = x; ...use(x)`) it is a
//     COPY: the field takes its own +1 and the local keeps its reference.
// Locals are mem2reg-promoted, so a surviving non-global `store_indirect` always
// writes heap memory; no extra heap check on `addrId` is needed.
function storeIsManagedFieldTransfer(ctx RcContext, liveAfter StdLiveAfter, addrId ValueId, valueId ValueId, pos NodeIndex) returns bool
	if not ctx.isManaged(valueId) 'notManaged'
		return false
	end 'notManaged'
	// A BORROWED param is caller-owned (no local +1, no last-use decref), so storing
	// it is a COPY (the field takes a fresh +1) — exclude it from the transfer path.
	// But a CONSUMED param received a transferable +1 from the caller (Concept C), so
	// storing it IS a transfer (its +1 moves into the field, no copy-incref); route it
	// through the transfer branch, where `transferValueAlreadyOwnsPlusOne` recognizes
	// the consumed param as already-owning and SUPPRESSES the store-incref. Without
	// this a `Self{field: param}` / union-payload constructor over a consumed param
	// double-counts (the box leaks — `Maybe.wrapped(Box)`).
	if ctx.isParam(valueId) and not valueIsConsumedParamOfCurrentFunc(ctx, valueId: valueId) 'borrowedParam'
		return false
	end 'borrowedParam'
	if storeTargetsModuleGlobal(ctx, addrId: addrId) 'global'
		return false
	end 'global'
	return not liveAfter.isLiveAfterBodyOp(pos, vid: valueId)
end 'storeIsManagedFieldTransfer'

// Reconstruct the C# field-store protocol's old-value release for a proven
// overwrite: reload the old field value (a pointer-width `load_indirect` of the
// same `[addrId + offset]`) and null-guarded-decref it. The load is planned at
// `pos` (so it lands with the incref-new, BEFORE the store, capturing the old
// pointer before it is clobbered); the decref is planned at `pos + 1` (AFTER the
// store). Combined with the incref-new at `pos`, the applied order is
// load-old, incref-new, store-new, decref-old — self-assign-safe.
//
// The decref is ALWAYS null-guarded (`__mm_decref_maybenull_helper`): a managed field
// may legitimately hold null on some path (a not-yet-assigned-on-this-path
// optional field, a cleared slot), and the null-guard makes that a no-op.
function planDecrefOldField(ctx RcContext, blockRef BlockRef, addrId ValueId, offset MachineWord, pos NodeIndex)
	let loadOld = buildLoadOldFieldOp(ctx.module, addrId: addrId, offset: offset, idRef: ctx.idRef)
	queueInsertion(ctx, blockRef: blockRef, pos: pos, opIdx: loadOld.opIdx)

	logTrace(LogCategory.ir, message: function() gives "RC-DECREF-OLD func={ctx.func.name} addr=%{addrId} off={offset} atpos={pos}")
	let decIdx = buildDecrefOp(ctx.module, valueId: loadOld.resultId, nullGuarded: true, idRef: ctx.idRef)
	queueInsertion(ctx, blockRef: blockRef, pos: pos + 1, opIdx: decIdx)
end 'planDecrefOldField'

// The OVERWRITE discriminator (read-modify-write detection). True iff the field
// at `[addrId + offset]` was PROVABLY initialized before the store at
// `storePos` in `storeBlock` — i.e. there is a `load_indirect` of the SAME
// `addrId` SSA value and the SAME `offset` that DOMINATES this store. Because
// `addrId` is an SSA value (a single immutable definition), "same addrId + same
// offset" denotes the same address with no aliasing blur, so a matching load
// reads exactly the memory this store writes.
//
// Two cases:
//   - WITHIN-BLOCK: a matching load earlier in `storeBlock` (a strictly smaller
//     op position) — it precedes the store on the linear intra-block path, so it
//     trivially dominates. This is the common CoW shape (load field, compute,
//     store field) and is checked first.
//   - CROSS-BLOCK: a matching load in a DIFFERENT block that STRICTLY DOMINATES
//     `storeBlock` (every path from entry to the store passes through that
//     block, so the load executed). Block-level dominance is the conservative,
//     sound proof.
//
// No matching dominating load → fall through to the PARAM-BASE rule below; if that
// also fails, treat as an INITIAL store (incref-new only, NO decref-old) — the bias
// that avoids the garbage-decref crash on a freshly-`mm_alloc`'d struct's first field
// write.
//
// PARAM-BASE rule (the `Map.ensureCapacity` / `Set.insert` reassign-leak fix): a field
// store whose base `addrId` is a `func.param` writes a field of a struct the CALLER
// already constructed — every managed field of a fully-constructed struct is
// initialized (Maxon requires all fields set at construction; a `Self{}` literal
// stores each), so the slot holds a real prior occupant, NEVER slab garbage. The
// dominating-load proof is therefore unnecessary here: `self.keys = KeyArray{}` in a
// method has no prior load of `self.keys`, so the load-based check misses it and the
// old array leaks. The garbage-decref hazard the load-proof guards against is unique
// to the CONSTRUCTION site (a fresh `mm_alloc` result base whose fields are not yet
// written) — and that base is `freshRc0`, never a param. So gating the relaxation on a
// param base is sound: it adds the missing decref-old for genuine reassignments while
// leaving every `Self{}`-construction initial store (fresh-alloc base) untouched. The
// decref stays null-guarded, so a legitimately-null managed field is a no-op. This is
// the move-model-consistent fix — it adds ONLY the one required decref-old, no
// C#-style incref-per-reference.
function storeIsFieldOverwrite(ctx RcContext, storeBlock IrBlock, addrId ValueId, offset MachineWord, storePos NodeIndex) returns bool
	// NEAREST-PRIOR-LOAD scan, BACKWARD from the store: the closest earlier
	// in-block read of `[addrId + offset]` decides.
	//   - a genuine load of the slot → the classic read-modify-write proof.
	//   - a load feeding ONLY `__mm_decref_maybenull_helper` → `lowerFieldStore`
	//     ALREADY released this slot's occupant for this store (its decref-old
	//     sequence is emitted contiguously with the store, so it is always the
	//     nearest slot read); adding a second decref-old would double-free the
	//     prior occupant (the `String.from` over-release).
	//
	// NOTE: the SOURCE-LEVEL managed-field reassign (`c.arguments = args`) is
	// handled by `lowerFieldStore`'s typed decref-old, NOT by a proof here — an
	// inserter-side "prior store / call-returned base proves initialization"
	// rule cannot tell an owning user-struct field from runtime-record plumbing
	// (a `__ManagedMemoryCursor` field holds a raw rdata pointer; decref'ing
	// its "prior occupant" faulted in the image), so slot ownership must be
	// decided where the field's declared type is known.
	var pos = storePos
	while pos > 0 'scanBack'
		pos = pos - 1
		let opIdx = try storeBlock.opRefs.get(pos) otherwise panic("storeIsFieldOverwrite: opRefs.get({pos}) failed despite pos < storePos")
		let op = try ctx.module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("storeIsFieldOverwrite: opIdx not in module.ops")
		let loadResult = fieldLoadResultId(op, addrId: addrId, offset: offset)
		if loadResult != REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE 'priorLoad'
			return not loadFeedsOnlyDecrefOldHelper(ctx, block: storeBlock, loadResultId: loadResult)
		end 'priorLoad'
	end 'scanBack'

	if hasMatchingLoadInDominatingBlock(ctx, storeBlockId: storeBlock.id, addrId: addrId, offset: offset) 'dominating'
		return true
	end 'dominating'

	// INLINED-ARG base: the param-base rule's reasoning survives inlining — a
	// value the inliner bound from a callee PARAM (`valueInlinedArg`, set at the
	// splice) was a fully-constructed struct at the call boundary, so a spliced
	// field store through it is the same reassignment shape as a param-base
	// store (the inlined `Container.setData` field-reassign leak). A fresh
	// `Self{...}` construction base is a body LOCAL of its constructor, never
	// an argument into it, so the garbage-decref hazard stays excluded.
	return ctx.isParam(addrId) or ctx.func.isValueInlinedArg(addrId)
end 'storeIsFieldOverwrite'

// The result ValueId of `op` if it is a `load_indirect` of `[addrId + offset]` (same
// base SSA value and same offset; width/sign/float tags are irrelevant — any read of
// the field address proves the field was initialized), else REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE. Callers
// inspect the loaded value's consumers, e.g. to tell a genuine prior-occupant read from
// a lowering-emitted decref-old sequence (`loadFeedsOnlyDecrefOldHelper`).
function fieldLoadResultId(op StdOp, addrId ValueId, offset MachineWord) returns ValueId
	return match op 'dispatch'
		system(s) gives sysFieldLoadResultId(s, addrId: addrId, offset: offset)
		arith gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		control gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		call gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		memory gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
	end 'dispatch'
end 'fieldLoadResultId'

function sysFieldLoadResultId(s StdSystemOp, addrId ValueId, offset MachineWord) returns ValueId
	return match s 'check'
		loadIndirect(resultId, loadAddrId, loadOffset, _, _, _) gives(resultId if (loadAddrId == addrId and loadOffset == offset) else REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE)
		globalAddr to loadByte gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		osExit to osWrite gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		free gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		osWriteErr to loadFramePtr gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		funcAddr gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		storeIndirect gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		drop gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		osAllocPages to osDirMkdir gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		atomicInc to osLockRelease gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		boxValue to dropTypeParam gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
	end 'check'
end 'sysFieldLoadResultId'

// True iff `loadResultId` is consumed within `block` by a `__mm_decref_maybenull_helper`
// call — the signature of `lowerFieldStore`'s synth-overwrite decref-old sequence
// (load-old → decref-old). Such a load already released its occupant, so it must not
// count as a still-live prior occupant for the inserter's overwrite decision.
function loadFeedsOnlyDecrefOldHelper(ctx RcContext, block IrBlock, loadResultId ValueId) returns bool
	for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
		let op = try ctx.module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("loadFeedsOnlyDecrefOldHelper: opIdx not in module.ops")
		if opIsDecrefOldHelperOf(op, argId: loadResultId) 'isDecref'
			return true
		end 'isDecref'
	end 'eachOp'
	return false
end 'loadFeedsOnlyDecrefOldHelper'

function opIsDecrefOldHelperOf(op StdOp, argId ValueId) returns bool
	return match op 'dispatch'
		call(c) gives callIsDecrefOldHelperOf(c, argId: argId)
		arith gives false
		control gives false
		memory gives false
		system gives false
	end 'dispatch'
end 'opIsDecrefOldHelperOf'

function callIsDecrefOldHelperOf(c StdCallOp, argId ValueId) returns bool
	return match c 'check'
		call(_, callee, argIds) gives(callee == "__mm_decref_maybenull_helper" and valueIdArrayContains(argIds, vid: argId))
		ret gives false
		tryCall to errorReturn gives false
	end 'check'
end 'callIsDecrefOldHelperOf'

// True iff some OTHER block that STRICTLY DOMINATES `storeBlockId` contains a
// `load_indirect` of the same field. The store's own block is excluded here
// (the within-block case is handled positionally by `hasMatchingLoadWithinBlock`
// — a load LATER in the store's block does not dominate the store, so scanning
// the whole block here would be unsound).
function hasMatchingLoadInDominatingBlock(ctx RcContext, storeBlockId BlockId, addrId ValueId, offset MachineWord) returns bool
	for blockRef in ctx.func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try ctx.module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("hasMatchingLoadInDominatingBlock: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		if block.id == storeBlockId 'sameBlock'
			continue
		end 'sameBlock'
		if not dominates(block.id, b: storeBlockId, domInfo: ctx.domInfo) 'notDominator'
			continue
		end 'notDominator'
		if blockHasMatchingLoad(ctx, block: block, addrId: addrId, offset: offset) 'found'
			return true
		end 'found'
	end 'eachBlock'
	return false
end 'hasMatchingLoadInDominatingBlock'

// True iff any body op in `block` is a `load_indirect` of `[addrId + offset]` that is
// a GENUINE prior-occupant read (NOT a lowering-emitted decref-old sequence, which has
// already released its occupant — see `hasMatchingLoadWithinBlock`).
function blockHasMatchingLoad(ctx RcContext, block IrBlock, addrId ValueId, offset MachineWord) returns bool
	for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
		let op = try ctx.module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("blockHasMatchingLoad: opIdx not in module.ops")
		let loadResult = fieldLoadResultId(op, addrId: addrId, offset: offset)
		if loadResult != REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE and not loadFeedsOnlyDecrefOldHelper(ctx, block: block, loadResultId: loadResult) 'match'
			return true
		end 'match'
	end 'eachOp'
	return false
end 'blockHasMatchingLoad'

// ============================================================
// Return increfs (param returned → hand caller a fresh +1)
// ============================================================

// A PARAM value flowing into `ret`/`errorReturn` had no acquire and the caller
// still owns its own +1, so the callee must hand the caller a fresh owned
// reference: incref the returned param immediately before the terminator. Every
// other returned class already carries the +1 to transfer (acquire-at-def, or
// the call's +1 for callReturnRc1) and needs no return-incref.
function planReturnIncrefs(ctx RcContext)
	for blockRef in ctx.func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try ctx.module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("planReturnIncrefs: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		if not block.hasTerminatorOp() 'noTerm'
			continue
		end 'noTerm'
		let term = try ctx.module.ops.get(block.terminatorIndex()) otherwise panic("planReturnIncrefs: terminator not in module.ops")
		planReturnIncrefForTerm(ctx, blockRef: blockRef, block: block, term: term)
	end 'eachBlock'
end 'planReturnIncrefs'

function planReturnIncrefForTerm(ctx RcContext, blockRef BlockRef, block IrBlock, term StdOp)
	match term 'dispatch'
		call(c) then planReturnIncrefForCall(ctx, blockRef: blockRef, block: block, c: c)
		arith then break 'dispatch'
		control then break 'dispatch'
		memory then break 'dispatch'
		system then break 'dispatch'
	end 'dispatch'
end 'planReturnIncrefForTerm'

function planReturnIncrefForCall(ctx RcContext, blockRef BlockRef, block IrBlock, c StdCallOp)
	match c 'check'
		ret(retValId) then planReturnIncrefValue(ctx, blockRef: blockRef, block: block, retValId: retValId)
		errorReturn(retValId, _) then planReturnIncrefValue(ctx, blockRef: blockRef, block: block, retValId: retValId)
		call to param then break 'check'
	end 'check'
end 'planReturnIncrefForCall'

function planReturnIncrefValue(ctx RcContext, blockRef BlockRef, block IrBlock, retValId ValueId)
	if not ctx.isManaged(retValId) 'notManaged'
		return
	end 'notManaged'
	if not ctx.isParam(retValId) 'notParam'
		return
	end 'notParam'
	// A CONSUMED param already OWNS the caller's transferred +1 (Concept C). Returning
	// it transfers that owned +1 to the caller directly — no fresh incref (the
	// `terminatorReturnsValue` guard in `planTerminatorDeaths` suppresses its release,
	// so the +1 flows straight out). A BORROWED returned param, by contrast, leaves the
	// caller's own reference intact and so must hand back a NEW +1 — that is the case
	// this incref serves. Without this skip a returned consumed param is double-counted.
	if valueIsConsumedParamOfCurrentFunc(ctx, valueId: retValId) 'consumedParam'
		return
	end 'consumedParam'
	// Place the incref right before the terminator (at the end of the body).
	logTrace(LogCategory.ir, message: function() gives "RC-RETURN-INCREF func={ctx.func.name} val=%{retValId} class={ownershipClassName(ctx.classOf(retValId))}")
	let incIdx = buildIncrefOp(ctx.module, valueId: retValId, idRef: ctx.idRef)
	queueInsertion(ctx, blockRef: blockRef, pos: block.opRefs.count(), opIdx: incIdx)
end 'planReturnIncrefValue'

// ============================================================
// Last-use decrefs
// ============================================================

// Plan the release (decref) for every managed value at its last use on each
// path. Three cases:
//   - IN-BLOCK death: V dies inside a block B (V live before some body op, dead
//     after, and V not live-out of B) → decref right after that op.
//   - EDGE death: V escapes B (live-out) but dies entering a successor S → an
//     edge release, recorded for `applyEdgeReleases` (splits critical edges).
//   - TERMINATOR death: V is live entering the terminator (used by it, e.g. as
//     a `ret` value's interior-borrow BASE) but is NOT live-out and is NOT
//     returned → neither of the above fires (no BODY op kills it — the
//     `planInBlockDeaths` scan covers `block.opRefs`, which excludes the
//     terminator — and it has no out-edge death because it does not survive into
//     any successor), so decref it right before the terminator.
function planLastUseDecrefs(ctx RcContext)
	for blockRef in ctx.func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try ctx.module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("planLastUseDecrefs: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		planInBlockDeaths(ctx, blockRef: blockRef, block: block)
		planEdgeDeaths(ctx, block: block)
		planTerminatorDeaths(ctx, blockRef: blockRef, block: block)
	end 'eachBlock'
end 'planLastUseDecrefs'

// Release a value that owns a transferable +1 (or is a droppable freshRc0 /
// type-param) but has ZERO uses — DEAD ON ARRIVAL at its def. The three last-use
// sweeps above are all liveness-driven: they release a value at an in-block /
// edge / terminator point where it is live-before and dies. A value that is never
// live anywhere — the canonical case being a DISCARDED owning result,
// `_ = try xs.pop() otherwise …` (a `callReturnRc1` whose +1 transfers to the
// discard binding that is never read) — is invisible to all three, so its +1 is
// never dropped and leaks. The popped element is freed neither at the discard nor
// by the array's later element-walk (it was removed from the array): a pure leak
// the liveness sweeps structurally cannot see.
//
// A dead-on-arrival value cannot have been MOVED at its def (a move is a use at a
// later op, which would make it live-after the def) and cannot be RETURNED (the
// `ret`/`errorReturn` terminator is a use), so no transfer-suppression applies —
// the local +1 genuinely stays here and must be released right where the value
// becomes available. For a `tryCall` result that is NULL on the error edge, the
// drop goes at the head of the SUCCESS block (the error-flag condBr's ELSE
// target), exactly mirroring `planAcquireForOp`'s success-block acquire placement;
// for any other def it goes immediately after the def op. Planned AFTER
// `planAcquireIncrefs` so a value that both acquires (success-block pos 0) and
// dead-drops there lands the acquire before the drop (the same-pos plan-order tie
// rule in `applyPlansForBlock`).
function planDeadDefDrops(ctx RcContext)
	for blockRef in ctx.func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try ctx.module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("planDeadDefDrops: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		let liveAfter = computeBlockLiveAfter(ctx.module, block: block, liveness: ctx.liveness)
		var pos = 0
		let opCount = block.opRefs.count()
		while pos < opCount 'eachOp'
			let opIdx = try block.opRefs.get(pos) otherwise panic("planDeadDefDrops: opRefs.get({pos}) failed despite pos < count")
			let op = try ctx.module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("planDeadDefDrops: opIdx not in module.ops")
			let operands = extractStdOpOperands(op)
			for defId in operands.writeIds 'eachDef'
				if deadDefNeedsDrop(ctx, block: block, liveAfter: liveAfter, pos: pos, defId: defId) 'dead'
					logTrace(LogCategory.ir, message: function() gives "RC-DEADDROP func={ctx.func.name} val=%{defId} atpos={pos} class={ownershipClassName(ctx.classOf(defId))} kind={releaseKindName(releaseKindAtLastUse(ctx, id: defId))}")
					let relIdx = buildReleaseOp(ctx, id: defId)
					queueInsertionAtDefPoint(ctx, defBlockRef: blockRef, defBlock: block, pos: pos, defId: defId, opIdx: relIdx)
				end 'dead'
			end 'eachDef'
			pos = pos + 1
		end 'eachOp'

		planDeadBlockParamDrops(ctx, blockRef: blockRef, block: block)
	end 'eachBlock'
end 'planDeadDefDrops'

// The BLOCK-PARAM counterpart of the body-op dead-def sweep above. A managed phi
// owns a +1 on arrival — either an edge incref (`planPhiEdgeIncrefs`) supplied it
// or the incoming value MOVED its own +1 in (`moveIntoPhi` suppressed the edge
// release). The +1 is normally consumed by the phi's last-use release, but a phi
// with ZERO uses — the canonical case being a discarded `for _ in arr` loop
// binding, whose element value rides an inline-continuation phi that nothing
// reads — is invisible to every liveness-driven sweep, so its +1 leaks (one
// element per iteration). Drop it at the head of its own block, mirroring the
// dead body-op def's drop-at-def-point.
function planDeadBlockParamDrops(ctx RcContext, blockRef NodeIndex, block IrBlock)
	var argIdx = 0
	while argIdx < block.blockArgs.count() 'eachArg'
		let arg = try block.blockArgs.get(argIdx) otherwise panic("planDeadBlockParamDrops: blockArgs.get({argIdx}) OOB")
		let vid = arg.valueId
		if deadBlockParamNeedsDrop(ctx, block: block, vid: vid) 'dead'
			logTrace(LogCategory.ir, message: function() gives "RC-DEADDROP func={ctx.func.name} val=%{vid} blockparam block={block.id} class={ownershipClassName(ctx.classOf(vid))} kind={releaseKindName(releaseKindAtLastUse(ctx, id: vid))}")
			let relIdx = buildReleaseOp(ctx, id: vid)
			queueInsertion(ctx, blockRef: blockRef, pos: 0, opIdx: relIdx)
		end 'dead'
		argIdx = argIdx + 1
	end 'eachArg'
end 'planDeadBlockParamDrops'

// True iff the block param `vid` owns a releasable +1 (`shouldReleaseAtLastUse`,
// same gate as the body-op sweep) yet has ZERO uses: no body op or terminator in
// its block reads it and it is not live-out into any successor. Same layout guard
// as `deadDefNeedsDrop` for the type-param drop form.
function deadBlockParamNeedsDrop(ctx RcContext, block IrBlock, vid ValueId) returns bool
	if blockReadsValue(ctx, block: block, vid: vid) 'hasUses'
		return false
	end 'hasUses'
	return deadValueDropGates(ctx, block: block, vid: vid)
end 'deadBlockParamNeedsDrop'

// The use-test-independent gates shared by the body-op and block-param dead-def
// sweeps: a releasable +1 (`shouldReleaseAtLastUse`), not returned, not live-out
// of the block, and — for the type-param drop form — a resolved layout
// descriptor (without one the drop cannot be built; the managed decref /
// dropManaged forms never need a layout).
function deadValueDropGates(ctx RcContext, block IrBlock, vid ValueId) returns bool
	if not shouldReleaseAtLastUse(ctx, id: vid) 'noRelease'
		return false
	end 'noRelease'
	if ctx.isReturned(vid) 'returned'
		return false
	end 'returned'
	if ctx.liveness.liveOutContains(block.id, vid: vid) 'escapes'
		return false
	end 'escapes'
	if releaseKindAtLastUse(ctx, id: vid) == ReleaseKind.dropTypeParam and ctx.layoutValueId == RELEASE_NO_LAYOUT 'noLayout'
		return false
	end 'noLayout'
	return true
end 'deadValueDropGates'

// True iff any body op or the terminator of `block` reads `vid`.
function blockReadsValue(ctx RcContext, block IrBlock, vid ValueId) returns bool
	for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
		let op = try ctx.module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("blockReadsValue: opIdx not in module.ops")
		if stdOpReadsValue(op, vid: vid) 'reads'
			return true
		end 'reads'
	end 'eachOp'
	if block.hasTerminatorOp() 'hasTerm'
		let term = try ctx.module.ops.get(block.terminatorIndex()) otherwise panic("blockReadsValue: terminator opIdx not in module.ops")
		if stdOpReadsValue(term, vid: vid) 'termReads'
			return true
		end 'termReads'
	end 'hasTerm'
	return false
end 'blockReadsValue'

// True iff `op` reads `vid` through any operand position.
function stdOpReadsValue(op StdOp, vid ValueId) returns bool
	let operands = extractStdOpOperands(op)
	for readId in operands.readIds 'eachRead'
		if readId == vid 'hit'
			return true
		end 'hit'
	end 'eachRead'
	return false
end 'stdOpReadsValue'

// True iff `defId` (defined by the op at `pos` in `block`) owns a +1 that needs
// releasing yet is DEAD ON ARRIVAL — never live, so no last-use sweep will drop
// it. Conditions, all required:
//   - `shouldReleaseAtLastUse`: it carries a releasable +1 (excludes
//     notManaged / borrowed / param / non-droppable incomingOwner).
//   - NOT live after its def op AND NOT live-out of the def block: an SSA value
//     with any use is live from just after its def to its last use, so "not live
//     immediately after the def" is exactly "zero uses". (A `tryCall` result used
//     only on the success edge is live-out of the def block, so it is excluded
//     here and handled by the normal edge/in-block sweeps in the success block.)
//   - NOT returned: defensive — a returned value is read by the terminator and so
//     is live, never reaching here, but the explicit guard keeps the
//     transfer-to-caller invariant legible.
//   - the type-param drop form needs a resolved layout descriptor (see
//     `deadValueDropGates`).
function deadDefNeedsDrop(ctx RcContext, block IrBlock, liveAfter StdLiveAfter, pos NodeIndex, defId ValueId) returns bool
	if liveAfter.isLiveAfterBodyOp(pos, vid: defId) 'hasUses'
		return false
	end 'hasUses'
	return deadValueDropGates(ctx, block: block, vid: defId)
end 'deadDefNeedsDrop'

// A BORROWED value moved into a container takes the CONTAINER's own reference. A
// `borrowed` element (an iterator `.current()` view structurally classified by the
// return-borrow analysis, owning no +1) consumed by a container mutator
// (`callConsumesManagedElement`) is raw-stored into the container's element buffer
// and decref'd ONCE by the container's destructor element-walk. The source
// collection still owns its own reference, so the container must INCREF on store
// or the source's teardown frees the element out from under the container (the
// rung-28 over-free → element-walk UAF). The retain is layout-routed
// (`__mm_retain_type_param`): it increfs a managed-pointer element and no-ops a
// primitive, so it is correct for a generic type-parameter element whose concrete
// managed-ness is a runtime fact. Only `borrowed` elements need it — an OWNED
// element (`freshRc0` / `callReturnRc1`, e.g. `s.insert(Item.create())`) carries a
// +1 that the move transfers straight into the container.
function planBorrowedElementContainerRetains(ctx RcContext)
	if ctx.layoutValueId == RELEASE_NO_LAYOUT 'noLayout'
		return
	end 'noLayout'
	for blockRef in ctx.func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try ctx.module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("planBorrowedElementContainerRetains: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		var pos = 0
		for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
			let op = try ctx.module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("planBorrowedElementContainerRetains: opIdx not in module.ops")
			let operands = extractStdOpOperands(op)
			for argId in operands.readIds 'eachArg'
				if borrowedElementConsumedByContainer(ctx, op: op, argId: argId) 'retain'
					logTrace(LogCategory.ir, message: function() gives "RC-ELEM-RETAIN func={ctx.func.name} val=%{argId} atpos={pos}")
					let retIdx = buildRetainForValue(ctx, valueId: argId)
					queueInsertion(ctx, blockRef: blockRef, pos: pos, opIdx: retIdx)
				end 'retain'
			end 'eachArg'
			pos = pos + 1
		end 'eachOp'
	end 'eachBlock'
end 'planBorrowedElementContainerRetains'

// COPY-incref a consumed argument the caller still needs. A CONSUMING call (a
// container mutator / intrinsic consumer / transparent wrap) unconditionally
// takes ownership of its argument's +1 — the callee stores the pointer without
// increfing and the new owner's destructor performs the matching decref. When
// the call is the argument's LAST use that is a pure MOVE (the last-use release
// is suppressed by the transfer guard). But when the argument stays LIVE AFTER
// the call (`Subprocess.run(.., cwd)` followed by `cwd.path`), the caller still
// owes a reference for the rest of the value's lifetime: without a copy the
// callee-side owner's teardown frees the value out from under the caller's
// later uses (UAF) and the value's own death-point release over-releases (the
// subprocess-cwd rc=0 trap). Mirror the heap-field-store copy rule
// (`storeIsManagedFieldTransfer`'s live-after gate): incref BEFORE the
// consuming call, so the callee consumes the minted +1 and the caller keeps its
// own. Only values that genuinely OWN a transferable +1 are copied
// (`transferValueAlreadyOwnsPlusOne`); a `borrowed` view owns nothing to
// transfer and is retained by the layout-routed
// `planBorrowedElementContainerRetains` instead. Type-param values never get
// plain increfs — they keep the consumed-earlier release suppression in
// `isInBlockDeathPoint`.
function planConsumedArgCopyIncrefs(ctx RcContext)
	for blockRef in ctx.func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try ctx.module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("planConsumedArgCopyIncrefs: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		let liveAfter = computeBlockLiveAfter(ctx.module, block: block, liveness: ctx.liveness)
		var pos = 0
		for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
			let op = try ctx.module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("planConsumedArgCopyIncrefs: opIdx not in module.ops")
			let operands = extractStdOpOperands(op)
			// The same value can be consumed at SEVERAL argument positions of one
			// call (`Outer.create(shared, second: shared)` stores it twice) — the
			// callee takes one +1 PER consumed position, so the copy count is
			// per-position, planned once per distinct value.
			var retainedHere = ValueIdArray.create()
			for argId in operands.readIds 'eachArg'
				if not valueIdArrayContains(retainedHere, vid: argId) 'notYetRetained'
					retainedHere.push(argId)
					let copies = consumedArgCopyCount(ctx, liveAfter: liveAfter, block: block, op: op, pos: pos, argId: argId)
					for _ in 0 upto copies 'eachCopy'
						logTrace(LogCategory.ir, message: function() gives "RC-CONSUME-COPY func={ctx.func.name} val=%{argId} atpos={pos}")
						// `buildRetainForValue` picks the copy form by domain: a
						// concrete managed pointer increfs directly; a type-param
						// value takes the layout-routed retain (per-ordinal when
						// the param name resolves).
						let incIdx = buildRetainForValue(ctx, valueId: argId)
						queueInsertion(ctx, blockRef: blockRef, pos: pos, opIdx: incIdx)
					end 'eachCopy'
				end 'notYetRetained'
			end 'eachArg'
			pos = pos + 1
		end 'eachOp'
	end 'eachBlock'
end 'planConsumedArgCopyIncrefs'

// The number of copies owed for `argId` at consuming op `op`: one per
// consumed argument position, minus the one +1 the MOVE itself transfers when
// the op is the value's real last use. 0 when the value isn't a +1-owning
// value (managed OR generic type-param) or the op doesn't consume it.
function consumedArgCopyCount(ctx RcContext, liveAfter StdLiveAfter, block IrBlock, op StdOp, pos NodeIndex, argId ValueId) returns NodeIndex
	if not ctx.isManaged(argId) and not ctx.isTypeParam(argId) 'notTracked'
		return 0
	end 'notTracked'
	// A type-param copy is the layout-routed retain — without a resolved layout
	// there is nothing to route through (mirrors `releaseKindAtLastUse`'s
	// no-layout skip: such a value is a monomorphized scalar needing no copy).
	if ctx.isTypeParam(argId) and ctx.layoutValueId == RELEASE_NO_LAYOUT 'noLayout'
		return 0
	end 'noLayout'
	if not transferValueAlreadyOwnsPlusOne(ctx, valueId: argId) 'noPlusOne'
		// A borrowed view owns nothing to transfer; its single container retain is
		// the layout-routed `planBorrowedElementContainerRetains`.
		return 0
	end 'noPlusOne'
	let consumedPositions = consumedArgPositionCount(ctx, op: op, argId: argId)
	if consumedPositions == 0 'notConsuming'
		return 0
	end 'notConsuming'

	if consumedArgKeepsOwnPlusOne(ctx, liveAfter: liveAfter, block: block, pos: pos, argId: argId) 'realLaterUse'
		// The caller keeps using the value after the call — every consumed
		// position gets a minted +1 and the original stays with the caller
		// (released at the value's real death point).
		return consumedPositions
	end 'realLaterUse'
	// The op is the value's real last use: the move transfers the original +1
	// into ONE consumed position; any further consumed positions need copies.
	return consumedPositions - 1
end 'consumedArgCopyCount'

// True iff the caller still owes ITSELF a reference past this consuming op —
// the value has a REAL later use, so its death-point release stays owed.
// Extended liveness alone is NOT a real later use: a borrow-recording callee's
// result (an iterator factory navigating its source) extends the ARG's liveness
// to wherever the RESULT lives, and the tryCall success/error machinery
// (`valueConsumedByTryCallOnSuccessEdgeInto` + the error-edge release) already
// balances that shape path-sensitively — a copy there has no matching release
// (the `CodepointView.createIterator` leak). Only a DIRECT later read of the
// value (a syntactic operand of a later op — `cwd.path` after
// `Subprocess.run(.., cwd)`) means the caller keeps using the pointer.
function consumedArgKeepsOwnPlusOne(ctx RcContext, liveAfter StdLiveAfter, block IrBlock, pos NodeIndex, argId ValueId) returns bool
	if not liveAfter.isLiveAfterBodyOp(pos, vid: argId) 'pureMove'
		return false
	end 'pureMove'
	return valueDirectlyReadElsewhere(ctx, block: block, pos: pos, argId: argId)
end 'consumedArgKeepsOwnPlusOne'

// Full-gated form of `consumedArgKeepsOwnPlusOne` for callers that haven't
// already established the value's domain: a value outside the copy domain
// (neither managed nor a layout-routable type-param) or a no-+1 view never
// receives a copy, so its consume can never leave the caller a retained
// reference. Mirrors `consumedArgCopyCount`'s gates exactly — the
// consumed-earlier release suppression must agree with whether a copy was
// minted at the consume site.
function consumedArgRetainedPastOp(ctx RcContext, liveAfter StdLiveAfter, block IrBlock, pos NodeIndex, argId ValueId) returns bool
	if not ctx.isManaged(argId) and not ctx.isTypeParam(argId) 'notTracked'
		return false
	end 'notTracked'
	if ctx.isTypeParam(argId) and ctx.layoutValueId == RELEASE_NO_LAYOUT 'noLayout'
		return false
	end 'noLayout'
	if not transferValueAlreadyOwnsPlusOne(ctx, valueId: argId) 'noPlusOne'
		return false
	end 'noPlusOne'
	return consumedArgKeepsOwnPlusOne(ctx, liveAfter: liveAfter, block: block, pos: pos, argId: argId)
end 'consumedArgRetainedPastOp'

// The number of argument positions of `op` at which the callee CONSUMES
// `argId`: positions >= 1 read the structural per-position consume bit; the
// arg-0 slot consumes only for a static-factory / transparent-wrap callee
// (`funcParamConsumes[callee][0]` — for instance methods arg 0 is the borrowed
// `self`, whose bit is never set). Trailing layout/witness args are non-managed
// and never equal a managed `argId`.
function consumedArgPositionCount(ctx RcContext, op StdOp, argId ValueId) returns NodeIndex
	return match op 'dispatch'
		call(c) gives callConsumedPositionCount(ctx, c: c, argId: argId)
		arith gives 0
		control gives 0
		memory gives 0
		system gives 0
	end 'dispatch'
end 'consumedArgPositionCount'

function callConsumedPositionCount(ctx RcContext, c StdCallOp, argId ValueId) returns NodeIndex
	return match c 'check'
		call(_, callee, argIds) gives consumedPositionsIn(ctx, callee: callee, argIds: argIds, argId: argId)
		tryCall(_, callee, argIds, _) gives consumedPositionsIn(ctx, callee: callee, argIds: argIds, argId: argId)
		ret gives 0
		indirectCall to errorReturn gives 0
	end 'check'
end 'callConsumedPositionCount'

function consumedPositionsIn(ctx RcContext, callee String, argIds ValueIdArray, argId ValueId) returns NodeIndex
	var count = 0
	var idx = 0
	while idx < argIds.count() 'each'
		let aid = try argIds.get(idx) otherwise panic("consumedPositionsIn: argIds.get({idx}) OOB despite idx < count")
		if aid == argId and paramConsumeBit(ctx.funcParamConsumes, callee: callee, argIndex: idx) 'consumed'
			count = count + 1
		end 'consumed'
		idx = idx + 1
	end 'each'
	return count
end 'consumedPositionsIn'

// True iff `argId` appears as a DIRECT read operand (NOT a borrow-expanded base)
// of a later body op or the terminator of `block`, or of any op/terminator of
// ANOTHER block. Flow direction across other blocks is over-approximated (a read
// in a sibling arm counts), which is safe: the copy gate also requires extended
// live-after at the consume, and a spuriously-copied value's extended death point
// still releases the extra +1 (`valueConsumedEarlierInBlock` only suppresses when
// NO copy was minted).
function valueDirectlyReadElsewhere(ctx RcContext, block IrBlock, pos NodeIndex, argId ValueId) returns bool
	let opCount = block.opRefs.count()
	var p = pos + 1
	while p < opCount 'laterOps'
		let opIdx = try block.opRefs.get(p) otherwise panic("valueDirectlyReadElsewhere: opRefs.get({p}) failed despite p < count")
		if opDirectlyReads(ctx, opIdx: opIdx, argId: argId) 'read'
			return true
		end 'read'
		p = p + 1
	end 'laterOps'

	if blockTerminatorDirectlyReads(ctx, block: block, argId: argId) 'termRead'
		return true
	end 'termRead'

	for otherRef in ctx.func.blockRefs 'otherBlocks'
		let other = try ctx.module.blocks.get(otherRef) otherwise panic("valueDirectlyReadElsewhere: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		if other.id == block.id 'sameBlock'
			continue
		end 'sameBlock'
		for opIdx in other.opRefs 'eachOp'
			if opDirectlyReads(ctx, opIdx: opIdx, argId: argId) 'read'
				return true
			end 'read'
		end 'eachOp'
		if blockTerminatorDirectlyReads(ctx, block: other, argId: argId) 'otherTermRead'
			return true
		end 'otherTermRead'
	end 'otherBlocks'
	return false
end 'valueDirectlyReadElsewhere'

function opDirectlyReads(ctx RcContext, opIdx OpIndex, argId ValueId) returns bool
	let op = try ctx.module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("opDirectlyReads: opIdx not in module.ops")
	return valueIdArrayContains(extractStdOpOperands(op).readIds, vid: argId)
end 'opDirectlyReads'

function blockTerminatorDirectlyReads(ctx RcContext, block IrBlock, argId ValueId) returns bool
	if not block.hasTerminatorOp() 'noTerm'
		return false
	end 'noTerm'
	return opDirectlyReads(ctx, opIdx: block.terminatorIndex(), argId: argId)
end 'blockTerminatorDirectlyReads'

// Incref a NO-+1 value at the op that TRANSPARENTLY WRAPS it (`Array.init` /
// `Vector.init` / `String.init` arg 0). The wrap's result owns the pointer (its
// destructor decrefs once), so a wrapped value that carries no transferable +1
// (a `borrowed` self-field load, a non-consumed param) must be retained at the
// wrap — owning classes transfer their existing +1 via the move instead and are
// excluded by the `noPlusOne` gate.
function planBorrowedWrapRetains(ctx RcContext)
	for blockRef in ctx.func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try ctx.module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("planBorrowedWrapRetains: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		var pos = 0
		for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
			let op = try ctx.module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("planBorrowedWrapRetains: opIdx not in module.ops")
			let operands = extractStdOpOperands(op)
			for argId in operands.readIds 'eachArg'
				if noPlusOneValueTransparentlyWrapped(ctx, op: op, argId: argId) 'retain'
					logTrace(LogCategory.ir, message: function() gives "RC-WRAP-RETAIN func={ctx.func.name} val=%{argId} atpos={pos}")
					let incIdx = buildIncrefOp(ctx.module, valueId: argId, idRef: ctx.idRef)
					queueInsertion(ctx, blockRef: blockRef, pos: pos, opIdx: incIdx)
				end 'retain'
			end 'eachArg'
			pos = pos + 1
		end 'eachOp'
	end 'eachBlock'
end 'planBorrowedWrapRetains'

function noPlusOneValueTransparentlyWrapped(ctx RcContext, op StdOp, argId ValueId) returns bool
	if not ctx.isManaged(argId) 'notManaged'
		return false
	end 'notManaged'
	if plusOneOwnership(ctx, id: argId) != PlusOneOwnership.noPlusOne 'hasPlusOne'
		return false
	end 'hasPlusOne'
	return callTransparentlyWrapsArg(ctx, op: op, argId: argId)
end 'noPlusOneValueTransparentlyWrapped'

// True iff `argId` is a `borrowed` value consumed by `op` (a container-mutator
// call at a non-self element position). Only `borrowed` (owns no +1) triggers the
// container retain; every owning class transfers its +1 via the move instead.
function borrowedElementConsumedByContainer(ctx RcContext, op StdOp, argId ValueId) returns bool
	if not classIsBorrowed(ctx, id: argId) 'notBorrowed'
		return false
	end 'notBorrowed'
	return callConsumesManagedElement(ctx.funcParamConsumes, op: op, argId: argId)
end 'borrowedElementConsumedByContainer'

// Retain each `borrowed` value the function FORWARDS as its own return value, so the
// returned pointer carries a real +1 the caller can own. A borrow-returning call
// result the return-borrow analysis marked `borrowed` (because the enclosing
// function returns it — `Array.get`'s `managed.get(...)`, `Map.get`'s
// `values.get(...)`) owns NO +1: the source collection owns the element. Returned
// AS-IS, the caller treats it as `callReturnRc1` and consumes a +1 that does not
// exist → double-free when the source collection's teardown frees the element (the
// `Map<K,Box>` get-borrow-after-free; the inlined dual is rung-11, where the
// `__managed_mem_get` result is `incomingOwner` and acquires on return). The retain
// is the def-side analogue of `planBorrowedElementContainerRetains`'s store-side
// one — same layout-routed `__mm_retain_type_param` (increfs a managed-pointer
// element, no-ops a primitive), so it is correct for the generic element type. A
// `tryCall` result is NULL on the error edge, so the retain is placed at the START
// of the SUCCESS block (where the result is provably non-null), mirroring
// `planAcquireForOp`; a non-tryCall def is retained immediately after its def.
function planReturnedBorrowRetains(ctx RcContext)
	if ctx.layoutValueId == RELEASE_NO_LAYOUT 'noLayout'
		return
	end 'noLayout'
	for blockRef in ctx.func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try ctx.module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("planReturnedBorrowRetains: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		var pos = 0
		for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
			let op = try ctx.module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("planReturnedBorrowRetains: opIdx not in module.ops")
			let operands = extractStdOpOperands(op)
			for defId in operands.writeIds 'eachDef'
				if returnedBorrowNeedsRetainCtx(ctx, id: defId) 'retain'
					logTrace(LogCategory.ir, message: function() gives "RC-RETBORROW-RETAIN func={ctx.func.name} val=%{defId} atpos={pos}")
					let retIdx = buildRetainForValue(ctx, valueId: defId)
					// A `tryCall` result is NULL on the error edge; `queueInsertionAtDefPoint`
					// retains it at the SUCCESS-block head (provably non-null), else
					// immediately after the def.
					queueInsertionAtDefPoint(ctx, defBlockRef: blockRef, defBlock: block, pos: pos, defId: defId, opIdx: retIdx)
				end 'retain'
			end 'eachDef'
			pos = pos + 1
		end 'eachOp'
	end 'eachBlock'
end 'planReturnedBorrowRetains'

// True iff `id` is a RETURNED `borrowed` value (a forwarded borrow-returning call
// result) — the values `planReturnedBorrowRetains` retains. Only `borrowed`, and
// only when the value is one of the function's returns.
function returnedBorrowNeedsRetainCtx(ctx RcContext, id ValueId) returns bool
	if not classIsBorrowed(ctx, id: id) 'notBorrowed'
		return false
	end 'notBorrowed'
	return ctx.isReturned(id)
end 'returnedBorrowNeedsRetainCtx'

// True iff value `id` is classified `borrowed`.
function classIsBorrowed(ctx RcContext, id ValueId) returns bool
	return ownershipClassIsBorrowed(ctx.classOf(id))
end 'classIsBorrowed'

// True iff value `id` is classified `callReturnRc1` (arrives owning a
// transferred +1).
function classIsCallReturnRc1(ctx RcContext, id ValueId) returns bool
	return match ctx.classOf(id) 'cls'
		callReturnRc1 gives true
		notManaged gives false
		freshRc0 gives false
		selfReturnBorrow to borrowed gives false
	end 'cls'
end 'classIsCallReturnRc1'

// Release values whose extended last use falls AT the block's terminator. A
// value live immediately after the last body op (so `planInBlockDeaths`, which
// only scans `block.opRefs`, never sees it die) but NOT live-out of the block
// dies at the terminator: the terminator is its final use and nothing carries it
// into a successor. `planEdgeDeaths` cannot release it either (it is absent from
// `liveOut`, so it is not on any out-edge). Without this it is never dropped and
// leaks.
//
// The canonical case is an interior-borrow BASE that feeds a `ret`: a
// pointer-width field-load borrows the base, the borrow-liveness extension keeps
// the base live across the load to wherever the loaded value is used, and when
// that use is the `ret` terminator the base's death lands exactly here.
// Concretely `let b = Box.create(); return b.get()` inlines to a qword field-load
// of `b` feeding the return — `b` is a `freshRc0` managed struct kept live to the
// `ret` by the borrow extension, so its decref belongs right before the `ret`.
//
// Returned values are skipped (`shouldReleaseAtLastUse` → `isReturned` → none):
// their +1 transfers to the caller. A value moved into a successor's phi is, by
// definition, live-out (present in some successor's `liveIn`), so it is excluded
// by the live-out filter and handled by `planEdgeDeaths`'s move guard instead.
// The release is inserted at `opRefs.count()` — after every body op and before
// the separate terminator op — so the decref runs on the way out of the block.
function planTerminatorDeaths(ctx RcContext, blockRef BlockRef, block IrBlock)
	if not block.hasTerminatorOp() 'noTerm'
		return
	end 'noTerm'
	let opCount = block.opRefs.count()
	// Values live immediately BEFORE the terminator: seed from `liveOut[block]`
	// and apply the terminator op backward (it defines nothing; its argIds /
	// condId — borrow-expanded — become live above it). This is exactly the set
	// the terminator may still consume, INCLUDING the interior-borrow bases of any
	// pointer it reads. Independent of body-op count, so it is correct for
	// terminator-only blocks too.
	let liveBeforeTerm = liveSetBeforeTerminator(ctx, block: block)
	var releasedHere = ValueIdArray.create()
	for vid in liveBeforeTerm.members 'eachLive'
		if valueIdArrayContains(releasedHere, vid: vid) 'dup'
			continue
		end 'dup'
		// Live-out values survive into a successor — released on an out-edge by
		// `planEdgeDeaths`, never here (releasing here would free a still-live
		// value). Only values that die AT the terminator remain.
		if ctx.liveness.liveOutContains(block.id, vid: vid) 'escapes'
			continue
		end 'escapes'
		// MOVE-into-phi guard: a value passed as a block-arg into a successor's
		// phi is MOVED (its +1 transfers into the phi); `planEdgeDeaths` already
		// suppresses its edge release. It is live-BEFORE the terminator (the phi-arg
		// pass reads it) but NOT live-out (the successor sees the phi result, not
		// this value), so it would otherwise fall through to a term-drop here — a
		// SECOND release that double-frees the moved value (the for-in iterator
		// passed into the createIterator success/error merge phi: move-suppressed on
		// the edge AND term-dropped, freeing the iterator the loop then reads). Skip
		// any value moved into a phi on a terminator out-edge — the phi owns it now.
		if valueMovedIntoAnyPhi(ctx, block: block, vid: vid) 'movedIntoPhi'
			continue
		end 'movedIntoPhi'
		// BORROW-ROOT DEFERRAL guard: `vid` is the owning allocation behind a
		// borrowed phi-arg (e.g. the array behind `Array.get`'s element) that
		// receives a phi-edge incref on an out-edge. Its release was deferred to
		// that edge (`planBorrowRootEdgeRelease`), AFTER the incref - term-dropping
		// it here would free the element before the incref secures the phi's +1
		// (the aliased-managed-element garbage-tag UAF). The edge-release owns it.
		if borrowRootDeferredToPhiEdge(ctx, block: block, vid: vid) 'borrowRootDeferred'
			continue
		end 'borrowRootDeferred'
		// RETURN-TRANSFER guard (path-sensitive): if THIS terminator is the
		// `ret`/`errorReturn` that returns `vid`, its +1 transfers to the caller here —
		// suppress the release (the def-acquire +1 IS the caller's reference). This is
		// the per-terminator form of the suppression that used to live value-globally in
		// `releaseKindAtLastUse` (`isReturned → none`); moving it here makes it
		// path-sensitive so a value returned on THIS arm but dropped on a SIBLING arm
		// still gets released on the sibling (planEdgeDeaths / planInBlockDeaths there),
		// fixing the one-arm-return leak. A value live-before this terminator but NOT
		// the returned one (e.g. the sibling `b` at `return a`) falls through and is
		// released here.
		if terminatorReturnsValue(ctx, block: block, vid: vid) 'returnedHere'
			continue
		end 'returnedHere'
		// TRYCALL-CONSUMED-ARG guard (path-sensitive, success edge): `vid`'s +1 was
		// CONSUMED by a `tryCall` argument on the SUCCESS edge INTO this block (a
		// transparent-wrapper factory — `StringIterator.create`/`ByteView.create` —
		// moving `managed` into the value it builds). The +1 transferred to the callee
		// on the success path, so term-dropping `vid` here is a SECOND release of an
		// already-moved +1 (it would free the String's buffer the new owner still holds
		// → `for c in s` twice reads a freed buffer → grapheme slice OOB). The matching
		// ERROR edge keeps its release (the throw path never consumed `vid`). The arg-
		// side dual of the result-side `tryCallResultDiesOnErrorEdge` error-edge guard.
		if valueConsumedByTryCallOnSuccessEdgeInto(ctx, intoBlockId: block.id, vid: vid) 'consumedOnEntry'
			logTrace(LogCategory.ir, message: function() gives "RC-TERMDROP-CONSUMED-SUPPRESS func={ctx.func.name} val=%{vid} block_{block.id} (consumed by tryCall on success edge, no release)")
			continue
		end 'consumedOnEntry'
		// `shouldReleaseAtLastUse` already excludes params (caller owns their +1),
		// borrowed views, and notManaged.
		if not shouldReleaseAtLastUse(ctx, id: vid) 'skip'
			continue
		end 'skip'
		// CONSUMED-EARLIER guard (same rule as `isInBlockDeathPoint`): borrow
		// extension can push a value's death to the terminator even though a body
		// op already MOVED its +1 unconditionally (a consuming factory whose result
		// borrows/owns the arg — the value stays live through the result's uses,
		// dies here, but the +1 is the callee's now). Releasing here strips the new
		// owner's reference. A consume site that minted a copy-incref does not
		// suppress (the original +1 is still owed its release).
		if valueConsumedEarlierInBlock(ctx, block: block, liveAfter: computeBlockLiveAfter(ctx.module, block: block, liveness: ctx.liveness), beforePos: opCount, vid: vid) 'consumedEarlier'
			logTrace(LogCategory.ir, message: function() gives "RC-TERMDROP-CONSUMED-SUPPRESS func={ctx.func.name} val=%{vid} block_{block.id} (unconditional move earlier in block)")
			continue
		end 'consumedEarlier'
		logTrace(LogCategory.ir, message: function() gives "RC-TERMDROP func={ctx.func.name} val=%{vid} block_{block.id} class={ownershipClassName(ctx.classOf(vid))} kind={releaseKindName(releaseKindAtLastUse(ctx, id: vid))}")
		let relIdx = buildReleaseOp(ctx, id: vid)
		queueInsertion(ctx, blockRef: blockRef, pos: opCount, opIdx: relIdx)
		releasedHere.push(vid)
	end 'eachLive'
end 'planTerminatorDeaths'

// Release the managed content of every ADDRESS-TAKEN slot at each function-return
// terminator. A managed value stored into a closure-captured (address-taken) slot is
// owned by the SLOT — its SSA-store release was suppressed (`moveIntoAddressTakenSlot`)
// so the closure can read it BY REFERENCE during the function body — so the matching
// release fires HERE, at scope exit, AFTER every closure use. At each `ret`/`errorReturn`
// the slot's current occupant is loaded and null-guarded-decref'd (the slot is
// zero-init'd at entry, so an unassigned path reads null and no-ops). Mirrors the C#
// bootstrap's scope-exit drop of a captured local; the env block itself is freed
// separately by `planClosureEnvFrees`.
function planAddressTakenSlotDrops(ctx RcContext)
	let slotCount = ctx.func.slotMaxonTypes.count()
	for blockRef in ctx.func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try ctx.module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("planAddressTakenSlotDrops: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		if not block.hasTerminatorOp() 'noTerm'
			continue
		end 'noTerm'
		if not terminatorIsReturn(ctx, block: block) 'notReturn'
			continue
		end 'notReturn'
		let opCount = block.opRefs.count()
		var slotId = 0
		while slotId < slotCount 'eachSlot'
			if ctx.isAddressTakenSlot(slotId as VarSlot) and addressTakenSlotHoldsManaged(ctx, slotId: slotId as VarSlot) 'managedCapture'
				// Insert `loadSlot` THEN `decref(loaded)` immediately before the
				// terminator. Both queue at `pos = opCount` (same pos): `applyPlans`
				// inserts same-pos ties in REVERSE plan-order, so queue the DECREF FIRST
				// and the LOAD SECOND — the load then lands ABOVE the decref (load
				// before decref), so the decref reads the just-loaded slot value, not
				// an undefined id (the garbage-tag `ArrayIterator` read otherwise).
				let loadId = allocValueId(ctx.idRef)
				let loadOpIdx = ctx.module.ops.count()
				ctx.module.ops.push(StdOp.memory(StdMemoryOp.loadSlot(loadId, slotId: slotId as VarSlot)))
				let decrefIdx = buildDecrefOp(ctx.module, valueId: loadId, nullGuarded: true, idRef: ctx.idRef)
				queueInsertion(ctx, blockRef: blockRef, pos: opCount, opIdx: decrefIdx)
				queueInsertion(ctx, blockRef: blockRef, pos: opCount, opIdx: loadOpIdx)
				logTrace(LogCategory.ir, message: function() gives "RC-ADDRSLOTDROP func={ctx.func.name} slot_{slotId} block_{block.id}")
			end 'managedCapture'
			slotId = slotId + 1
		end 'eachSlot'
	end 'eachBlock'
end 'planAddressTakenSlotDrops'

// True iff some `storeSlot(slotId, value)` in the function stores a MANAGED value into
// slot `slotId` — i.e. the address-taken slot holds an owned managed reference needing a
// scope-exit decref. (A non-managed capture — an `Integer` slot — holds a value, not an
// owned pointer; its store is non-managed, so this is false and no drop is emitted.)
// Uses `ctx.isManaged` on the stored value so it agrees with the suppression decision
// (`moveIntoAddressTakenSlot`) that this slot's store was a managed transfer.
function addressTakenSlotHoldsManaged(ctx RcContext, slotId VarSlot) returns bool
	for blockRef in ctx.func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try ctx.module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("addressTakenSlotHoldsManaged: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
			let op = try ctx.module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("addressTakenSlotHoldsManaged: opIdx not in module.ops")
			if opStoresManagedIntoSlot(ctx, op: op, slotId: slotId) 'managedStore'
				return true
			end 'managedStore'
		end 'eachOp'
	end 'eachBlock'
	return false
end 'addressTakenSlotHoldsManaged'

function opStoresManagedIntoSlot(ctx RcContext, op StdOp, slotId VarSlot) returns bool
	return match op 'dispatch'
		memory(m) gives memStoresManagedIntoSlot(ctx, m: m, slotId: slotId)
		arith gives false
		control gives false
		call gives false
		system gives false
	end 'dispatch'
end 'opStoresManagedIntoSlot'

function memStoresManagedIntoSlot(ctx RcContext, m StdMemoryOp, slotId VarSlot) returns bool
	return match m 'check'
		storeSlot(targetSlot, valueId) gives targetSlot == slotId and ctx.isManaged(valueId)
		loadSlot gives false
	end 'check'
end 'memStoresManagedIntoSlot'

// True iff `block`'s terminator is a `ret`/`errorReturn` (a function-scope exit) — the
// point at which an address-taken slot's captured content is released.
function terminatorIsReturn(ctx RcContext, block IrBlock) returns bool
	let term = try ctx.module.ops.get(block.terminatorIndex()) otherwise panic("terminatorIsReturn: terminatorIndex not in module.ops")
	return opIsReturnTerminator(term)
end 'terminatorIsReturn'

function opIsReturnTerminator(op StdOp) returns bool
	return match op 'dispatch'
		call(c) gives callIsReturnTerminator(c)
		arith gives false
		control gives false
		memory gives false
		system gives false
	end 'dispatch'
end 'opIsReturnTerminator'

function callIsReturnTerminator(c StdCallOp) returns bool
	return match c 'check'
		ret gives true
		errorReturn gives true
		call to tailCall gives false
		param gives false
	end 'check'
end 'callIsReturnTerminator'

// True iff `block`'s terminator is a `ret`/`errorReturn` whose returned value is
// `vid` — i.e. `vid`'s +1 transfers to the caller AT this terminator. The
// path-sensitive replacement for the value-global `isReturned` suppression: a value
// returned on this arm is suppressed here, while the SAME SSA value dropped on a
// sibling arm is released by that arm's own death sweep.
function terminatorReturnsValue(ctx RcContext, block IrBlock, vid ValueId) returns bool
	if not block.hasTerminatorOp() 'noTerm'
		return false
	end 'noTerm'
	let term = try ctx.module.ops.get(block.terminatorIndex()) otherwise panic("terminatorReturnsValue: terminatorIndex not in module.ops")
	let retValId = try returnedValueOfTerminator(term) otherwise return false
	return retValId == vid
end 'terminatorReturnsValue'

// The set of values live immediately BEFORE the block's terminator: seed from
// `liveOut[block]` and apply the terminator backward (it defines nothing; its
// reads — borrow-expanded — become live above it). Mirrors the terminator step
// `computeBlockLiveAfter` runs before its body walk, but standalone so it works
// for any block (including terminator-only blocks). The caller's guard requires
// `block.hasTerminatorOp()`.
function liveSetBeforeTerminator(ctx RcContext, block IrBlock) returns StdLiveSet
	var running = StdLiveSet.create(ctx.liveness.maxValueId)
	let blockLiveOut = try ctx.liveness.liveOut.get(block.id) otherwise panic("liveSetBeforeTerminator: liveOut missing for block id={block.id}")
	_ = stdLiveSetUnionInto(running, from: blockLiveOut)
	let term = try ctx.module.ops.get(block.terminatorIndex()) otherwise panic("liveSetBeforeTerminator: terminatorIndex not in module.ops")
	applyOpBackward(term, running: running, borrows: ctx.liveness.borrows)
	return running
end 'liveSetBeforeTerminator'

// The release op `id` needs at its last use, or `none` if release is skipped.
// Two release domains, checked in priority order (dropTypeParam > decref):
//
//   - TYPE-PARAMETER (`sys.dropTypeParam`): a generic local/param. Released at
//     last use unless RETURNED. NOT param-skipped — the legacy slot-keyed
//     injector (`injectDropsBeforeTerminator`) dropped every live type-parameter
//     SLOT at function exit, params included (the callee owns its generic-typed
//     params); the value-keyed inserter preserves that by releasing type-param
//     params too.
//   - MANAGED (`mm_decref`): excludes borrowed, params (caller owns the +1), and
//     returned values (the +1 transfers to the caller).
//
// A value is at most one of these — a type-parameter is never managed.
//
// `isReturned` is value-global (V flows into SOME `ret`/`errorReturn` on SOME
// path) and is DELIBERATELY NOT consulted here: the return-transfer suppression is
// PATH-SENSITIVE and applied only at the terminator that actually returns V
// (`planTerminatorDeaths`'s `terminatorReturnsValue` guard). A value returned on
// one arm of a branch but DROPPED on the sibling arm (`if flag: return a else:
// return b` — `a` and `b` each transfer out on one arm and die on the other) must
// still be released on its non-returning arm; a global `isReturned → none` here
// suppressed that release and leaked the sibling (the `moveIntoPhi × returnTransfer`
// interaction). The def-acquire (`valueEscapes` → `isReturned`) still gives the
// value its +1 so the returning arm has a reference to transfer; this release rule
// just lets the OTHER arm reclaim it.
function releaseKindAtLastUse(ctx RcContext, id ValueId) returns ReleaseKind
	if ctx.isTypeParam(id) 'typeParam'
		// A `sys.dropTypeParam` needs the function's implicit `__layout` descriptor
		// to know HOW to drop the generic value. A function with NO layout param
		// (`funcHasDroppableTypeParam` was false, so `ctx.layoutValueId` is unset)
		// is non-generic at this call site: any value carrying a stale type-param
		// bit here (e.g. an `arr.get` result inlined into non-generic `main`, whose
		// concrete element is a plain `Byte`) is a fully MONOMORPHIZED scalar that
		// needs no drop. Emitting a `dropTypeParam` would panic in
		// `buildDropTypeParamForValue` (no layout to resolve). Skip it — the
		// concrete value owns no generic resource. (The classification carries the
		// callee's generic type-param bit through inlining; layout availability is
		// the authoritative "is this actually droppable HERE" signal.)
		if ctx.layoutValueId == RELEASE_NO_LAYOUT 'noLayout'
			return ReleaseKind.none
		end 'noLayout'
		// A generic type-parameter value is released via `sys.dropTypeParam` ONLY
		// when it is an OWNED local — a `.get`-style load (`incomingOwner`) that
		// gained a new owning copy, or a freshly-produced value. A `borrowed` view
		// (a relay / for-loop element into a collection the function does not own)
		// is NEVER dropped (doing so frees the collection's element — double-free).
		// `notManaged`-classed type-param values (no producer class recorded) are
		// likewise left alone. This mirrors the managed-value skip rules.
		return match ctx.classOf(id) 'tpClass'
			freshRc0 gives ReleaseKind.dropTypeParam
			incomingOwner gives ReleaseKind.dropTypeParam
			selfReturnBorrow gives ReleaseKind.dropTypeParam
			callReturnRc1 gives ReleaseKind.dropTypeParam
			borrowed gives ReleaseKind.none
			notManaged gives ReleaseKind.none
		end 'tpClass'
	end 'typeParam'
	// The managed domain is suppressed in stdlib type-param-only mode.
	if not ctx.includeManaged 'managedDisabled'
		return ReleaseKind.none
	end 'managedDisabled'
	if not ctx.isManaged(id) 'notManaged'
		return ReleaseKind.none
	end 'notManaged'
	// A BORROWED param is caller-owned (the caller releases) → no local release. A
	// CONSUMED param owns the caller's transferred +1 (Concept C) and must release it
	// at last use UNLESS moved onward — so it falls through to the `plusOneOwnership`
	// match below, where it is `acquiredAtDef` → `decref`. The transfer-suppression
	// (`isInBlockDeathPoint`/`planTerminatorDeaths`/`planEdgeDeaths`) suppresses that
	// decref wherever the +1 is forwarded/stored/returned. (`planReturnIncrefs` skips
	// the return-incref for a consumed param so a returned consumed param transfers its
	// owned +1 without a spurious second incref.)
	if ctx.isParam(id) and not valueIsConsumedParamOfCurrentFunc(ctx, valueId: id) 'borrowedParam'
		return ReleaseKind.none
	end 'borrowedParam'
	// `incomingOwner` releases at last use ONLY when it acquired a local +1 — the
	// decref is PAIRED with the acquire (`shouldAcquire`). A pure pass-through
	// borrow (no acquire) holds no local +1, so releasing it would drive the
	// SOURCE's reference down and free it out from under the still-live source
	// (the under-acquire UAF). The MOVE/return suppression for an acquired
	// `incomingOwner` is handled downstream (`isReturned`, `opMovesValueIntoContainer`).
	// View over Concept A. A value carrying a transferable +1 (`acquiredAtDef` or
	// the `callReturnRc1` `arrivesOwning`) `decref`s that +1 at last use — the
	// release is PAIRED with the acquire (or with the call's transferred +1). A
	// `noPlusOne` value holds no transferable +1: a `freshRc0` that never escaped
	// lived its whole life at rc=0 as the sole owner, so its last use FREES it via
	// `dropManaged` (the redundant-incref/decref-pair elimination); every other
	// `noPlusOne` here (a pure pass-through `incomingOwner` borrow, a `borrowed`
	// view) holds no owning ref at all and is left alone — releasing it would drive
	// the SOURCE's reference down and free it out from under the still-live source
	// (the under-acquire UAF). (notManaged/param were excluded by the early returns
	// above.)
	return match plusOneOwnership(ctx, id: id) 'p1'
		acquiredAtDef gives ReleaseKind.decref
		arrivesOwning gives ReleaseKind.decref
		noPlusOne gives freshRc0ReleaseKind(ctx, id: id)
	end 'p1'
end 'releaseKindAtLastUse'

// The release kind for a `noPlusOne` managed value at its last use: a `freshRc0`
// here never escaped (it would be `acquiredAtDef` otherwise — same `valueEscapes`
// predicate that drives the acquire decision, so acquire/release stay paired), so
// it lives at rc=0 and its last use FREES it via `dropManaged` (free-at-rc-0).
// Any OTHER `noPlusOne` class (a non-acquiring `incomingOwner` pass-through borrow,
// a `borrowed` view) owns no local reference → `none`.
function freshRc0ReleaseKind(ctx RcContext, id ValueId) returns ReleaseKind
	return match ctx.classOf(id) 'class'
		freshRc0 gives ReleaseKind.dropManaged
		incomingOwner gives ReleaseKind.none
		selfReturnBorrow gives ReleaseKind.none
		callReturnRc1 gives ReleaseKind.none
		borrowed gives ReleaseKind.none
		notManaged gives ReleaseKind.none
	end 'class'
end 'freshRc0ReleaseKind'

// True iff `id` needs any release op at its last use.
function shouldReleaseAtLastUse(ctx RcContext, id ValueId) returns bool
	return match releaseKindAtLastUse(ctx, id: id) 'kind'
		none gives false
		decref gives true
		dropTypeParam gives true
		dropManaged gives true
	end 'kind'
end 'shouldReleaseAtLastUse'

// Build the release op `id` needs at a release point, dispatching on its
// `ReleaseKind`. `nullGuarded` only applies to the decref form (dropTypeParam is
// emitted on a value the inserter proved live up to this point, never null).
// Panics on `none` — callers gate on `shouldReleaseAtLastUse` first.

function buildReleaseOp(ctx RcContext, id ValueId) returns OpIndex
	return match releaseKindAtLastUse(ctx, id: id) 'kind'
		decref gives buildDecrefOp(ctx.module, valueId: id, nullGuarded: releaseIsNullGuarded(ctx, id: id), idRef: ctx.idRef)
		dropTypeParam gives buildDropTypeParamForValue(ctx, valueId: id)
		dropManaged gives buildDropManagedOp(ctx.module, valueId: id, idRef: ctx.idRef)
		none panic("buildReleaseOp: value {id} has ReleaseKind.none — caller must gate on shouldReleaseAtLastUse")
	end 'kind'
end 'buildReleaseOp'

// Build an `mm_drop(value)` call op — the owner-drop of a never-escaped freshRc0
// value (frees at rc==0, else decrefs). Emits the runtime.std wrapper `mm_drop`
// (bare name), exactly like the inserter would reach mm_decref: the wrapper is
// seeded as a runtime-reachability root in BOTH link legs, so its always-present
// `call __mm_drop` edge keeps the stdlib body symmetric (cache parity) and the
// wrapper's signature is known from runtime.std. The result id is unused.
function buildDropManagedOp(module StdModule, valueId ValueId, idRef ValueIdRef) returns OpIndex
	let resultId = allocValueId(idRef)
	var argIds = ValueIdArray.create()
	argIds.push(valueId)
	let opIdx = module.ops.count()
	module.ops.push(StdOp.call(StdCallOp.call(resultId, callee: "mm_drop", argIds: argIds)))
	return opIdx
end 'buildDropManagedOp'

// mm-trace only: queue a trace-only `mm_move` marker at every ownership-move site.
// A move is where a managed value's +1 transfers to a new owner WITHOUT a refcount
// op — the inserter's `valueEscapes` chokepoint recognizes exactly three forms, and
// this mirrors them so the trace shows each transfer:
//   - body op that MOVES the value into a container/global/field (`mm_move ... -> container`)
//   - terminator that MOVES the value into a successor phi (`mm_move ... -> phi`)
//   - `ret` / `errorReturn` of the value (`mm_move ... -> return`)
// Pure instrumentation: queued via the same `queueInsertion`/`applyPlans` machinery
// as real refcount ops but with no refcount effect. Inserted BEFORE the moving op
// (at its position) so the trace line prints just before the transfer happens.
function planMoveTraces(ctx RcContext)
	for blockRef in ctx.func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try ctx.module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise continue
		var pos = 0
		for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
			let op = try ctx.module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise continue
			planMoveTraceForBodyOp(ctx, blockRef: blockRef, op: op, pos: pos)
			pos = pos + 1
		end 'eachOp'
		if block.hasTerminatorOp() 'hasTerm'
			planMoveTraceForTerminator(ctx, blockRef: blockRef, block: block)
		end 'hasTerm'
	end 'eachBlock'
end 'planMoveTraces'

// Queue an `mm_move ... -> container` for each managed operand this body op MOVES
// into a container/global/field (mirrors the `opMovesValueIntoContainer` move set).
function planMoveTraceForBodyOp(ctx RcContext, blockRef BlockRef, op StdOp, pos NodeIndex)
	var argId = 0
	while argId <= ctx.liveness.maxValueId 'eachArg'
		if ctx.isManaged(argId) and opMovesValueIntoContainer(ctx, op: op, argId: argId) 'moved'
			queueMoveTrace(ctx, blockRef: blockRef, pos: pos, valueId: argId, dest: MOVE_DEST_CONTAINER)
		end 'moved'
		argId = argId + 1
	end 'eachArg'
end 'planMoveTraceForBodyOp'

// Queue an `mm_move ... -> return` for a returned managed value, or `... -> phi`
// for a managed value carried into a successor phi, at the block's terminator. The
// matching `mm_scope_pop()` is appended separately by `emitScopePopsAtRets` (after
// applyPlans) so it lands strictly below this move.
function planMoveTraceForTerminator(ctx RcContext, blockRef BlockRef, block IrBlock)
	let term = try ctx.module.ops.get(block.terminatorIndex()) otherwise panic("planMoveTraceForTerminator: terminatorIndex not in module.ops")
	let opCount = block.opRefs.count()
	if let retValId = try returnedValueOfTerminator(term) 'isReturn'
		if ctx.isManaged(retValId) 'managed'
			queueMoveTrace(ctx, blockRef: blockRef, pos: opCount, valueId: retValId, dest: MOVE_DEST_RETURN)
			return
		end 'managed'
	end 'isReturn'
	// Phi move: any managed value carried into a successor block-arg phi.
	var vid = 0
	while vid <= ctx.liveness.maxValueId 'eachVal'
		if ctx.isManaged(vid) and valueMovedIntoAnyPhi(ctx, block: block, vid: vid) 'phiMove'
			queueMoveTrace(ctx, blockRef: blockRef, pos: opCount, valueId: vid, dest: MOVE_DEST_PHI)
		end 'phiMove'
		vid = vid + 1
	end 'eachVal'
end 'planMoveTraceForTerminator'

// mm-trace only: append `mm_scope_pop()` as the LAST body op of every `ret`/
// `errorReturn` block, balancing the function's entry `mm_scope_push`. Run AFTER
// `applyPlans` so the pop is guaranteed below all queued releases/moves at the
// terminator — the value's last-use drop/decref reads this frame (stack top), then
// the pop restores the caller's frame for whatever runs after (the inlined-into
// continuation). Appended directly (not queued) since it must be unconditionally
// last and applyPlans' position machinery can't express "after everything".
//
// Only functions that ALSO carry an entry `mm_scope_push` get a balancing pop: this
// per-function Std pass runs over the WHOLE module (user source + the linked stdlib
// runtime), but only user-source functions receive the entry push (emitted by
// `emitMmTraceScopePush` during `LowerMaxonToStd`, which never touches the precompiled
// stdlib). Popping at the rets of a push-less stdlib trace helper (e.g.
// `__mmTracePackedTag`) would net-pop the scope stack on every call, unwinding the
// caller's frames so every subsequent trace line reads the wrong (or empty) scope.
function emitScopePopsAtRets(ctx RcContext)
	if not ctx.mmTrace 'untraced'
		return
	end 'untraced'
	if not funcHasEntryScopePush(ctx) 'noEntryPush'
		return
	end 'noEntryPush'
	for blockRef in ctx.func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		var block = try ctx.module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise continue
		if not block.hasTerminatorOp() 'noTerm'
			continue
		end 'noTerm'
		let term = try ctx.module.ops.get(block.terminatorIndex()) otherwise continue
		if not isRetOrErrorReturnTerminator(term) 'notRet'
			continue
		end 'notRet'
		let resultId = allocValueId(ctx.idRef)
		let popOpIdx = ctx.module.ops.count()
		ctx.module.ops.push(StdOp.call(StdCallOp.call(resultId, callee: "mm_scope_pop", argIds: ValueIdArray.create())))
		block.opRefs.append(popOpIdx)
	end 'eachBlock'
end 'emitScopePopsAtRets'

// True iff the function's entry block contains a `mm_scope_push` call — i.e. it was
// lowered from user source with a scope frame and therefore needs a balancing pop at
// each ret. Precompiled stdlib functions never get the entry push, so they return
// false and `emitScopePopsAtRets` leaves them untouched (see its note).
function funcHasEntryScopePush(ctx RcContext) returns bool
	let entryBlock = try ctx.module.blocks.get(blockRefForId(ctx, blockId: ctx.entryBlockId)) otherwise return false
	for opIdx in entryBlock.opRefs 'eachOp'
		let op = try ctx.module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise continue
		if opIsCallToCallee(op, name: "mm_scope_push") 'isPush'
			return true
		end 'isPush'
	end 'eachOp'
	return false
end 'funcHasEntryScopePush'

// True iff `op` is a plain `call` whose callee is exactly `name`.
function opIsCallToCallee(op StdOp, name String) returns bool
	return match op 'dispatch'
		call(c) gives match c 'inner'
			call(_, callee, _) gives callee == name
			ret gives false
			tryCall to errorReturn gives false
		end 'inner'
		arith gives false
		control gives false
		memory gives false
		system gives false
	end 'dispatch'
end 'opIsCallToCallee'

// True iff `term` is a `ret` or `errorReturn` terminator.
function isRetOrErrorReturnTerminator(term StdOp) returns bool
	return match term 'dispatch'
		call(c) gives match c 'check'
			ret gives true
			errorReturn gives true
			call to param gives false
		end 'check'
		arith gives false
		control gives false
		memory gives false
		system gives false
	end 'dispatch'
end 'isRetOrErrorReturnTerminator'

// The returned ValueId of a `ret`/`errorReturn` terminator. THROWS
// `NotAReturnTerminator` for any other op rather than returning a sentinel:
// `ValueId` is unsigned (`0 to u64.max`), so there is no in-range "absent" value,
// and a sentinel forces callers into a dead `>= 0` guard. Callers use
// `try ... otherwise` to handle the non-return case explicitly.
function returnedValueOfTerminator(term StdOp) returns ValueId throws NotAReturnTerminator
	return match term 'dispatch'
		call(c) gives match c 'check'
			ret(retValId) gives retValId
			errorReturn(retValId, _) gives retValId
			default throws NotAReturnTerminator.notAReturn
		end 'check'
		default throws NotAReturnTerminator.notAReturn
	end 'dispatch'
end 'returnedValueOfTerminator'

// A terminator op that is not a value-returning `ret`/`errorReturn` — the
// throwing "absent" signal for `returnedValueOfTerminator`.
enum NotAReturnTerminator implements Error
	notAReturn
end 'NotAReturnTerminator'

// Move-destination codes for `mm_move(value, dest)` — must match the
// `__mm_move_trace` dest→literal mapping in stdlib/Internals.maxon
// (0 → ` -> return`, 1 → ` -> container`, 2 → ` -> phi`).
typealias MoveDestCode = int(0 to 2)

let MOVE_DEST_RETURN = 0 as MoveDestCode
let MOVE_DEST_CONTAINER = 1 as MoveDestCode
let MOVE_DEST_PHI = 2 as MoveDestCode

// Queue an `mm_move(value, dest)` trace-only marker — a no-runtime-effect line for
// an ownership MOVE (the value's +1 transfers to a new owner with no refcount op).
// Emits the runtime.std wrapper `mm_move` (bare name), seeded as a runtime-
// reachability root in BOTH link legs like `mm_drop`, so its `call __mm_move_trace`
// edge stays symmetric (cache parity) and the body DCEs to nothing in untraced
// builds. The `dest` immediate needs its own `const` op; BOTH must be inserted into
// the block (pushing the const to the op pool without a block placement leaves its
// result vreg with a def but no live range → SSA-coloring panic). Both are queued
// at the SAME `pos`: applyPlans inserts ties in reverse plan-order, so queuing the
// const THEN the call lands them as `const, call` (the call inserted first at `pos`,
// then the const inserted at `pos` pushes the call down). Using `pos`+`pos+1` would
// break — applyPlans inserts descending, so `pos+1` is applied while the const is
// not yet present (out-of-bounds at a terminator where pos == opCount). Callers gate
// on `ctx.mmTrace`.
function queueMoveTrace(ctx RcContext, blockRef BlockRef, pos NodeIndex, valueId ValueId, dest MoveDestCode)
	let resultId = allocValueId(ctx.idRef)
	var argIds = ValueIdArray.create()
	argIds.push(valueId)
	let callOpIdx = ctx.module.ops.count()
	ctx.module.ops.push(StdOp.call(StdCallOp.call(resultId, callee: moveTraceCallee(dest), argIds: argIds)))
	queueInsertion(ctx, blockRef: blockRef, pos: pos, opIdx: callOpIdx)
end 'queueMoveTrace'

// The runtime wrapper name for a move to `dest`. The destination is baked into the
// callee (mm_move_return/container/phi) rather than a runtime operand, so there is no
// `dest`-const ValueId to be misordered by regalloc at a branch terminator.
function moveTraceCallee(dest MoveDestCode) returns String
	return match dest 'pick'
		0 gives "mm_move_return"
		1 gives "mm_move_container"
		2 gives "mm_move_phi"
		default panic("moveTraceCallee: invalid dest {dest}")
	end 'pick'
end 'moveTraceCallee'

// Build a `sys.dropTypeParam` for a generic type-parameter value, threading the
// function's resolved implicit `__layout` descriptor ValueId. `ctx.layoutValueId`
// was resolved up front (gated on `funcHasDroppableTypeParam`); a type-param value
// reaching a release point always has a usable layout — a `RELEASE_NO_LAYOUT` here
// is an upstream contract violation (a type-param value in a function with no
// implicit layout param).
//
// Single-layout model: there is exactly one implicit layout slot, so every
// type-param value's drop routes through `ctx.layoutValueId` regardless of the
// value's recorded type-param name. (feature/roadmap's per-type-param multi-layout
// — routing a String-keyed map's int value through the int-array descriptor — is
// not ported on this branch.)
function buildDropTypeParamForValue(ctx RcContext, valueId ValueId) returns OpIndex
	if ctx.layoutValueId == RELEASE_NO_LAYOUT 'noLayout'
		panic("buildDropTypeParamForValue: value {valueId} of '{ctx.func.name}' is a type-parameter to release but the layout descriptor was not resolved (no implicit layout param)")
	end 'noLayout'
	// Route the drop through the value's PER-ARG heap-ref bit when its type
	// parameter resolves to an ordinal: `mm_drop_type_param_at` decrefs iff
	// `flags@24` bit `8 + ordinal` is set. The aggregate descriptor's
	// `destroyFunc` describes the INSTANCE (e.g. `__layout_destroy_Map_K_V`
	// reads three Map fields), so the old `sys.dropTypeParam` indirect call
	// only ever worked on elements whose shape coincided with the instance's
	// (single managed field at offset 0) and faulted otherwise (the
	// String-keyed `findSlot` key drop). Values with no recorded param name
	// keep the legacy aggregate path.
	let ordinal = typeParamOrdinalForValue(ctx, valueId: valueId)
	if ordinal >= 0 'perArg'
		return buildOrdinalLayoutCall(ctx, callee: "mm_drop_type_param_at", valueId: valueId, ordinal: ordinal as NodeIndex)
	end 'perArg'
	return buildDropTypeParamOp(ctx.module, valueId: valueId, layoutValueId: ctx.layoutValueId)
end 'buildDropTypeParamForValue'

// The per-arg heap-ref bit ordinal of `valueId`'s type parameter within the
// enclosing generic's declared order (`func.typeParamNames`), or -1 when the
// value carries no recorded param name or the name isn't in the list.
function typeParamOrdinalForValue(ctx RcContext, valueId ValueId) returns ParsedInt
	let name = ctx.func.valueTypeParamNameOf(valueId)
	if name.isEmpty() 'noName'
		return (-1)
	end 'noName'
	var idx = 0
	while idx < ctx.func.typeParamNames.count() 'each'
		let candidate = try ctx.func.typeParamNames.get(idx) otherwise panic("typeParamOrdinalForValue: typeParamNames.get({idx}) OOB despite idx < count")
		if candidate == name 'hit'
			return idx
		end 'hit'
		idx = idx + 1
	end 'each'
	return (-1)
end 'typeParamOrdinalForValue'

// Build a `callee(value, layout, ordinalConst)` runtime call (the per-arg
// drop/retain forms). The ordinal constant is minted once per function in the
// entry block (`ordinalConstId`) and shared by every per-ordinal call.
function buildOrdinalLayoutCall(ctx RcContext, callee String, valueId ValueId, ordinal NodeIndex) returns OpIndex
	let ordConstId = ordinalConstId(ctx, ordinal: ordinal)
	let resultId = allocValueId(ctx.idRef)
	var argIds = ValueIdArray.create()
	argIds.push(valueId)
	argIds.push(ctx.layoutValueId)
	argIds.push(ordConstId)
	let opIdx = ctx.module.ops.count()
	ctx.module.ops.push(StdOp.call(StdCallOp.call(resultId, callee: callee, argIds: argIds)))
	return opIdx
end 'buildOrdinalLayoutCall'

// The entry-block `constI64` ValueId for `ordinal`, minted on first request.
// Only the ID is minted here — the const OP itself is materialized at the
// entry-block head by `flushOrdinalConsts` at the very end of insertion,
// because per-ordinal drop/retain calls are built BOTH at plan time and at
// `applyEdgeReleases` time (after `applyPlans`), so a queued insertion would
// never apply for the edge-built ones.
function ordinalConstId(ctx RcContext, ordinal NodeIndex) returns ValueId
	while ctx.ordinalConstIds.count() <= ordinal 'grow'
		ctx.ordinalConstIds.push(REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE)
	end 'grow'
	let existing = try ctx.ordinalConstIds.get(ordinal) otherwise panic("ordinalConstId: get({ordinal}) OOB after grow")
	if existing != REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE 'cached'
		return existing
	end 'cached'

	let resultId = allocValueId(ctx.idRef)
	try ctx.ordinalConstIds.set(ordinal, value: resultId) otherwise panic("ordinalConstId: set({ordinal}) OOB after grow")
	return resultId
end 'ordinalConstId'

// Materialize the lazily-minted per-ordinal `constI64` ops at the entry-block
// head, AFTER the leading `func.param` ops (the inliner's arg binding and the
// backend's param materialization both expect params to be entry's first
// ops). Runs LAST (after `applyEdgeReleases`): every drop/retain call that
// references these ids is already in place, and a direct insertion cannot
// disturb plan positions (all plans are applied). The entry head dominates
// every use.
function flushOrdinalConsts(ctx RcContext)
	var hasMinted = false
	for cid in ctx.ordinalConstIds 'scan'
		if cid != REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE 'minted'
			hasMinted = true
		end 'minted'
	end 'scan'
	if not hasMinted 'nothing'
		return
	end 'nothing'

	let entryBlock = try ctx.module.blocks.get(blockRefForId(ctx, blockId: ctx.entryBlockId)) otherwise panic("flushOrdinalConsts: entry blockRef not in module.blocks")
	var insertAt = 0
	while insertAt < entryBlock.opRefs.count() 'skipParams'
		let opIdx = try entryBlock.opRefs.get(insertAt) otherwise panic("flushOrdinalConsts: opRefs.get({insertAt}) OOB despite insertAt < count")
		let op = try ctx.module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("flushOrdinalConsts: opIdx not in module.ops")
		if not opIsFuncParam(op) 'pastParams'
			break
		end 'pastParams'
		insertAt = insertAt + 1
	end 'skipParams'

	var ordinal = 0
	while ordinal < ctx.ordinalConstIds.count() 'each'
		let cid = try ctx.ordinalConstIds.get(ordinal) otherwise panic("flushOrdinalConsts: get({ordinal}) OOB despite ordinal < count")
		if cid != REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE 'minted'
			let opIdx = ctx.module.ops.count()
			ctx.module.ops.push(StdOp.arith(StdArithOp.const(StdArithConst.create(StdArithConstOpcode.constI64, resultId: cid, value: ordinal as ParsedInt))))
			try entryBlock.opRefs.insert(insertAt, value: opIdx) otherwise panic("flushOrdinalConsts: entry opRefs.insert({insertAt}) failed")
		end 'minted'
		ordinal = ordinal + 1
	end 'each'
end 'flushOrdinalConsts'

function opIsFuncParam(op StdOp) returns bool
	return match op 'dispatch'
		call(c) gives callIsFuncParam(c)
		arith gives false
		control gives false
		memory gives false
		system gives false
	end 'dispatch'
end 'opIsFuncParam'

function callIsFuncParam(c StdCallOp) returns bool
	return match c 'check'
		param gives true
		call to funcRef gives false
		ret gives false
		tailCall gives false
		errorReturn gives false
	end 'check'
end 'callIsFuncParam'

// Build the right retain op for a value a container/return must take its own
// reference to: a CONCRETE managed pointer increfs directly; a type-param value
// with a resolved ordinal routes through its per-arg heap-ref bit
// (`mm_retain_type_param_at`); a type-param value with no recorded name falls
// back to the aggregate-bit `mm_retain_type_param` (status quo).
function buildRetainForValue(ctx RcContext, valueId ValueId) returns OpIndex
	if ctx.isManaged(valueId) 'concreteManaged'
		return buildIncrefOp(ctx.module, valueId: valueId, idRef: ctx.idRef)
	end 'concreteManaged'
	let ordinal = typeParamOrdinalForValue(ctx, valueId: valueId)
	if ordinal >= 0 'perArg'
		return buildOrdinalLayoutCall(ctx, callee: "mm_retain_type_param_at", valueId: valueId, ordinal: ordinal as NodeIndex)
	end 'perArg'
	return buildRetainTypeParamCall(ctx.module, valueId: valueId, layoutValueId: ctx.layoutValueId, idRef: ctx.idRef)
end 'buildRetainForValue'

// A value that may legitimately be null at the release point uses the
// null-guarded decref. Merged phis and selfReturnBorrow values can be null on
// some path (an undefined / not-yet-stored edge feeds the phi the synthetic
// zero); a freshly-allocated freshRc0 / a callReturnRc1 are provably non-null.
function releaseIsNullGuarded(ctx RcContext, id ValueId) returns bool
	return match ctx.classOf(id) 'class'
		incomingOwner gives true
		selfReturnBorrow gives true
		freshRc0 gives false
		// A call result may be a LEGITIMATE null on a documented miss path —
		// `__Builtins.subprocessResolveOnPath` (unresolvable name) and
		// `__managed_file_wrap` (failed open) return exactly 0. The guard
		// tolerates ONLY exact 0 (`__mm_decref_maybenull_helper`); a garbage
		// non-null pointer still faults loudly inside the strict decref it
		// routes to, so the strict-decref debugging contract is preserved.
		callReturnRc1 gives true
		borrowed gives false
		notManaged gives false
	end 'class'
end 'releaseIsNullGuarded'

// In-block deaths: scan the block's per-op-position liveness for values whose
// last use is a body op (live before, dead after) and that are NOT live-out.
function planInBlockDeaths(ctx RcContext, blockRef BlockRef, block IrBlock)
	let liveAfter = computeBlockLiveAfter(ctx.module, block: block, liveness: ctx.liveness)
	let opCount = block.opRefs.count()

	var pos = 0
	while pos < opCount 'eachOp'
		let opIdx = try block.opRefs.get(pos) otherwise panic("planInBlockDeaths: opRefs.get({pos}) failed despite pos < count")
		let op = try ctx.module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("planInBlockDeaths: opIdx not in module.ops")
		let operands = extractStdOpOperands(op)
		// A value dies at this op iff it is read here, live BEFORE this op, and
		// not live AFTER it. Each read operand is a death candidate — and so is
		// the BASE of any interior pointer read here (`expandReadsWithBorrows`):
		// an op reading a pointer borrowed out of a managed base is where that
		// base's extended last use can fall, so the base's decref lands AFTER the
		// borrow's last read, not at the (earlier) load. Without this the base's
		// extended death — no longer a syntactic operand of this op — would be
		// invisible to the inserter and never released (a leak), or, with the old
		// non-extended liveness, released too early (the UAF this fixes).
		let candidates = expandReadsWithBorrows(operands.readIds, borrows: ctx.liveness.borrows)
		// A value can appear MORE THAN ONCE in `candidates` — as a direct read AND
		// as the borrow base of an interior pointer read at the SAME op (e.g.
		// `print(s)` reads `s` and `s.buffer` which borrows from `s`). Each death
		// point must emit at most ONE release, so dedupe per-op: a value released
		// once here is not released again for a duplicate occurrence. Without this,
		// a managed value used both directly and as a borrow base at its last use
		// is decref'd TWICE → over-free / double-free crash (the file-io / map
		// String double-free that Fix-1's managed-String classification exposed).
		var releasedHere = ValueIdArray.create()
		for useId in candidates 'eachUse'
			if not valueIdArrayContains(releasedHere, vid: useId) 'notYetReleased'
				if isInBlockDeathPoint(ctx, block: block, liveAfter: liveAfter, pos: pos, useId: useId) 'dies'
					logTrace(LogCategory.ir, message: function() gives "RC-LASTUSE func={ctx.func.name} val=%{useId} atpos={pos} class={ownershipClassName(ctx.classOf(useId))} kind={releaseKindName(releaseKindAtLastUse(ctx, id: useId))}")
					let relIdx = buildReleaseOp(ctx, id: useId)
					// A tryCall RESULT that dies inside the tryCall's OWN block (the
					// `if let x = try f() else (e) … x …` shape, where the bound value is
					// consumed-and-dropped before/within the error-flag branch) must NOT be
					// decref'd in this block: on the THROW path the result register holds
					// garbage (the dual-value error ABI zeroed/clobbered it), so an
					// unconditional decref here faults (addr=-8, the tcp/http error-path
					// crash). Route the release to the head of the SUCCESS block (the
					// error-flag condBr's ELSE target), mirroring the def-acquire and
					// dead-def-drop success-block placement.
					let inBlockSuccessId = tryCallResultSuccessBlock(ctx, block: block, resultId: useId)
					if inBlockSuccessId != REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE 'tryResultDies'
						queueInsertion(ctx, blockRef: blockRefForId(ctx, blockId: inBlockSuccessId), pos: 0, opIdx: relIdx)
					end 'tryResultDies' else 'normalDeath'
						queueInsertion(ctx, blockRef: blockRef, pos: pos + 1, opIdx: relIdx)
					end 'normalDeath'
					releasedHere.push(useId)
				end 'dies'
			end 'notYetReleased'
		end 'eachUse'
		pos = pos + 1
	end 'eachOp'
end 'planInBlockDeaths'

function isInBlockDeathPoint(ctx RcContext, block IrBlock, liveAfter StdLiveAfter, pos NodeIndex, useId ValueId) returns bool
	if not shouldReleaseAtLastUse(ctx, id: useId) 'skip'
		return false
	end 'skip'
	// V escapes the block — its death is on an out-edge, handled by
	// planEdgeDeaths, not here.
	if ctx.liveness.liveOutContains(block.id, vid: useId) 'escapes'
		return false
	end 'escapes'
	// Last use within the block: live before this op, dead after it.
	if not liveAfter.isLiveBeforeBodyOp(pos, vid: useId) 'notLiveBefore'
		return false
	end 'notLiveBefore'
	if liveAfter.isLiveAfterBodyOp(pos, vid: useId) 'stillLiveAfter'
		return false
	end 'stillLiveAfter'
	// MOVE guard (Concept B): the guards above already proved this op is V's LAST
	// use (live-before, dead-after, not live-out) — exactly the transfer condition.
	// So ANY op-keyed move disposition here is a transfer the local release must be
	// suppressed for: a move into a heap container / global / type-param sink
	// (released by the CONTAINER's destructor), AND the plain heap-FIELD store
	// (`moveIntoHeapField` — the field becomes owner-of-record, the Set/Map `init`
	// over-free). Releasing here would free the value out from under its new owner
	// (double-free / UAF). `shouldReleaseAtLastUse` already excluded params /
	// notManaged, and a type-param store is caught as `moveIntoTypeParamSink`, so the
	// single dispatcher funnel subsumes both the former container-move guard and the
	// separate managed-field-transfer recognizer.
	let opIdx = try block.opRefs.get(pos) otherwise panic("isInBlockDeathPoint: opRefs.get({pos}) failed despite pos < count")
	let op = try ctx.module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("isInBlockDeathPoint: opIdx not in module.ops")
	if opTransfersOperand(ctx, op: op, argId: useId) 'movedAway'
		return false
	end 'movedAway'

	// CONSUMED-EARLIER guard: conservative borrow tracking can extend V's
	// liveness PAST the op that unconditionally MOVED its +1 away — an
	// integer-width field load of V is indistinguishable from an interior
	// pointer, so a later use of that loaded scalar pushes V's death point past
	// a consuming `Array.push(.., V, ..)`. At the death point V's +1 is already
	// the container's; releasing strips the container's reference (the
	// driftsort `newRun` double-release: `push(stack, newRun)` followed by an
	// `addi` reading newRun's previously-loaded length field). Only the
	// UNCONDITIONAL consume kinds suppress here — the last-use-gated kinds
	// (field/global/addr-taken-slot stores) took their own +1 via store-incref
	// when V stayed live, so V's own release is still owed. A consume site that
	// minted a COPY-incref (`planConsumedArgCopyIncrefs` — the value has a
	// direct later read) does NOT suppress either: the copy balances the
	// consume, so the death-point release of the original +1 is owed.
	if valueConsumedEarlierInBlock(ctx, block: block, liveAfter: liveAfter, beforePos: pos, vid: useId) 'consumedEarlier'
		logTrace(LogCategory.ir, message: function() gives "RC-LASTUSE-CONSUMED-SUPPRESS func={ctx.func.name} val=%{useId} atpos={pos} (unconditional move earlier in block)")
		return false
	end 'consumedEarlier'
	return true
end 'isInBlockDeathPoint'

// True iff an op at a position strictly before `beforePos` in `block`
// UNCONDITIONALLY consumed `vid`'s +1 — a container-mutator arg, an intrinsic
// consumer, a transparent wrap, or a type-param sink — WITHOUT a copy-incref
// minted at that site. These callees store the value regardless of the caller's
// liveness, so the +1 is gone no matter where the death point lands. A consume
// site that DID mint a copy (`consumedArgNeedsCopyIncref` — the value has a
// direct later read) handed the callee the minted +1 instead; the original is
// still owed its death-point release, so it does not suppress.
function valueConsumedEarlierInBlock(ctx RcContext, block IrBlock, liveAfter StdLiveAfter, beforePos NodeIndex, vid ValueId) returns bool
	var p = 0
	while p < beforePos 'scan'
		let earlierIdx = try block.opRefs.get(p) otherwise panic("valueConsumedEarlierInBlock: opRefs.get({p}) failed despite p < beforePos")
		let earlierOp = try ctx.module.ops.get(earlierIdx) otherwise panic("valueConsumedEarlierInBlock: opIdx not in module.ops")
		if opUnconditionallyConsumesOperand(ctx, op: earlierOp, argId: vid) 'consumed'
			return not consumedArgRetainedPastOp(ctx, liveAfter: liveAfter, block: block, pos: p, argId: vid)
		end 'consumed'
		p = p + 1
	end 'scan'
	return false
end 'valueConsumedEarlierInBlock'

// The UNCONDITIONAL subset of `opTransferDisposition`'s move kinds: ones whose
// consume does not depend on the op being the value's last use.
function opUnconditionallyConsumesOperand(ctx RcContext, op StdOp, argId ValueId) returns bool
	return match opTransferDisposition(ctx, op: op, argId: argId) 'disp'
		moveIntoContainerArg gives true
		moveIntoIntrinsicConsumer gives true
		moveIntoTransparentWrap gives true
		moveIntoTypeParamSink gives true
		moveIntoGlobal gives false
		moveIntoHeapField gives false
		moveIntoAddressTakenSlot gives false
		localRelease gives false
		returnTransfer gives false
		moveIntoPhi gives false
	end 'disp'
end 'opUnconditionallyConsumesOperand'

// True iff `op` MOVES `argId` into a container that then owns it (so the
// inserter must not also release it locally). The set of moving ops differs by
// the value's refcount domain:
//   - MANAGED value: only the `mrt_managed_list_*` value-taking helpers move it
//     here (their runtime bodies link the pointer in WITHOUT increfing). A plain
//     `store_indirect` of a managed value into a heap struct field is NOT handled
//     here — it is the field-transfer move, recognized at the use site by
//     `isInBlockDeathPoint` (`opStoresValueIntoNonGlobalHeapField`) ONLY when the
//     store is the value's last use, with the matching store-incref suppression in
//     `planManagedHeapStore`'s `fieldTransfer` branch. (Splitting it out keeps the
//     liveness gate at the death point, where last-use is already proven, rather
//     than in this op-only predicate which `valueEscapes` also calls un-gated.)
//   - TYPE-PARAMETER value (released via `dropTypeParam`): the inserter never
//     increfs it, so ANY transfer of it into container memory is a pure move —
//     a `store_indirect` of it into a heap struct/tuple/element, OR a
//     managed-memory / list runtime helper (`mrt_managed_memory_set`,
//     `mrt_managed_list_*`) that stores it. The container's destructor (or the
//     enclosing generic destructor) performs the matching `dropTypeParam`.
// CONCEPT B — the single op-keyed decision surface. Returns the
// `TransferDisposition` for `argId` at the body op `op`: the ONE place that decides
// "is this op a move of this operand, and if so, what kind?". Every op-keyed move
// reason is enumerated here exactly once; the value-global / edge-keyed shapes
// (`returnTransfer`, `moveIntoPhi`) are recognized at their own sites. Checked in a
// fixed reason order; the first match wins.
//
//   - MODULE-GLOBAL store: `store_indirect [global_addr @__data_* + _] = argId`
//     transfers `argId` into the long-lived global (owner-of-record). The store
//     does NOT incref, so the value's local +1 IS the global's reference — a
//     last-use release here would drive the global's occupant to rc=0 mid-init.
//   - INTRINSIC CONSUMER: a runtime helper (`mrt_managed_list_*_value`,
//     `__managed_mem_set`) that re-homes the LAST arg into a container without
//     increfing; the container's destructor performs the matching decref.
//   - TYPE-PARAMETER SINK: the inserter never increfs a type-param value, so ANY
//     store/box/call hand-off is a conservative move (matching `dropTypeParam`
//     performed by the retainer). Type-param values dispatch here exclusively.
//   - CONTAINER MUTATOR arg: a concrete managed value at a non-self position of a
//     generic mutator (`Array.push`/`Map.set`/`Set.insert`/...) binds a
//     type-parameter param the callee consumes (moves into storage via the
//     type-param-move chain). The receiver (`self`, arg 0) is NOT consumed.
//   - TRANSPARENT WRAPPER arg: the wrapped arg 0 of `Array.init`/`Vector.init` is
//     moved into the result that aliases it (no alloc, no incref).
//   - HEAP FIELD store: a plain `store_indirect` of `argId` into a non-global heap
//     field. Reported LAST so the more specific store reasons (global / intrinsic)
//     win first. This reason is acquire-analysis-only at the op level; the release
//     suppression applies it only when the store is the value's LAST use (see the
//     `opMovesValueIntoContainer` view, which EXCLUDES it).
function opTransferDisposition(ctx RcContext, op StdOp, argId ValueId) returns TransferDisposition
	if opStoresValueIntoModuleGlobal(ctx, op: op, argId: argId) 'globalMove'
		return TransferDisposition.moveIntoGlobal
	end 'globalMove'
	if opMovesArgIntoContainer(ctx, op: op, argId: argId) 'intrinsicMove'
		return TransferDisposition.moveIntoIntrinsicConsumer
	end 'intrinsicMove'
	if ctx.isTypeParam(argId) 'typeParam'
		return (TransferDisposition.moveIntoTypeParamSink if opMovesTypeParamIntoContainer(op, argId: argId) else TransferDisposition.localRelease)
	end 'typeParam'
	if callConsumesManagedElement(ctx.funcParamConsumes, op: op, argId: argId) 'containerArg'
		return TransferDisposition.moveIntoContainerArg
	end 'containerArg'
	if callTransparentlyWrapsArg(ctx, op: op, argId: argId) 'transparentWrap'
		return TransferDisposition.moveIntoTransparentWrap
	end 'transparentWrap'
	if opStoresValueIntoNonGlobalHeapField(ctx, op: op, argId: argId) 'heapField'
		return TransferDisposition.moveIntoHeapField
	end 'heapField'
	// ADDRESS-TAKEN SLOT store: a `storeSlot` of `argId` into a stack slot whose
	// address was captured into a closure env (pinned in memory by mem2reg). The slot
	// becomes owner-of-record — the closure reads the value BY REFERENCE through the
	// env AFTER this store, so the value must outlive this store. Last-use-gated like
	// the heap-field store; `planAddressTakenSlotDrops` releases the slot's content at
	// the function's scope exit.
	if opStoresValueIntoAddressTakenSlot(ctx, op: op, argId: argId) 'addrTakenSlot'
		return TransferDisposition.moveIntoAddressTakenSlot
	end 'addrTakenSlot'
	return TransferDisposition.localRelease
end 'opTransferDisposition'

// True iff `op` is a `storeSlot(slot, argId)` whose `slot` is ADDRESS-TAKEN (its
// address was captured into a closure env via a `sys.stack_addr`). The stored value
// becomes owned by the slot (released at scope exit by `planAddressTakenSlotDrops`),
// not at this store.
function opStoresValueIntoAddressTakenSlot(ctx RcContext, op StdOp, argId ValueId) returns bool
	return match op 'dispatch'
		memory(m) gives memStoresValueIntoAddressTakenSlot(ctx, m: m, argId: argId)
		arith gives false
		control gives false
		call gives false
		system gives false
	end 'dispatch'
end 'opStoresValueIntoAddressTakenSlot'

function memStoresValueIntoAddressTakenSlot(ctx RcContext, m StdMemoryOp, argId ValueId) returns bool
	return match m 'check'
		storeSlot(slotId, valueId) gives valueId == argId and ctx.isAddressTakenSlot(slotId)
		loadSlot gives false
	end 'check'
end 'memStoresValueIntoAddressTakenSlot'

// View over Concept B: `op` MOVES `argId` into a durable owner such that the
// inserter must NOT also release it locally at THIS op — every op-keyed move reason
// EXCEPT the plain heap-field store. The field store is excluded here because it is
// the last-use-GATED field transfer, recognized at the death point by
// `isInBlockDeathPoint` (where last-use is already proven) with the matching
// store-incref suppression in `planManagedHeapStore`'s `fieldTransfer` branch —
// keeping the liveness gate at the death point rather than in this op-only predicate
// which `valueEscapes` also calls un-gated. (The full transfer set, including the
// field store, is `markOpTransferredOperands` for the acquire analysis.)
function opMovesValueIntoContainer(ctx RcContext, op StdOp, argId ValueId) returns bool
	return match opTransferDisposition(ctx, op: op, argId: argId) 'disp'
		moveIntoGlobal gives true
		moveIntoIntrinsicConsumer gives true
		moveIntoTypeParamSink gives true
		moveIntoContainerArg gives true
		moveIntoTransparentWrap gives true
		moveIntoHeapField gives false
		moveIntoAddressTakenSlot gives false
		localRelease gives false
		returnTransfer gives false
		moveIntoPhi gives false
	end 'disp'
end 'opMovesValueIntoContainer'

// True iff `op` is a call that CONSUMES `argId` at its FIRST argument position (arg
// 0) — the wrapped-value slot of a transparent wrapper (`Array.init`/`Vector.init`'s
// `managed`) or any static factory that moves arg 0 into the value it builds. The
// wrapped value is moved into the result (which aliases it). This is the arg-0
// counterpart of `calleeConsumesArg` (which guards out position 0, since for INSTANCE
// methods arg 0 is the borrowed `self`); a STATIC factory's arg 0 is a real
// consumed parameter, so it is handled here. The layout/witness trailing args are
// non-managed and never reach this check as a release candidate.
//
// AUTHORITATIVE signal: `funcParamConsumes[callee][0]` (the structural consume bit
// for arg 0, computed by `analyzeParamConsumes`).
function callTransparentlyWrapsArg(ctx RcContext, op StdOp, argId ValueId) returns bool
	return match op 'dispatch'
		call(c) gives callTransparentWrapsArgId(ctx, c: c, argId: argId)
		arith gives false
		control gives false
		memory gives false
		system gives false
	end 'dispatch'
end 'callTransparentlyWrapsArg'

function callTransparentWrapsArgId(ctx RcContext, c StdCallOp, argId ValueId) returns bool
	return match c 'check'
		call(_, callee, argIds) gives calleeConsumesFirstArg(ctx, callee: callee, argIds: argIds, argId: argId)
		tryCall(_, callee, argIds, _) gives calleeConsumesFirstArg(ctx, callee: callee, argIds: argIds, argId: argId)
		ret gives false
		indirectCall to errorReturn gives false
	end 'check'
end 'callTransparentWrapsArgId'

// CONCEPT C — is `argId` the consumed FIRST argument (arg 0) of `callee`? Read the
// structural `funcParamConsumes` bit at position 0 (a static factory / transparent
// wrapper that moves arg 0 into the value it builds). This replaced the
// `calleeTransparentlyWrapsArg` name list.
function calleeConsumesFirstArg(ctx RcContext, callee String, argIds ValueIdArray, argId ValueId) returns bool
	if not isFirstArg(argIds, vid: argId) 'notFirst'
		return false
	end 'notFirst'
	return paramConsumeBit(ctx.funcParamConsumes, callee: callee, argIndex: 0)
end 'calleeConsumesFirstArg'

// True iff `vid` is the FIRST argument in `argIds` — the wrapped value's position
// in a transparent-wrapper `init(managed, layout...)`.
function isFirstArg(argIds ValueIdArray, vid ValueId) returns bool
	let first = try argIds.get(0) otherwise return false
	return first == vid
end 'isFirstArg'

// True iff `op` is a `store_indirect` of `argId` (as the STORED value) through a
// module-global address (`sys.global_addr @__data_*`). This is the ownership
// MOVE into a long-lived module global — the store transfers `argId`'s +1 to the
// global, so the inserter must NOT release `argId` at its last use. `argId` must
// be the VALUE being stored, not the address: a store's address operand is the
// `global_addr` result (non-managed), so it is never a release candidate reaching
// this check, but the `valueId == argId` guard makes the value/address
// distinction explicit and total.
function opStoresValueIntoModuleGlobal(ctx RcContext, op StdOp, argId ValueId) returns bool
	return match op 'dispatch'
		system(s) gives sysStoresValueIntoModuleGlobal(ctx, s: s, argId: argId)
		arith gives false
		control gives false
		call gives false
		memory gives false
	end 'dispatch'
end 'opStoresValueIntoModuleGlobal'

function sysStoresValueIntoModuleGlobal(ctx RcContext, s StdSystemOp, argId ValueId) returns bool
	return match s 'check'
		storeIndirect(addrId, _, valueId, _, _) gives valueId == argId and ctx.isModuleGlobalAddr(addrId)
		globalAddr to loadByte gives false
		osExit to osWrite gives false
		free gives false
		osWriteErr to loadFramePtr gives false
		loadIndirect gives false
		funcAddr gives false
		drop gives false
		osAllocPages to osDirMkdir gives false
		atomicInc to osLockRelease gives false
		boxValue to dropTypeParam gives false
	end 'check'
end 'sysStoresValueIntoModuleGlobal'

// True iff `op` is a `store_indirect` whose STORED VALUE is `argId` and whose base
// is NOT a module global — i.e. a plain store of the value into a NON-global heap
// struct field. The complement of `opStoresValueIntoModuleGlobal` on the stored-
// value axis: a managed value's last-use store into such a field TRANSFERS the
// value's reference into the field (the field becomes owner-of-record, released by
// the container's destructor at rc→0), mirroring the module-global transfer. The
// address operand is excluded (only the stored value gains an owner). Locals are
// mem2reg-promoted away, so any surviving `store_indirect` writes heap memory.
function opStoresValueIntoNonGlobalHeapField(ctx RcContext, op StdOp, argId ValueId) returns bool
	return match op 'dispatch'
		system(s) gives sysStoresValueIntoNonGlobalHeapField(ctx, s: s, argId: argId)
		arith gives false
		control gives false
		call gives false
		memory gives false
	end 'dispatch'
end 'opStoresValueIntoNonGlobalHeapField'

function sysStoresValueIntoNonGlobalHeapField(ctx RcContext, s StdSystemOp, argId ValueId) returns bool
	return match s 'check'
		storeIndirect(addrId, _, valueId, _, _) gives valueId == argId and not ctx.isModuleGlobalAddr(addrId)
		globalAddr to loadByte gives false
		osExit to osWrite gives false
		free gives false
		osWriteErr to loadFramePtr gives false
		loadIndirect gives false
		funcAddr gives false
		drop gives false
		osAllocPages to osDirMkdir gives false
		atomicInc to osLockRelease gives false
		boxValue to dropTypeParam gives false
	end 'check'
end 'sysStoresValueIntoNonGlobalHeapField'

// True iff `op` is a call whose parameter for `argId` CONSUMES it — a generic
// container MUTATOR (`Array.push`/`Map.set`/`Set.insert`/...) or any callee that moves
// `argId` into durable storage, per the structural `funcParamConsumes` bit. See the
// move rationale in `opTransferDisposition`.
module function callConsumesManagedElement(funcParamConsumes FuncParamConsumesMap, op StdOp, argId ValueId) returns bool
	return match op 'dispatch'
		call(c) gives callConsumesElement(funcParamConsumes, c: c, argId: argId)
		arith gives false
		control gives false
		memory gives false
		system gives false
	end 'dispatch'
end 'callConsumesManagedElement'

function callConsumesElement(funcParamConsumes FuncParamConsumesMap, c StdCallOp, argId ValueId) returns bool
	return match c 'check'
		call(_, callee, argIds) gives calleeConsumesArg(funcParamConsumes, callee: callee, argIds: argIds, argId: argId)
		tryCall(_, callee, argIds, _) gives calleeConsumesArg(funcParamConsumes, callee: callee, argIds: argIds, argId: argId)
		ret gives false
		indirectCall to errorReturn gives false
	end 'check'
end 'callConsumesElement'

// CONCEPT C — decide whether `callee` consumes `argId` (at its position in
// `argIds`). The signal is the structural `funcParamConsumes` bit computed by
// `analyzeParamConsumes` — does the callee body MOVE this arg position into durable
// storage WITHOUT increfing (vs. BORROW it for a read like `Map.get`/`Set.contains`,
// or RETAIN it like an iterator capturing its source)? This replaced the three
// hand-synced callee-NAME allowlists (`isConsumingContainerMutator` + the structural
// type-param-position test, `calleeMovesValue`, `calleeTransparentlyWrapsArg`) — every
// new stdlib container method was a latent double-free / leak until someone edited a
// string list. The fact is now computed once from each callee's body and persisted in
// the stdlib cache, so a non-inlined consuming callee reads the real bit. Self (index
// 0) is the borrowed receiver for an instance method; a STATIC factory's consumed arg
// 0 is recognized separately by `calleeConsumesFirstArg`.
function calleeConsumesArg(funcParamConsumes FuncParamConsumesMap, callee String, argIds ValueIdArray, argId ValueId) returns bool
	let argIndex = argPositionOf(argIds, vid: argId)
	if argIndex == 0 'selfOrAbsent'
		return false
	end 'selfOrAbsent'
	return paramConsumeBit(funcParamConsumes, callee: callee, argIndex: argIndex)
end 'calleeConsumesArg'

// The structural consume bit for `callee`'s parameter at `argIndex`, or false if no
// consume info was recorded (a callee the analysis never saw / a non-consuming arg).
function paramConsumeBit(funcParamConsumes FuncParamConsumesMap, callee String, argIndex NodeIndex) returns bool
	let bits = try funcParamConsumes.get(callee) otherwise return false
	return try bits.get(argIndex) otherwise false
end 'paramConsumeBit'

// The position (>= 1) of `vid` in `argIds` at any non-self slot, or 0 if `vid` is
// the receiver (index 0) / absent. The element/key/value args of a container
// mutator are all at index >= 1; the receiver at index 0 is owned by the caller. A
// descriptor (layout/witness) arg is non-managed, so it is never a release
// candidate reaching this check.
function argPositionOf(argIds ValueIdArray, vid ValueId) returns NodeIndex
	var idx = 1
	while idx < argIds.count() 'each'
		let aid = try argIds.get(idx) otherwise panic("argPositionOf: argIds.get({idx}) OOB despite idx < count")
		if aid == vid 'hit'
			return idx
		end 'hit'
		idx = idx + 1
	end 'each'
	return 0
end 'argPositionOf'

// CONSERVATIVE move detection for a TYPE-PARAMETER value: because the inserter
// never increfs a type-param value, ANY op that could hand its bytes off to be
// retained elsewhere is treated as a move (the value is then destroyed by the
// retainer — a container destructor, a callee, or the generic destructor —
// never by a local `dropTypeParam`). The conservative bias matters: a missed
// move would DOUBLE-FREE (rc<0 / UAF, undetectable by the leak gate), whereas an
// over-suppression merely LEAKS (rc>0, caught by the gate and recoverable). So
// we suppress the local drop whenever the last use is:
//   - a `store_indirect` of the value (into heap struct/tuple/element storage),
//   - a `box_value` of the value (boxed into heap storage), or
//   - ANY call passing the value as an argument (the callee may store it into a
//     container — e.g. `__managed_mem_set`, the `mrt_managed_list_*` inserters,
//     or any generic helper that re-homes its argument).
// Only a pure compute/compare last use (arith, or a system op that provably does
// not store the value) leaves the local `dropTypeParam` in place — the genuine
// load → use → discard generic-local case.
function opMovesTypeParamIntoContainer(op StdOp, argId ValueId) returns bool
	return match op 'dispatch'
		system(s) gives sysRetainsValue(s, argId: argId)
		call(c) gives callTakesValueArg(c, argId: argId)
		arith gives false
		control gives false
		memory gives false
	end 'dispatch'
end 'opMovesTypeParamIntoContainer'

function sysRetainsValue(s StdSystemOp, argId ValueId) returns bool
	return match s 'check'
		storeIndirect(_, _, valueId, _, _) gives valueId == argId
		boxValue(_, valueId, _) gives valueId == argId
		globalAddr to loadByte gives false
		osExit to osWrite gives false
		free gives false
		osWriteErr to loadFramePtr gives false
		loadIndirect gives false
		funcAddr gives false
		drop gives false
		osAllocPages to osDirMkdir gives false
		atomicInc to osLockRelease gives false
		unboxValue gives false
		loadLayoutDescriptor to dropTypeParam gives false
	end 'check'
end 'sysRetainsValue'

// Any call that passes the value as an argument is a potential move of a
// type-param value (the callee may store it into a container). Conservative —
// see `opMovesTypeParamIntoContainer`.
function callTakesValueArg(c StdCallOp, argId ValueId) returns bool
	return match c 'check'
		call(_, _, argIds) gives valueIdArrayContains(argIds, vid: argId)
		tryCall(_, _, argIds, _) gives valueIdArrayContains(argIds, vid: argId)
		indirectCall(_, _, argIds, _, _, _) gives valueIdArrayContains(argIds, vid: argId)
		witnessCall(_, _, _, _, argIds) gives valueIdArrayContains(argIds, vid: argId)
		witnessTryCall(_, _, _, _, argIds, _) gives valueIdArrayContains(argIds, vid: argId)
		tailCall(_, argIds) gives valueIdArrayContains(argIds, vid: argId)
		ret gives false
		funcRef gives false
		param gives false
		errorReturn gives false
	end 'check'
end 'callTakesValueArg'

// True iff `op` is a call to a runtime helper that MOVES a managed argument into a
// heap container it retains (storing the pointer without an incref), and `argId` is
// that argument. Such an argument is consumed (its +1 transfers to the container)
// rather than borrowed — the inserter must not release it.
//
// AUTHORITATIVE signal: the structural `funcParamConsumes` bit (the runtime helpers
// are SEEDED as intrinsic leaf-consumers of their value param by
// `analyzeParamConsumes`, since their slot-form runtime.std bodies are not in the
// analyzed module). This replaced the `calleeMovesValue` name-list allowlist.
function opMovesArgIntoContainer(ctx RcContext, op StdOp, argId ValueId) returns bool
	return match op 'dispatch'
		call(c) gives callMovesArgIntoContainer(ctx, c: c, argId: argId)
		arith gives false
		control gives false
		memory gives false
		system gives false
	end 'dispatch'
end 'opMovesArgIntoContainer'

function callMovesArgIntoContainer(ctx RcContext, c StdCallOp, argId ValueId) returns bool
	return match c 'check'
		call(_, callee, argIds) gives calleeMovesArg(ctx, callee: callee, argIds: argIds, argId: argId)
		tryCall(_, callee, argIds, _) gives calleeMovesArg(ctx, callee: callee, argIds: argIds, argId: argId)
		ret gives false
		indirectCall to errorReturn gives false
	end 'check'
end 'callMovesArgIntoContainer'

// CONCEPT C — is `argId` the moved (consumed) argument of intrinsic runtime helper
// `callee`? Read the structural `funcParamConsumes` bit at `argId`'s position (the
// runtime.std raw helpers are seeded as intrinsic leaf-consumers of their value arg by
// `analyzeParamConsumes`). This replaced the `calleeMovesValue and isLastArg`
// name-list allowlist.
function calleeMovesArg(ctx RcContext, callee String, argIds ValueIdArray, argId ValueId) returns bool
	let argIndex = argPositionOf(argIds, vid: argId)
	return argIndex >= 1 and paramConsumeBit(ctx.funcParamConsumes, callee: callee, argIndex: argIndex)
end 'calleeMovesArg'

// Edge deaths: for each managed value live-out of B that is dead entering a
// successor S, schedule an edge release — UNLESS V is MOVED into S's block-arg
// phi on that edge (the MOVE guard: the +1 transfers into the phi, which gets
// its own release).
//
// SIBLING-EDGE PHI RELEASE (Fix 4): a value B passes as a phi-arg on ONE
// out-edge is a terminator USE, so it lands in `liveIn[B]`/`use[B]` but NOT in
// `liveOut[B]` (liveOut unions only successor live-ins, and a phi-arg is
// consumed by the successor's block-arg def, not live-in the successor). The
// `liveOut` sweep above therefore never sees it, so on the SIBLING out-edges
// where it is dead its +1 leaks (the conditionally-dead `var x="default"` String
// in the `Box.make` repro). We supplement the sweep with B's own phi-arg values:
// each is fed through the same per-edge `planEdgeDeathForValue`, which MOVE-
// suppresses the edge it is passed on (`valueMovedIntoPhi`), skips any edge where
// it is still live-in (the multi-block phi chain — keeps `URL.parse` correct),
// and releases it on the remaining sibling edges where it is dead.
function planEdgeDeaths(ctx RcContext, block IrBlock)
	let blockLiveOut = try ctx.liveness.liveOut.get(block.id) otherwise return
	let succs = try ctx.cfg.successors.get(block.id) otherwise return

	for vid in blockLiveOut.members 'eachLiveOut'
		if not shouldReleaseAtLastUse(ctx, id: vid) 'skip'
			continue
		end 'skip'
		planEdgeDeathForValue(ctx, block: block, succs: succs, vid: vid)
	end 'eachLiveOut'

	// Supplement with B's phi-arg values that are absent from `liveOut[B]` (the
	// sibling-edge gap). Values already in `liveOut[B]` were handled above; skip
	// them here so no edge is double-released.
	let phiArgVals = collectTerminatorPhiArgValues(ctx, block: block)
	for vid in phiArgVals 'eachPhiArg'
		if ctx.liveness.liveOutContains(block.id, vid: vid) 'alreadyHandled'
			continue
		end 'alreadyHandled'
		if not shouldReleaseAtLastUse(ctx, id: vid) 'skip'
			continue
		end 'skip'
		planEdgeDeathForValue(ctx, block: block, succs: succs, vid: vid)
	end 'eachPhiArg'
end 'planEdgeDeaths'

// The deduplicated set of values `block` passes as block-arg (phi) arguments on
// ANY out-edge of its terminator. Used by `planEdgeDeaths` to recover the
// sibling-edge release for phi-args that are absent from `liveOut[block]`.
function collectTerminatorPhiArgValues(ctx RcContext, block IrBlock) returns ValueIdArray
	var result = ValueIdArray.create()
	if not block.hasTerminatorOp() 'noTerm'
		return result
	end 'noTerm'
	let term = try ctx.module.ops.get(block.terminatorIndex()) otherwise panic("collectTerminatorPhiArgValues: terminator not in module.ops")
	match term 'dispatch'
		control(cf) then collectCfPhiArgValues(cf, result: result)
		arith then break 'dispatch'
		call then break 'dispatch'
		memory then break 'dispatch'
		system then break 'dispatch'
	end 'dispatch'
	return result
end 'collectTerminatorPhiArgValues'

function collectCfPhiArgValues(cf StdControlOp, result ValueIdArray)
	match cf 'check'
		br(_, argIds) then appendUnique(result, src: argIds)
		condBr(_, _, thenArgIds, _, elseArgIds) then collectCondBrPhiArgValues(thenArgIds, elseArgIds: elseArgIds, result: result)
	end 'check'
end 'collectCfPhiArgValues'

function collectCondBrPhiArgValues(thenArgIds ValueIdArray, elseArgIds ValueIdArray, result ValueIdArray)
	appendUnique(result, src: thenArgIds)
	appendUnique(result, src: elseArgIds)
end 'collectCondBrPhiArgValues'

// Append each value of `src` to `result`, skipping any already present (the
// then/else arg lists may share a value; the dedup keeps each processed once).
function appendUnique(result ValueIdArray, src ValueIdArray)
	for v in src 'each'
		if not valueIdArrayContains(result, vid: v) 'new'
			result.push(v)
		end 'new'
	end 'each'
end 'appendUnique'

function planEdgeDeathForValue(ctx RcContext, block IrBlock, succs BlockIdArray, vid ValueId)
	for succId in succs 'eachSucc'
		// V dies on this edge iff it is NOT live entering the successor.
		if ctx.liveness.liveInContains(succId, vid: vid) 'stillLive'
			continue
		end 'stillLive'
		// MOVE guard (F4): V passed as a branch arg into S's block-arg phi is a
		// MOVE — the +1 transfers into the phi. Do NOT edge-release it. (Applies
		// to managed phis; raw-heap/type-param values are not phi-merged into a
		// managed block-arg, but a type-param phi is likewise its own owner.)
		if valueMovedIntoPhi(ctx, fromBlock: block, toBlockId: succId, vid: vid) 'isMove'
			logTrace(LogCategory.ir, message: function() gives "RC-EDGE-MOVE-SUPPRESS func={ctx.func.name} val=%{vid} edge=block_{block.id}->block_{succId} (moved into phi, no release)")
			continue
		end 'isMove'
		// ERROR-EDGE guard: `vid` is the RESULT of a `tryCall` in `block` and this
		// edge is the tryCall's ERROR branch (the `then` arm of the error-flag
		// `condBr`). On the throw path the call NEVER produced or owned the result —
		// the value register is zeroed by the error-return ABI — so it carries no +1
		// to release. The success edge owns and releases it (at its real last use).
		// Releasing on the error edge strict-decrefs a NULL pointer → write-fault at
		// `[0 - 8]` (the `findFirst("xyz") otherwise ...` crash). Suppress here: no
		// double-free (the +1 never existed on this path) and no leak (nothing owned).
		if tryCallResultDiesOnErrorEdge(ctx, block: block, succId: succId, vid: vid) 'errorEdge'
			logTrace(LogCategory.ir, message: function() gives "RC-EDGE-ERRPATH-SUPPRESS func={ctx.func.name} val=%{vid} edge=block_{block.id}->block_{succId} (tryCall result null on error edge, no release)")
			continue
		end 'errorEdge'
		// TRYCALL-CONSUMED-ARG guard (success edge): `vid` is an argument CONSUMED by a
		// `tryCall` in THIS block whose SUCCESS target is `succId` — its +1 transferred
		// to the callee on this edge, so an edge-release here would double-release the
		// moved +1. The error edge falls through to a real release (the throw path never
		// consumed it). The live-out counterpart of the term-drop guard in
		// `planTerminatorDeaths` (used when `vid` is live-out of the tryCall block).
		if tryCallTransferringArgSuccessBlock(ctx, block: block, argId: vid) == succId 'consumedOnSuccessEdge'
			logTrace(LogCategory.ir, message: function() gives "RC-EDGE-CONSUMED-SUPPRESS func={ctx.func.name} val=%{vid} edge=block_{block.id}->block_{succId} (consumed by tryCall on success edge, no release)")
			continue
		end 'consumedOnSuccessEdge'
		logTrace(LogCategory.ir, message: function() gives "RC-EDGE-RELEASE func={ctx.func.name} val=%{vid} edge=block_{block.id}->block_{succId} class={ownershipClassName(ctx.classOf(vid))} kind={releaseKindName(releaseKindAtLastUse(ctx, id: vid))}")
		ctx.edgeReleases.push(RcEdgeRelease.release(block.id, toBlockId: succId, valueId: vid))
	end 'eachSucc'
end 'planEdgeDeathForValue'

// True iff `vid` is the RESULT of a `tryCall` in `block` AND the `block`->`succId`
// edge is that tryCall's ERROR branch — so `vid` is null/unowned there (the
// error-return ABI zeroed the result register; the call threw before producing a
// +1). Recognised structurally: a `tryCall(resultId=vid, _, _, errorFlagId=f)` in
// the block, whose error flag `f` feeds the terminator `condBr`'s condition (a
// `cmpi ne f, 0`), with `succId` as that condBr's THEN (error) target. The success
// path is the ELSE target, where the result is genuinely owned and released.
function tryCallResultDiesOnErrorEdge(ctx RcContext, block IrBlock, succId BlockId, vid ValueId) returns bool
	if not block.hasTerminatorOp() 'noTerm'
		return false
	end 'noTerm'
	let errorFlagId = tryCallErrorFlagForResult(ctx, block: block, resultId: vid)
	if errorFlagId == REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE 'notTryResult'
		return false
	end 'notTryResult'
	let term = try ctx.module.ops.get(block.terminatorIndex()) otherwise panic("tryCallResultDiesOnErrorEdge: terminator not in module.ops")
	return match term 'dispatch'
		control(cf) gives condBrErrorThenTargets(ctx, cf: cf, errorFlagId: errorFlagId, succId: succId)
		arith gives false
		call gives false
		memory gives false
		system gives false
	end 'dispatch'
end 'tryCallResultDiesOnErrorEdge'

// True iff `vid`'s +1 was CONSUMED by a `tryCall` argument on the SUCCESS edge that
// reaches block `intoBlockId` — so `vid` no longer owns a transferable +1 once control
// arrives there and must NOT be released in/into that block.
//
// This is the ARG-SIDE dual of `tryCallResultDiesOnErrorEdge` (which suppresses the
// tryCall RESULT's release on the ERROR edge). A `tryCall` that CONSUMES one of its
// args (a transparent-wrapper factory like `StringIterator.create`/`ByteView.create`
// moving `managed` into the value it builds) transfers that arg's +1 to the callee
// ONLY when the call SUCCEEDS — on the throw path the callee returned before taking
// ownership, so the arg's +1 is still owned and the caller must release it (the
// error-edge release stays). The success path moved the +1 onward, so a term-drop /
// edge-release of the arg in the SUCCESS block is a SECOND release of an already-
// transferred +1 → the source's reference is driven down and freed out from under the
// new owner (the `for c in s` twice → second iterator reads a freed buffer → grapheme
// slice OOB). The op-level transfer-suppression at the call site fires in the tryCall's
// OWN block; this guard extends it across the success edge, where the arg outlives the
// call (it is live-after the tryCall, used by nothing but its own death sweep in the
// success successor).
//
// Recognised structurally: a predecessor `P` of `intoBlockId` whose terminator is the
// error-flag `condBr` selecting `intoBlockId` as the SUCCESS target, containing a
// `tryCall` that TRANSFERS `vid` as a consumed argument (`opTransfersOperand` — the
// same full move set the acquire analysis reads, covering both the transparent-wrapper
// arg-0 case and a non-self consumed element arg).
function valueConsumedByTryCallOnSuccessEdgeInto(ctx RcContext, intoBlockId BlockId, vid ValueId) returns bool
	let preds = try ctx.cfg.predecessors.get(intoBlockId) otherwise return false
	for predId in preds 'eachPred'
		// `predId` is a BlockId (the CFG keys on block.id), NOT a BlockRef (the
		// module.blocks array index) — resolve through `blockRefForId` exactly as the
		// edge-incref placement sites do.
		let predBlock = try ctx.module.blocks.get(blockRefForId(ctx, blockId: predId)) otherwise continue
		if not predBlock.hasTerminatorOp() 'noTerm'
			continue
		end 'noTerm'
		if tryCallArgConsumedReachingSuccess(ctx, predBlock: predBlock, successBlockId: intoBlockId, vid: vid) 'consumed'
			return true
		end 'consumed'
	end 'eachPred'
	return false
end 'valueConsumedByTryCallOnSuccessEdgeInto'

// True iff `predBlock` holds a `tryCall` that (a) TRANSFERS `vid` as a consumed
// argument and (b) whose error-flag `condBr` terminator selects `successBlockId` as
// its SUCCESS (non-throw) target. The two facts together mean `vid`'s +1 left via the
// callee precisely on the edge into `successBlockId`.
function tryCallArgConsumedReachingSuccess(ctx RcContext, predBlock IrBlock, successBlockId BlockId, vid ValueId) returns bool
	var foundConsumingTry = false
	for opIdx in predBlock.opRefs 'eachOp'
		let op = try ctx.module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("tryCallArgConsumedReachingSuccess: opIdx not in module.ops")
		if opIsTryCallTransferringArg(ctx, op: op, argId: vid) 'consumingTry'
			foundConsumingTry = true
			break
		end 'consumingTry'
	end 'eachOp'
	if not foundConsumingTry 'noConsumingTry'
		return false
	end 'noConsumingTry'
	// The tryCall's success target must be exactly `successBlockId`: the +1 transferred
	// on the success edge only. Reuse the result-side success-block resolver keyed on
	// the SAME tryCall (its result id), so the polarity handling stays in one place.
	return tryCallTransferringArgSuccessBlock(ctx, block: predBlock, argId: vid) == successBlockId
end 'tryCallArgConsumedReachingSuccess'

// True iff `op` is a `tryCall` that TRANSFERS `argId` (a consumed argument — the
// transparent-wrapper arg-0 or a non-self consumed element). Mirrors the op-level
// transfer set `markOpTransferredOperands` / `opTransfersOperand` reads, restricted to
// the tryCall form (the only call form with a success/error split this guard spans).
function opIsTryCallTransferringArg(ctx RcContext, op StdOp, argId ValueId) returns bool
	return match op 'dispatch'
		call(c) gives match c 'inner'
			tryCall gives opTransfersOperand(ctx, op: op, argId: argId)
			witnessTryCall gives opTransfersOperand(ctx, op: op, argId: argId)
			ret gives false
			call gives false
			indirectCall to witnessCall gives false
			funcRef to errorReturn gives false
		end 'inner'
		arith gives false
		control gives false
		memory gives false
		system gives false
	end 'dispatch'
end 'opIsTryCallTransferringArg'

// The SUCCESS-edge BlockId for the `tryCall` in `block` that TRANSFERS `argId`, or
// `REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE` if no such tryCall exists. Finds the tryCall by its argument
// (`argId` is consumed by it), then resolves its success target by the error-flag
// `condBr` polarity (the same resolver the result-side uses).
function tryCallTransferringArgSuccessBlock(ctx RcContext, block IrBlock, argId ValueId) returns BlockId
	let errorFlagId = tryCallErrorFlagForTransferredArg(ctx, block: block, argId: argId)
	if errorFlagId == REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE 'notTryArg'
		return REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
	end 'notTryArg'
	let term = try ctx.module.ops.get(block.terminatorIndex()) otherwise panic("tryCallTransferringArgSuccessBlock: terminator not in module.ops")
	return match term 'dispatch'
		control(cf) gives condBrSuccessTargetForErrorFlag(ctx, cf: cf, errorFlagId: errorFlagId)
		arith gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		call gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		memory gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		system gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
	end 'dispatch'
end 'tryCallTransferringArgSuccessBlock'

// The error-flag ValueId of the `tryCall` in `block` that TRANSFERS `argId` as a
// consumed argument, or `REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE`. The tryCall's two SSA defs are its result
// and its error flag; here we key off the consumed ARGUMENT instead of the result.
function tryCallErrorFlagForTransferredArg(ctx RcContext, block IrBlock, argId ValueId) returns ValueId
	for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
		let op = try ctx.module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("tryCallErrorFlagForTransferredArg: opIdx not in module.ops")
		if opIsTryCallTransferringArg(ctx, op: op, argId: argId) 'transferringTry'
			return tryCallErrorFlagOf(op)
		end 'transferringTry'
	end 'eachOp'
	return REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
end 'tryCallErrorFlagForTransferredArg'

// The error-flag SSA id of a `tryCall`/`witnessTryCall` op, or `REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE` for
// any other op shape.
function tryCallErrorFlagOf(op StdOp) returns ValueId
	return match op 'dispatch'
		call(c) gives match c 'inner'
			tryCall(_, _, _, errorFlagId) gives errorFlagId
			witnessTryCall(_, _, _, _, _, errorFlagId) gives errorFlagId
			ret gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
			call gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
			indirectCall to witnessCall gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
			funcRef to errorReturn gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		end 'inner'
		arith gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		control gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		memory gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		system gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
	end 'dispatch'
end 'tryCallErrorFlagOf'

// The SUCCESS-edge BlockId for a `tryCall` whose result is `resultId` defined in
// `block`, or `REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE` if `resultId` is not a tryCall result in `block`.
// On a throw the error-return ABI zeroes the result register, so `resultId` is null
// on the ERROR edge (the condBr's THEN target) and valid only on the SUCCESS edge
// (the ELSE target). A def-acquire incref of `resultId` must therefore be placed at
// the START of the success block, NOT immediately after the tryCall (which runs on
// BOTH edges before the branch → `incref(null)` on the throw path → write-fault).
function tryCallResultSuccessBlock(ctx RcContext, block IrBlock, resultId ValueId) returns BlockId
	if not block.hasTerminatorOp() 'noTerm'
		return REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
	end 'noTerm'
	let errorFlagId = tryCallErrorFlagForResult(ctx, block: block, resultId: resultId)
	if errorFlagId == REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE 'notTryResult'
		return REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
	end 'notTryResult'
	let term = try ctx.module.ops.get(block.terminatorIndex()) otherwise panic("tryCallResultSuccessBlock: terminator not in module.ops")
	return match term 'dispatch'
		control(cf) gives condBrSuccessTargetForErrorFlag(ctx, cf: cf, errorFlagId: errorFlagId)
		arith gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		call gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		memory gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		system gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
	end 'dispatch'
end 'tryCallResultSuccessBlock'

// The SUCCESS (non-throw) target of `cf` when it is the error-flag `condBr` for
// `errorFlagId`; `REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE` otherwise. The success target depends on the
// comparison POLARITY used to test the flag:
//   - `flag != 0`  → THEN = throw, ELSE = success  (a `try … otherwise` body)
//   - `flag == 0`  → THEN = success, ELSE = throw  (a `try …` used directly as an
//                    `if`/bool condition, e.g. `if try s.findLast(x) … else …`)
// Handling only the `!=` polarity left the `==` shape's tryCall result decref in
// the tryCall block (executed on BOTH edges, before the branch) UNGUARDED — the
// throw ABI zeroes the result register, so the decref read `[null-8]` and faulted
// (addr=-8; the `find-last-not-found` crash). Pick the success target by polarity.
function condBrSuccessTargetForErrorFlag(ctx RcContext, cf StdControlOp, errorFlagId ValueId) returns BlockId
	return match cf 'check'
		condBr(condId, thenTarget, _, elseTarget, _) gives errorFlagSuccessTarget(ctx, condId: condId, errorFlagId: errorFlagId, thenTarget: thenTarget, elseTarget: elseTarget)
		br gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
	end 'check'
end 'condBrSuccessTargetForErrorFlag'

// Resolve the success branch target for an error-flag `condBr`, by the polarity of
// the comparison that produced `condId`. `flag != 0` → ELSE is success; `flag == 0`
// → THEN is success. Returns `REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE` if `condId` is not an error-flag
// comparison of `errorFlagId` against zero.
function errorFlagSuccessTarget(ctx RcContext, condId ValueId, errorFlagId ValueId, thenTarget BlockId, elseTarget BlockId) returns BlockId
	return match classifyErrorFlagCondBr(ctx, condId: condId, errorFlagId: errorFlagId) 'polarity'
		notErrorCheck gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		neThenThrow gives elseTarget
		eqThenSuccess gives thenTarget
	end 'polarity'
end 'errorFlagSuccessTarget'

// The error-flag ValueId of a `tryCall` in `block` whose result is `resultId`, or
// `REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE` if no such tryCall exists. The tryCall result and error flag
// are the two SSA defs of a `func.try_call` op.
function tryCallErrorFlagForResult(ctx RcContext, block IrBlock, resultId ValueId) returns ValueId
	for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
		let op = try ctx.module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("tryCallErrorFlagForResult: opIdx not in module.ops")
		let flag = tryCallErrorFlagIfResult(op, resultId: resultId)
		if flag != REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE 'hit'
			return flag
		end 'hit'
	end 'eachOp'
	return REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
end 'tryCallErrorFlagForResult'

function tryCallErrorFlagIfResult(op StdOp, resultId ValueId) returns ValueId
	return match op 'dispatch'
		call(c) gives match c 'inner'
			tryCall(r, _, _, errorFlagId) gives(errorFlagId if r == resultId else REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE)
			witnessTryCall(r, _, _, _, _, errorFlagId) gives(errorFlagId if r == resultId else REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE)
			ret gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
			call gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
			indirectCall to witnessCall gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
			funcRef to errorReturn gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		end 'inner'
		arith gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		control gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		memory gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		system gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
	end 'dispatch'
end 'tryCallErrorFlagIfResult'

// True iff `cf` is a `condBr` whose THROW (error) target is `succId`. Polarity-aware:
// for a `flag != 0` condition the throw target is THEN; for a `flag == 0` condition
// (a `try` used directly as a bool/`if` condition) it is ELSE.
function condBrErrorThenTargets(ctx RcContext, cf StdControlOp, errorFlagId ValueId, succId BlockId) returns bool
	return match cf 'check'
		condBr(condId, thenTarget, _, elseTarget, _) gives errorEdgeMatches(ctx, condId: condId, errorFlagId: errorFlagId, thenTarget: thenTarget, elseTarget: elseTarget, succId: succId)
		br gives false
	end 'check'
end 'condBrErrorThenTargets'

function errorEdgeMatches(ctx RcContext, condId ValueId, errorFlagId ValueId, thenTarget BlockId, elseTarget BlockId, succId BlockId) returns bool
	return match classifyErrorFlagCondBr(ctx, condId: condId, errorFlagId: errorFlagId) 'polarity'
		notErrorCheck gives false
		neThenThrow gives thenTarget == succId
		eqThenSuccess gives elseTarget == succId
	end 'polarity'
end 'errorEdgeMatches'

// Polarity of a tryCall error-flag `condBr` condition. The `try`/`otherwise` body
// lowering emits `flag != 0` (THEN = throw); a `try` used directly as a bool/`if`
// condition emits `flag == 0` (THEN = success). `notErrorCheck` for anything that
// is not a comparison of `errorFlagId` against zero — conservative, so a non-error
// condBr is never mistaken for either path.
union ErrorFlagPolarity
	notErrorCheck
	neThenThrow
	eqThenSuccess
end 'ErrorFlagPolarity'

// Classify `condId` as the `errorFlagId != 0` / `== 0` test the try-lowering emits
// between a `tryCall` and its branch. Scans for the cmp op that produced `condId`.
function classifyErrorFlagCondBr(ctx RcContext, condId ValueId, errorFlagId ValueId) returns ErrorFlagPolarity
	for blockRef in ctx.func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try ctx.module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("classifyErrorFlagCondBr: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
			let op = try ctx.module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("classifyErrorFlagCondBr: opIdx not in module.ops")
			let polarity = errorFlagCmpPolarity(op, resultId: condId, operandId: errorFlagId)
			if not polarityIsNotErrorCheck(polarity) 'hit'
				return polarity
			end 'hit'
		end 'eachOp'
	end 'eachBlock'
	return ErrorFlagPolarity.notErrorCheck
end 'classifyErrorFlagCondBr'

function polarityIsNotErrorCheck(p ErrorFlagPolarity) returns bool
	return match p 'check'
		notErrorCheck gives true
		neThenThrow gives false
		eqThenSuccess gives false
	end 'check'
end 'polarityIsNotErrorCheck'

function errorFlagCmpPolarity(op StdOp, resultId ValueId, operandId ValueId) returns ErrorFlagPolarity
	return match op 'dispatch'
		arith(a) gives arithBinaryErrorFlagPolarity(a, resultId: resultId, operandId: operandId)
		call gives ErrorFlagPolarity.notErrorCheck
		control gives ErrorFlagPolarity.notErrorCheck
		memory gives ErrorFlagPolarity.notErrorCheck
		system gives ErrorFlagPolarity.notErrorCheck
	end 'dispatch'
end 'errorFlagCmpPolarity'

function arithBinaryErrorFlagPolarity(a StdArithOp, resultId ValueId, operandId ValueId) returns ErrorFlagPolarity
	return match a 'check'
		binary(b) gives binaryErrorFlagPolarity(b, resultId: resultId, operandId: operandId)
		const to unary gives ErrorFlagPolarity.notErrorCheck
	end 'check'
end 'arithBinaryErrorFlagPolarity'

function binaryErrorFlagPolarity(b StdArithBinaryOp, resultId ValueId, operandId ValueId) returns ErrorFlagPolarity
	if b.resultId != resultId 'notThisCond'
		return ErrorFlagPolarity.notErrorCheck
	end 'notThisCond'
	if b.leftId != operandId and b.rightId != operandId 'notThisFlag'
		return ErrorFlagPolarity.notErrorCheck
	end 'notThisFlag'
	return match b.opcode 'op'
		addI64 to maxF64 gives ErrorFlagPolarity.notErrorCheck
		cmpI64Eq gives ErrorFlagPolarity.eqThenSuccess
		cmpI64Ne gives ErrorFlagPolarity.neThenThrow
		cmpI64Lt to cmpF64Ge gives ErrorFlagPolarity.notErrorCheck
	end 'op'
end 'binaryErrorFlagPolarity'

// True iff `vid` is passed from `fromBlock`'s terminator as a block-arg into
// `toBlockId` (i.e. it is moved into a phi on this edge). Reads the terminator's
// per-edge arg list.
function valueMovedIntoPhi(ctx RcContext, fromBlock IrBlock, toBlockId BlockId, vid ValueId) returns bool
	if not fromBlock.hasTerminatorOp() 'noTerm'
		return false
	end 'noTerm'
	let term = try ctx.module.ops.get(fromBlock.terminatorIndex()) otherwise panic("valueMovedIntoPhi: terminator not in module.ops")
	return match term 'dispatch'
		control(cf) gives edgeArgsContain(cf, toBlockId: toBlockId, vid: vid)
		arith gives false
		call gives false
		memory gives false
		system gives false
	end 'dispatch'
end 'valueMovedIntoPhi'

// True iff `vid` is moved into a RELEASABLE phi on some out-edge of `block`'s
// terminator — i.e. passed as a block-arg into a successor phi whose own result
// is managed/type-param (so the phi will be released at ITS last use, absorbing
// the moved +1). Used by `planTerminatorDeaths` to skip the terminator-death of
// such a value: term-dropping it here would be a SECOND release of the +1 the
// phi now owns (the for-in iterator double-free).
//
// The phi-result-class check is load-bearing: a managed value moved into a phi
// whose result is `notManaged` (e.g. an inliner-continuation phi that escaped
// classification) is NOT truly transferred — that phi never releases it — so
// suppressing the term-drop there would LEAK the value. Only suppress when the
// destination phi genuinely owns and will release the +1. This mirrors the
// invariant `planEdgeDeaths`'s MOVE guard relies on (the phi is releasable), made
// explicit so a mis-classified phi degrades to a (recoverable) term-drop rather
// than a leak.
function valueMovedIntoAnyPhi(ctx RcContext, block IrBlock, vid ValueId) returns bool
	let succs = try ctx.cfg.successors.get(block.id) otherwise return false
	for succId in succs 'eachSucc'
		if valueMovedIntoReleasablePhi(ctx, fromBlock: block, toBlockId: succId, vid: vid) 'moved'
			return true
		end 'moved'
	end 'eachSucc'
	return false
end 'valueMovedIntoAnyPhi'

// True iff `vid` is a block-arg on the `fromBlock`->`toBlockId` edge AND the
// phi result it feeds (same positional index in `toBlock.blockArgs`) is itself a
// value the inserter releases (managed or type-param). The positional match is
// how SSA block-args bind: the Nth edge arg feeds the Nth successor block-arg.
//
function valueMovedIntoReleasablePhi(ctx RcContext, fromBlock IrBlock, toBlockId BlockId, vid ValueId) returns bool
	if not fromBlock.hasTerminatorOp() 'noTerm'
		return false
	end 'noTerm'
	let term = try ctx.module.ops.get(fromBlock.terminatorIndex()) otherwise panic("valueMovedIntoReleasablePhi: terminator not in module.ops")
	let toBlock = findBlockById(ctx, blockId: toBlockId)
	return match term 'k'
		control(cf) gives edgeFeedsReleasablePhi(ctx, cf: cf, toBlock: toBlock, toBlockId: toBlockId, vid: vid)
		arith gives false
		call gives false
		memory gives false
		system gives false
	end 'k'
end 'valueMovedIntoReleasablePhi'

function edgeFeedsReleasablePhi(ctx RcContext, cf StdControlOp, toBlock IrBlock, toBlockId BlockId, vid ValueId) returns bool
	return match cf 'c'
		br(target, argIds) gives argsFeedReleasablePhi(ctx, target: target, argIds: argIds, toBlock: toBlock, toBlockId: toBlockId, vid: vid)
		condBr(_, thenTarget, thenArgIds, elseTarget, elseArgIds) gives argsFeedReleasablePhi(ctx, target: thenTarget, argIds: thenArgIds, toBlock: toBlock, toBlockId: toBlockId, vid: vid) or argsFeedReleasablePhi(ctx, target: elseTarget, argIds: elseArgIds, toBlock: toBlock, toBlockId: toBlockId, vid: vid)
	end 'c'
end 'edgeFeedsReleasablePhi'

// Scan the edge's block-arg list positionally: if `vid` appears at index N and
// `toBlock`'s Nth block-arg (the phi it feeds) is managed/type-param, the move
// transfers `vid`'s +1 into a phi that will release it.
function argsFeedReleasablePhi(ctx RcContext, target BlockId, argIds ValueIdArray, toBlock IrBlock, toBlockId BlockId, vid ValueId) returns bool
	if target != toBlockId 'wrongEdge'
		return false
	end 'wrongEdge'
	var i = 0
	for id in argIds 'each'
		if id == vid and i < toBlock.blockArgs.count() 'hit'
			let phiArg = try toBlock.blockArgs.get(i) otherwise return false
			return ctx.isManaged(phiArg.valueId) or ctx.isTypeParam(phiArg.valueId)
		end 'hit'
		i = i + 1
	end 'each'
	return false
end 'argsFeedReleasablePhi'

function edgeArgsContain(cf StdControlOp, toBlockId BlockId, vid ValueId) returns bool
	return match cf 'check'
		br(target, argIds) gives target == toBlockId and valueIdArrayContains(argIds, vid: vid)
		condBr(_, thenTarget, thenArgIds, elseTarget, elseArgIds) gives condBrEdgeArgsContain(thenTarget, thenArgIds: thenArgIds, elseTarget: elseTarget, elseArgIds: elseArgIds, toBlockId: toBlockId, vid: vid)
	end 'check'
end 'edgeArgsContain'

function condBrEdgeArgsContain(thenTarget BlockId, thenArgIds ValueIdArray, elseTarget BlockId, elseArgIds ValueIdArray, toBlockId BlockId, vid ValueId) returns bool
	if thenTarget == toBlockId and valueIdArrayContains(thenArgIds, vid: vid) 'thenHit'
		return true
	end 'thenHit'
	if elseTarget == toBlockId and valueIdArrayContains(elseArgIds, vid: vid) 'elseHit'
		return true
	end 'elseHit'
	return false
end 'condBrEdgeArgsContain'

// ============================================================
// Phi-edge reconciliation (mixed-class block-arg)
// ============================================================
// A block-arg (phi) merging managed values is a fresh owned value released at
// ITS last use (handled by the normal last-use logic, since the phi's valueId
// is just another managed SSA value). For the phi to hold a clean +1 on EVERY
// incoming edge, each edge must MOVE a +1 into it. Edges whose incoming value
// carries a transferable +1 (it would otherwise be released locally) supply that
// +1 by the MOVE (their edge-decref was already suppressed by the MOVE guard).
// Edges whose incoming value does NOT carry a +1 — a `borrowed` view, a param
// (caller-owned, no local +1), or the synthetic null/undef sentinel — must
// IRREF the incoming value on that edge so the phi receives a clean owned ref.
//
// This runs as part of edge-release application: it appends an incref to the
// (possibly freshly split) edge block carrying the move.

// For each managed block-arg (phi), examine every predecessor edge's incoming
// value. If that value does NOT carry a transferable +1 (a `borrowed` view, a
// param, or the synthetic null/undef sentinel), incref it on that edge so the
// phi receives a clean owned reference on every path. Edges whose value carries
// a +1 supply it via the MOVE (their edge-decref was already suppressed by the
// MOVE guard), so they get nothing here.
function planPhiEdgeIncrefs(ctx RcContext)
	for blockRef in ctx.func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try ctx.module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("planPhiEdgeIncrefs: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		if block.blockArgs.count() == 0 'noPhis'
			continue
		end 'noPhis'
		planPhiEdgeIncrefsForBlock(ctx, block: block)
	end 'eachBlock'
end 'planPhiEdgeIncrefs'

function planPhiEdgeIncrefsForBlock(ctx RcContext, block IrBlock)
	let preds = try ctx.cfg.predecessors.get(block.id) otherwise return
	var argIdx = 0
	while argIdx < block.blockArgs.count() 'eachArg'
		let arg = try block.blockArgs.get(argIdx) otherwise panic("planPhiEdgeIncrefsForBlock: blockArgs.get({argIdx}) OOB")
		if ctx.isManaged(arg.valueId) 'managedPhi'
			planPhiArgEdgeIncrefs(ctx, block: block, preds: preds, argIdx: argIdx)
		end 'managedPhi'
		argIdx = argIdx + 1
	end 'eachArg'
end 'planPhiEdgeIncrefsForBlock'

function planPhiArgEdgeIncrefs(ctx RcContext, block IrBlock, preds BlockIdArray, argIdx NodeIndex)
	let phiArg = try block.blockArgs.get(argIdx) otherwise panic("planPhiArgEdgeIncrefs: blockArgs.get({argIdx}) OOB")

	for predId in preds 'eachPred'
		let predBlock = findBlockById(ctx, blockId: predId)
		let incoming = incomingPhiArg(ctx, predBlock: predBlock, toBlockId: block.id, argIdx: argIdx)
		if incoming == REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE 'noArg'
			continue
		end 'noArg'
		// An incoming value that already carries a +1 (the MOVE supplies it) or is a
		// constant-zero null sentinel must NOT be increfed here — `phiArgGetsEdgeIncref`
		// is the single source of truth for that decision, shared with the term-drop
		// suppression predicate (`borrowRootDeferredOnEdge`) so the two can never drift.
		if not phiArgGetsEdgeIncref(ctx, toBlockId: block.id, phiValueId: phiArg.valueId, incoming: incoming) 'noIncref'
			continue
		end 'noIncref'
		// No +1 on this edge — incref the incoming value so the phi owns a
		// clean reference along this path.
		logTrace(LogCategory.ir, message: function() gives "RC-EDGE-INCREF func={ctx.func.name} val=%{incoming} edge=block_{predId}->block_{block.id} class={ownershipClassName(ctx.classOf(incoming))}")
		ctx.edgeReleases.push(RcEdgeRelease.incref(predId, toBlockId: block.id, valueId: incoming))

		// BORROW-BASE DEFERRAL: when the increfed phi-arg is an interior BORROW
		// (`incoming` is `Array.get`'s element pointer, borrowing the array), the
		// borrow's owning allocation (its ROOT — the array) must stay live until the
		// incref above secures the phi's OWN +1. Pushing the root's release HERE —
		// after the incref, on the SAME edge — orders it after the incref in the split
		// edge block, so the array (and its element-walk) frees only AFTER the borrowed
		// element has its independent +1. Without this the array's last-use term-drop
		// in the predecessor frees the element before the incref, which then increfs a
		// freed header (the `let ys = xs; let a = ys.get(0); a.value` garbage-tag UAF).
		// The matching term-drop suppression is in `planTerminatorDeaths`
		// (`borrowRootDeferredToPhiEdge`).
		planBorrowRootEdgeRelease(ctx, predId: predId, toBlockId: block.id, borrowed: incoming)
	end 'eachPred'
end 'planPhiArgEdgeIncrefs'

// The borrow ROOT whose release defers onto a phi edge when `borrowed` is
// increfed there, or `REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE` if `borrowed` does not qualify. The
// deferral root is a DISTINCT managed allocation (`isBorrow`, `root != borrowed`)
// that is releasable at last use (`shouldReleaseAtLastUse`, which already excludes
// function params — caller-owned — borrowed views and notManaged). This is the one
// definition of the deferral condition; both the release (`planBorrowRootEdgeRelease`)
// and the term-drop suppression (`borrowRootIs`) read it, so they cannot disagree.
function borrowDeferralRoot(ctx RcContext, borrowed ValueId) returns ValueId
	if not ctx.liveness.borrows.isBorrow(borrowed) 'notBorrow'
		return REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
	end 'notBorrow'
	let root = ctx.liveness.borrows.rootOf(borrowed)
	if root == borrowed 'selfRoot'
		return REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
	end 'selfRoot'
	if not shouldReleaseAtLastUse(ctx, id: root) 'notReleasable'
		return REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
	end 'notReleasable'
	return root
end 'borrowDeferralRoot'

// Schedule the release of `borrowed`'s borrow ROOT on the `predId`->`toBlockId`
// edge, AFTER the phi-edge incref of `borrowed` just pushed by the caller. Fires
// only when the root is a deferral root (`borrowDeferralRoot`) that dies on this
// edge — not live-out of the predecessor, else `planEdgeDeaths` owns it. The
// predecessor's term-drop of the same root is suppressed by
// `borrowRootDeferredToPhiEdge` so the +1 is released exactly once, here.
function planBorrowRootEdgeRelease(ctx RcContext, predId BlockId, toBlockId BlockId, borrowed ValueId)
	let root = borrowDeferralRoot(ctx, borrowed: borrowed)
	if root == REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE 'noDeferral'
		return
	end 'noDeferral'
	// Live-out of the predecessor → it survives into a successor and is released
	// there by the normal edge/in-block sweeps; releasing here would double-free.
	if ctx.liveness.liveOutContains(predId, vid: root) 'escapes'
		return
	end 'escapes'
	logTrace(LogCategory.ir, message: function() gives "RC-BORROWROOT-EDGEDROP func={ctx.func.name} root=%{root} borrow=%{borrowed} edge=block_{predId}->block_{toBlockId}")
	ctx.edgeReleases.push(RcEdgeRelease.release(predId, toBlockId: toBlockId, valueId: root))
end 'planBorrowRootEdgeRelease'

// True iff `vid` is the borrow ROOT of some managed phi-arg that receives a
// phi-edge incref on an out-edge of `block` — i.e. its release was DEFERRED to that
// edge by `planBorrowRootEdgeRelease`. Used by `planTerminatorDeaths` to suppress
// the term-drop that would otherwise free `vid` (the borrowed element's owning
// allocation) BEFORE the edge incref secures the element's own +1. Mirrors the
// edge-release predicate exactly so the +1 is released on exactly one path.
function borrowRootDeferredToPhiEdge(ctx RcContext, block IrBlock, vid ValueId) returns bool
	let succs = try ctx.cfg.successors.get(block.id) otherwise return false
	for succId in succs 'eachSucc'
		if borrowRootDeferredOnEdge(ctx, fromBlock: block, toBlockId: succId, vid: vid) 'deferred'
			return true
		end 'deferred'
	end 'eachSucc'
	return false
end 'borrowRootDeferredToPhiEdge'

// True iff some managed phi-arg passed on the `fromBlock`->`toBlockId` edge (1) gets
// a phi-edge incref (does not carry a +1, is not a null sentinel) AND (2) has `vid`
// as its borrow root. This is the exact condition under which
// `planBorrowRootEdgeRelease` scheduled `vid`'s edge-release, so the term-drop must
// step aside.
function borrowRootDeferredOnEdge(ctx RcContext, fromBlock IrBlock, toBlockId BlockId, vid ValueId) returns bool
	let toBlock = findBlockById(ctx, blockId: toBlockId)
	var argIdx = 0
	while argIdx < toBlock.blockArgs.count() 'eachArg'
		let phiArg = try toBlock.blockArgs.get(argIdx) otherwise panic("borrowRootDeferredOnEdge: blockArgs.get({argIdx}) OOB")
		if ctx.isManaged(phiArg.valueId) 'managedPhi'
			let incoming = incomingPhiArg(ctx, predBlock: fromBlock, toBlockId: toBlockId, argIdx: argIdx)
			if incoming != REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE and phiArgGetsEdgeIncref(ctx, toBlockId: toBlockId, phiValueId: phiArg.valueId, incoming: incoming) and borrowRootIs(ctx, borrowed: incoming, root: vid) 'hit'
				return true
			end 'hit'
		end 'managedPhi'
		argIdx = argIdx + 1
	end 'eachArg'
	return false
end 'borrowRootDeferredOnEdge'

// True iff phi-arg `incoming` would receive a phi-edge incref — it lacks a
// transferable +1 and is not a constant-zero null sentinel. The single source of
// truth for the incref decision: `planPhiArgEdgeIncrefs` (which edges incref) and
// the term-drop suppression predicate (`borrowRootDeferredOnEdge`) both call this,
// so they can never disagree on which edges incref.
function phiArgGetsEdgeIncref(ctx RcContext, toBlockId BlockId, phiValueId ValueId, incoming ValueId) returns bool
	// A SELF-FEEDING loop edge (the latch passes the phi its own current value —
	// a `var` left unassigned on that path) re-binds the SAME single reference;
	// it neither moves nor needs a new +1, regardless of liveness.
	if incoming == phiValueId 'selfEdge'
		return false
	end 'selfEdge'

	// An incoming value already carrying a +1 supplies it via the MOVE — no
	// incref. The move is only real when the value's life ends at the merge: its
	// own release is then naturally absent and the single +1 continues as the
	// phi's. A value still LIVE INTO the merge block (a real use after the merge
	// — e.g. the try-merge phi the lowering feeds the still-live receiver of a
	// void chainable) keeps its +1 for its real last use, so the phi must take
	// its OWN reference via the edge incref; without it the phi's release and
	// the value's own release double-count the single +1 (the
	// `try m.insert(...) otherwise ignore` success-edge over-release). Live-in
	// of the DESTINATION — not live-out of the predecessor — is the right test:
	// a value feeding several phis on mutually exclusive paths is statically
	// live-out of each predecessor yet dynamically transfers its one +1 to
	// whichever merge actually runs (increfing those edges leaked one +1 per
	// taken edge across `URL.parse`'s component merges).
	if edgeValueCarriesPlusOne(ctx, vid: incoming) and not ctx.liveness.liveInContains(toBlockId, vid: incoming) 'hasPlusOne'
		return false
	end 'hasPlusOne'
	// A TYPE-PARAM-classed incoming with the TRANSFER class (`callReturnRc1` —
	// `mrt_managed_list_remove`'s unlinked element threaded into a concrete
	// caller) carries a real +1 the managed-gated `edgeValueCarriesPlusOne`
	// cannot see (the value's managed bit is false; its declared type was the
	// callee's `Element`). The +1 MOVES into the phi exactly like a managed
	// carrier's. Increfing the edge on top of it strands one reference: the
	// caller has no layout param, so the value's own type-param release is
	// `ReleaseKind.none`, and only the phi's single release ever fires (the
	// `try list.removeFirst() otherwise …` Pair leak).
	if ctx.isTypeParam(incoming) and classIsCallReturnRc1(ctx, id: incoming) and not ctx.liveness.liveInContains(toBlockId, vid: incoming) 'typeParamPlusOne'
		return false
	end 'typeParamPlusOne'
	// A CONSTANT-ZERO phi input carries NO reference — it is the null sentinel a
	// `try`/`otherwise` error edge feeds into a merge phi (the result is undefined
	// on the throw path, so the lowering passes `0`). Increfing it would
	// `incref(null)` and write-fault (the `arr.slice(...) otherwise return ...`
	// crash). A literal `0` can NEVER be incref'd regardless of edge; the phi's
	// real +1 comes from its non-zero (success) inputs. The phi value is null on
	// this path and any release of it is null-guarded, so skipping the incref is
	// balanced.
	if valueIsConstantZero(ctx, vid: incoming) 'nullSentinel'
		return false
	end 'nullSentinel'
	// A NOT-MANAGED incoming whose merge already carries a SPLICED ACQUIRE is
	// the inlined `__mm_alloc` continuation shape: the phi receives the fresh
	// allocation as a raw `slab + header` pointer (classified notManaged), and
	// the spliced callee body's own acquire — an `__mm_incref` call or its
	// inlined `subi v, 8; atomic_inc` form, carried verbatim by the inliner —
	// supplies the phi's +1 right after the merge. Edge-increfing the raw
	// pointer on top of that double-counts (rc=2, one release — the inlined
	// tuple-per-iteration leak in `for (i, v) in r.withIterator()`). A
	// notManaged incoming WITHOUT a body acquire keeps the edge incref: an
	// inlined element-loader's borrow (`__managed_mem_get`'s result threads
	// notManaged into the caller) gets its only +1 from this edge, and the
	// merge phi's release counts on it (the `try args.get(1) otherwise ""`
	// element over-release).
	if not ctx.isManaged(incoming) and (valueHasBodyAcquire(ctx, vid: incoming) or valueHasBodyAcquire(ctx, vid: phiValueId)) 'splicedAcquire'
		return false
	end 'splicedAcquire'
	return true
end 'phiArgGetsEdgeIncref'

// True iff the function body already contains an ACQUIRE of `vid`: an
// `__mm_incref`-family call with `vid` as its argument, or the inliner-spliced
// inlined form — `sys.atomic_inc` of an address computed as `subi vid, 8` (the
// refcount header word). Scans only pre-existing body ops (the inserter's own
// queued ops are not yet applied when the phi-edge plan runs), so a hit always
// means the +1 was minted by a spliced callee body, not by this pass.
function valueHasBodyAcquire(ctx RcContext, vid ValueId) returns bool
	for blockRef in ctx.func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try ctx.module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("valueHasBodyAcquire: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		var headerAddrId = REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
			let op = try ctx.module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("valueHasBodyAcquire: opIdx not in module.ops")
			if opIsIncrefCallOf(op, vid: vid) 'callForm'
				return true
			end 'callForm'
			let subResult = opDefinesRcHeaderAddr(op, vid: vid)
			if subResult != REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE 'headerAddr'
				headerAddrId = subResult
			end 'headerAddr'
			if headerAddrId != REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE and opIsAtomicIncOf(op, addrId: headerAddrId) 'inlinedForm'
				return true
			end 'inlinedForm'
		end 'eachOp'
	end 'eachBlock'
	return false
end 'valueHasBodyAcquire'

// True iff `op` is a static call to the incref runtime entry with `vid` as arg 0.
function opIsIncrefCallOf(op StdOp, vid ValueId) returns bool
	return match op 'dispatch'
		call(c) gives callIsIncrefOf(c, vid: vid)
		arith gives false
		control gives false
		memory gives false
		system gives false
	end 'dispatch'
end 'opIsIncrefCallOf'

function callIsIncrefOf(c StdCallOp, vid ValueId) returns bool
	return match c 'check'
		call(_, callee, argIds) gives calleeNameIsIncref(callee) and isFirstArg(argIds, vid: vid)
		ret gives false
		tryCall gives false
		indirectCall to errorReturn gives false
	end 'check'
end 'callIsIncrefOf'

function calleeNameIsIncref(callee String) returns bool
	return callee == "stdlib.__mm_incref" or callee == "__mm_incref" or callee == "mm_incref"
end 'calleeNameIsIncref'

// If `op` is `arith.subi vid, 8` (the refcount-header address computation of the
// inlined incref body), return its result id; else REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE.
function opDefinesRcHeaderAddr(op StdOp, vid ValueId) returns ValueId
	return match op 'dispatch'
		arith(a) gives arithDefinesRcHeaderAddr(a, vid: vid)
		call gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		control gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		memory gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		system gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
	end 'dispatch'
end 'opDefinesRcHeaderAddr'

function arithDefinesRcHeaderAddr(a StdArithOp, vid ValueId) returns ValueId
	return match a 'check'
		binary(op) gives binaryDefinesRcHeaderAddr(op, vid: vid)
		const gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		unary gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
	end 'check'
end 'arithDefinesRcHeaderAddr'

function binaryDefinesRcHeaderAddr(op StdArithBinaryOp, vid ValueId) returns ValueId
	let isSub = match op.opcode 'opc'
		subI64 gives true
		addI64 gives false
		mulI64 to cmpF64Ge gives false
	end 'opc'
	if not isSub or op.leftId != vid 'notHeaderSub'
		return REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
	end 'notHeaderSub'
	return op.resultId
end 'binaryDefinesRcHeaderAddr'

function opIsAtomicIncOf(op StdOp, addrId ValueId) returns bool
	return match op 'dispatch'
		system(s) gives sysIsAtomicIncOf(s, addrId: addrId)
		arith gives false
		call gives false
		control gives false
		memory gives false
	end 'dispatch'
end 'opIsAtomicIncOf'

function sysIsAtomicIncOf(s StdSystemOp, addrId ValueId) returns bool
	return match s 'check'
		atomicInc(target) gives target == addrId
		globalAddr to osDirMkdir gives false
		atomicDec to dropTypeParam gives false
	end 'check'
end 'sysIsAtomicIncOf'

// True iff `root` is the borrow-deferral root of `borrowed` (`borrowDeferralRoot`).
// The term-drop suppression side of the deferral: `planBorrowRootEdgeRelease`
// additionally skips a root that is live-out of the predecessor, but the term-drop
// is only reached for non-live-out values (the `liveOutContains` guard earlier in
// `planTerminatorDeaths` already `continue`d on a live-out value), so the shared
// `borrowDeferralRoot` predicate is sufficient here.
function borrowRootIs(ctx RcContext, borrowed ValueId, root ValueId) returns bool
	let deferral = borrowDeferralRoot(ctx, borrowed: borrowed)
	return deferral != REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE and deferral == root
end 'borrowRootIs'

// True iff `vid` is defined by an `arith.constant {value = 0}` op anywhere in the
// function — i.e. a constant null/zero. Used to skip the phi-edge incref of a
// try/otherwise error-path null sentinel (incref(0) would write-fault).
function valueIsConstantZero(ctx RcContext, vid ValueId) returns bool
	for blockRef in ctx.func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try ctx.module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("valueIsConstantZero: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
			let op = try ctx.module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("valueIsConstantZero: opIdx not in module.ops")
			if opDefinesConstantZero(op, vid: vid) 'hit'
				return true
			end 'hit'
		end 'eachOp'
	end 'eachBlock'
	return false
end 'valueIsConstantZero'

function opDefinesConstantZero(op StdOp, vid ValueId) returns bool
	return match op 'dispatch'
		arith(a) gives arithDefinesConstantZero(a, vid: vid)
		call gives false
		control gives false
		memory gives false
		system gives false
	end 'dispatch'
end 'opDefinesConstantZero'

function arithDefinesConstantZero(a StdArithOp, vid ValueId) returns bool
	return match a 'check'
		const(c) gives(c.resultId == vid and c.value == 0)
		unary to binary gives false
	end 'check'
end 'arithDefinesConstantZero'

// The ValueId the `predBlock` terminator passes as block-arg `argIdx` on the
// edge into `toBlockId`. `REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE` if the terminator carries no such
// arg (shouldn't happen in well-formed SSA, but guarded).
function incomingPhiArg(ctx RcContext, predBlock IrBlock, toBlockId BlockId, argIdx NodeIndex) returns ValueId
	if not predBlock.hasTerminatorOp() 'noTerm'
		return REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
	end 'noTerm'
	let term = try ctx.module.ops.get(predBlock.terminatorIndex()) otherwise panic("incomingPhiArg: terminator not in module.ops")
	return match term 'dispatch'
		control(cf) gives incomingPhiArgCf(cf, toBlockId: toBlockId, argIdx: argIdx)
		arith gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		call gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		memory gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
		system gives REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
	end 'dispatch'
end 'incomingPhiArg'

function incomingPhiArgCf(cf StdControlOp, toBlockId BlockId, argIdx NodeIndex) returns ValueId
	return match cf 'check'
		br(target, argIds) gives(argAtOrNone(argIds, argIdx: argIdx) if target == toBlockId else REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE)
		condBr(_, thenTarget, thenArgIds, elseTarget, elseArgIds) gives incomingCondBrArg(thenTarget, thenArgIds: thenArgIds, elseTarget: elseTarget, elseArgIds: elseArgIds, toBlockId: toBlockId, argIdx: argIdx)
	end 'check'
end 'incomingPhiArgCf'

function incomingCondBrArg(thenTarget BlockId, thenArgIds ValueIdArray, elseTarget BlockId, elseArgIds ValueIdArray, toBlockId BlockId, argIdx NodeIndex) returns ValueId
	if thenTarget == toBlockId 'then'
		return argAtOrNone(thenArgIds, argIdx: argIdx)
	end 'then'
	if elseTarget == toBlockId 'else'
		return argAtOrNone(elseArgIds, argIdx: argIdx)
	end 'else'
	return REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
end 'incomingCondBrArg'

function argAtOrNone(argIds ValueIdArray, argIdx NodeIndex) returns ValueId
	return try argIds.get(argIdx) otherwise REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE
end 'argAtOrNone'

// True iff the incoming `vid` on an edge into a managed phi carries a
// transferable local +1 (so the MOVE alone is enough — no edge-incref).
// View over Concept A: a value carries a transferable +1 RIGHT NOW (at an edge /
// at a transfer store) iff it is NOT `noPlusOne` — i.e. either `acquiredAtDef`
// (it took its +1 at the def) or `arrivesOwning` (`callReturnRc1`, which carries
// the call's +1 without a def-acquire). This is the predicate that must NOT be the
// narrower `shouldAcquire`: a `callReturnRc1`-returning builder fed to a global /
// field transfers the call's +1 straight in, and using `shouldAcquire` here would
// add a SECOND +1 (a 1-per-owner leak). The non-managed/param/borrowed/non-
// acquiring-`incomingOwner` cases all collapse to `noPlusOne` in `plusOneOwnership`
// (a non-managed value reaching a managed phi is mem2reg's undef/zero sentinel; a
// non-acquiring `incomingOwner` is a pass-through borrow the phi-edge
// reconciliation must incref to hand the merged block-arg a clean owned ref).
function edgeValueCarriesPlusOne(ctx RcContext, vid ValueId) returns bool
	return match plusOneOwnership(ctx, id: vid) 'p1'
		acquiredAtDef gives true
		arrivesOwning gives true
		noPlusOne gives false
	end 'p1'
end 'edgeValueCarriesPlusOne'

// ============================================================
// Apply body-op insertions
// ============================================================

// Apply all queued body-op insertions. Insertions for one block are applied in
// DESCENDING position order so an earlier insert never shifts the index of a
// later one. Positions were all computed against the original op list.
function applyPlans(ctx RcContext)
	// Group by blockRef. blockRefs are dense small integers; a per-blockRef
	// bucket list keeps this O(n) without a map.
	for blockRef in ctx.func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		applyPlansForBlock(ctx, blockRef: blockRef)
	end 'eachBlock'
end 'applyPlans'

function applyPlansForBlock(ctx RcContext, blockRef BlockRef)
	// Collect this block's insertions.
	var mine = RcInsertionArray.create()
	for ins in ctx.insertions 'collect'
		if ins.blockRef == blockRef 'match'
			mine.push(ins)
		end 'match'
	end 'collect'
	if mine.count() == 0 'none'
		return
	end 'none'

	// Selection sort descending by position; ties keep insertion order reversed
	// so multiple ops planned at the same position land in plan order (an incref
	// planned before a decref at the same pos stays before it after both are
	// inserted descending — applying the later-planned one first at pos P pushes
	// it down, then the earlier one at pos P lands above it).
	sortInsertionsDescending(mine)

	let block = try ctx.module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("applyPlansForBlock: blockRef not in module.blocks")
	for ins in mine 'apply'
		try block.opRefs.insert(ins.pos, value: ins.opIdx) otherwise panic("applyPlansForBlock: opRefs.insert at {ins.pos} failed (count={block.opRefs.count()})")
	end 'apply'
end 'applyPlansForBlock'

// Selection sort of an RcInsertion array by descending `pos`. Stable enough for
// the same-position tie rule (equal positions retain their relative order, so
// applying them in sequence at the same index reverses them — see the caller's
// note). The arrays are tiny (a handful of refcount ops per block).
function sortInsertionsDescending(arr RcInsertionArray)
	let n = arr.count()
	var i = 0
	while i < n 'outer'
		var bestIdx = i
		var bestPos = (try arr.get(i) otherwise panic("sortInsertionsDescending: get({i}) OOB")).pos
		var j = i + 1
		while j < n 'inner'
			let cand = try arr.get(j) otherwise panic("sortInsertionsDescending: get({j}) OOB")
			if cand.pos > bestPos 'newBest'
				bestPos = cand.pos
				bestIdx = j
			end 'newBest'
			j = j + 1
		end 'inner'
		if bestIdx != i 'swap'
			// Snapshot both slots into fresh value copies before any `set` so
			// neither read borrows `arr` across a mutation.
			let aSnap = copyInsertion(try arr.get(i) otherwise panic("sortInsertionsDescending: swap get(i) OOB"))
			let bSnap = copyInsertion(try arr.get(bestIdx) otherwise panic("sortInsertionsDescending: swap get(bestIdx) OOB"))
			try arr.set(i, value: bSnap) otherwise panic("sortInsertionsDescending: swap set(i) OOB")
			try arr.set(bestIdx, value: aSnap) otherwise panic("sortInsertionsDescending: swap set(bestIdx) OOB")
		end 'swap'
		i = i + 1
	end 'outer'
end 'sortInsertionsDescending'

// Snapshot an RcInsertion into a fresh value (all fields are scalars), used by
// the swap so a read does not borrow the array across a `set`.
function copyInsertion(src RcInsertion) returns RcInsertion
	return RcInsertion.create(src.blockRef, pos: src.pos, opIdx: src.opIdx)
end 'copyInsertion'

// ============================================================
// Apply edge releases (with critical-edge splitting)
// ============================================================

// Apply every queued edge release. For an edge B→S:
//   - if S has exactly one predecessor (B), the decref is safe to emit at S's
//     head (every entry to S comes from B);
//   - otherwise the edge is CRITICAL: a fresh edge block E is inserted with the
//     decref + `br S`, and B's terminator is rewritten to target E. The edge's
//     phi args (if S has block-args) move to E's branch.
// Multiple releases for the same edge accumulate into the same edge block.
function applyEdgeReleases(ctx RcContext)
	for er in ctx.edgeReleases 'each'
		applyOneEdgeRelease(ctx, er: er)
	end 'each'
end 'applyEdgeReleases'

function applyOneEdgeRelease(ctx RcContext, er RcEdgeRelease)
	let fromBlock = findBlockById(ctx, blockId: er.fromBlockId)
	let toPreds = try ctx.cfg.predecessors.get(er.toBlockId) otherwise panic("applyOneEdgeRelease: predecessors missing for block {er.toBlockId}")

	let rcIdx = buildEdgeRcOp(ctx, er: er)

	if toPreds.count() == 1 'singlePred'
		// Single predecessor — every entry to the successor comes from this
		// edge, so the op is safe at the successor's head. (For an incref into a
		// phi this is fine: block-args bind on entry; an incref right after is
		// equivalent to incref-on-the-edge.)
		let toBlock = findBlockById(ctx, blockId: er.toBlockId)
		try toBlock.opRefs.insert(0, value: rcIdx) otherwise panic("applyOneEdgeRelease: opRefs.insert(0) failed at block {er.toBlockId}")
		return
	end 'singlePred'

	// Critical edge — split it. Reuse an edge block already created for this
	// (from, to) pair if one exists, else create one. The op (already pushed to
	// module.ops by buildEdgeRcOp) lands in the edge block's body, before its
	// `br toBlockId` terminator (terminators are not in opRefs, so appending to
	// the body keeps the op above the branch).
	let edgeBlock = getOrCreateEdgeBlock(ctx, fromBlock: fromBlock, toBlockId: er.toBlockId)
	try edgeBlock.opRefs.insert(edgeBlock.opRefs.count(), value: rcIdx) otherwise panic("applyOneEdgeRelease: edge-block opRefs.insert failed")
end 'applyOneEdgeRelease'

// Build the incref or release op for an edge refcount operation. The release
// form dispatches on the value's ReleaseKind (decref / free / dropTypeParam)
// via `buildReleaseOp`.
function buildEdgeRcOp(ctx RcContext, er RcEdgeRelease) returns OpIndex
	if er.isIncref 'incref'
		return buildIncrefOp(ctx.module, valueId: er.valueId, idRef: ctx.idRef)
	end 'incref'
	return buildReleaseOp(ctx, id: er.valueId)
end 'buildEdgeRcOp'

// Find or create the edge block splitting fromBlock→toBlockId. The created
// block does `br toBlockId` carrying the original edge's phi args, and
// fromBlock's terminator is rewritten to target the new block. Caches via a
// per-context list so repeated releases on the same edge share one block.
function getOrCreateEdgeBlock(ctx RcContext, fromBlock IrBlock, toBlockId BlockId) returns IrBlock
	// A previously-created edge block for this pair is the (unique) successor of
	// fromBlock whose label marks it as the split block targeting toBlockId. We
	// detect it by re-reading fromBlock's terminator: if it already targets a
	// block whose sole successor is toBlockId AND that block carries the split
	// label, reuse it.
	let existing = findExistingEdgeBlock(ctx, fromBlock: fromBlock, toBlockId: toBlockId)
	if existing.valueId != REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE 'reuse'
		return findBlockById(ctx, blockId: existing.valueId)
	end 'reuse'

	// Capture the original edge's phi args before rewriting the terminator.
	let edgeArgs = edgeArgsFor(ctx, fromBlock: fromBlock, toBlockId: toBlockId)

	let edgeBlock = ctx.module.addBlock(ctx.func, label: "__rc_edge_{fromBlock.id}_{toBlockId}")
	ctx.module.setTerminator(edgeBlock, op: StdOp.control(StdControlOp.br(toBlockId, argIds: edgeArgs)))

	// Rewrite fromBlock's terminator: retarget the toBlockId edge to edgeBlock,
	// dropping the phi args on that edge (they now flow from edgeBlock).
	rewriteTerminatorTarget(ctx, fromBlock: fromBlock, oldTarget: toBlockId, newTarget: edgeBlock.id)

	return edgeBlock
end 'getOrCreateEdgeBlock'

// A nullable BlockId result: `valueId == REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE` means "none".
type EdgeBlockLookup
	export var valueId as BlockId
	static function none() returns EdgeBlockLookup
		return Self{valueId: REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE}
	end 'none'
	static function some(blockId BlockId) returns EdgeBlockLookup
		return Self{valueId: blockId}
	end 'some'
end 'EdgeBlockLookup'

// Look for a split edge block already targeting toBlockId among fromBlock's
// current successors (identified by the `__rc_edge_` label prefix and a sole
// `br toBlockId` terminator).
function findExistingEdgeBlock(ctx RcContext, fromBlock IrBlock, toBlockId BlockId) returns EdgeBlockLookup
	if not fromBlock.hasTerminatorOp() 'noTerm'
		return EdgeBlockLookup.none()
	end 'noTerm'
	let term = try ctx.module.ops.get(fromBlock.terminatorIndex()) otherwise panic("findExistingEdgeBlock: terminator not in module.ops")
	let targets = terminatorTargets(term)
	for t in targets 'eachTarget'
		let candidate = tryFindBlockById(ctx, blockId: t)
		if candidate.valueId == REFCOUNT_NO_VALUE 'noBlock'
			continue
		end 'noBlock'
		let cand = findBlockById(ctx, blockId: t)
		if isSplitEdgeBlockTo(ctx, block: cand, toBlockId: toBlockId) 'isSplit'
			return EdgeBlockLookup.some(cand.id)
		end 'isSplit'
	end 'eachTarget'
	return EdgeBlockLookup.none()
end 'findExistingEdgeBlock'

function isSplitEdgeBlockTo(ctx RcContext, block IrBlock, toBlockId BlockId) returns bool
	if not block.label.startsWith("__rc_edge_") 'notSplit'
		return false
	end 'notSplit'
	if not block.hasTerminatorOp() 'noTerm'
		return false
	end 'noTerm'
	let term = try ctx.module.ops.get(block.terminatorIndex()) otherwise panic("isSplitEdgeBlockTo: terminator not in module.ops")
	return match term 'dispatch'
		control(cf) gives brTargets(cf, toBlockId: toBlockId)
		arith gives false
		call gives false
		memory gives false
		system gives false
	end 'dispatch'
end 'isSplitEdgeBlockTo'

function brTargets(cf StdControlOp, toBlockId BlockId) returns bool
	return match cf 'check'
		br(target, _) gives target == toBlockId
		condBr gives false
	end 'check'
end 'brTargets'

// The phi-arg list the original fromBlock→toBlockId edge passed (empty if the
// edge carried no args or the successor has no block-args).
function edgeArgsFor(ctx RcContext, fromBlock IrBlock, toBlockId BlockId) returns ValueIdArray
	if not fromBlock.hasTerminatorOp() 'noTerm'
		return ValueIdArray.create()
	end 'noTerm'
	let term = try ctx.module.ops.get(fromBlock.terminatorIndex()) otherwise panic("edgeArgsFor: terminator not in module.ops")
	return match term 'dispatch'
		control(cf) gives edgeArgsForCf(cf, toBlockId: toBlockId)
		arith gives ValueIdArray.create()
		call gives ValueIdArray.create()
		memory gives ValueIdArray.create()
		system gives ValueIdArray.create()
	end 'dispatch'
end 'edgeArgsFor'

function edgeArgsForCf(cf StdControlOp, toBlockId BlockId) returns ValueIdArray
	return match cf 'check'
		br(target, argIds) gives(cloneValueIdArray(argIds) if target == toBlockId else ValueIdArray.create())
		condBr(_, thenTarget, thenArgIds, elseTarget, elseArgIds) gives condBrEdgeArgs(thenTarget, thenArgIds: thenArgIds, elseTarget: elseTarget, elseArgIds: elseArgIds, toBlockId: toBlockId)
	end 'check'
end 'edgeArgsForCf'

function condBrEdgeArgs(thenTarget BlockId, thenArgIds ValueIdArray, elseTarget BlockId, elseArgIds ValueIdArray, toBlockId BlockId) returns ValueIdArray
	if thenTarget == toBlockId 'then'
		return cloneValueIdArray(thenArgIds)
	end 'then'
	if elseTarget == toBlockId 'else'
		return cloneValueIdArray(elseArgIds)
	end 'else'
	return ValueIdArray.create()
end 'condBrEdgeArgs'

function cloneValueIdArray(src ValueIdArray) returns ValueIdArray
	var copy = ValueIdArray.create()
	for v in src 'each'
		copy.push(v)
	end 'each'
	return copy
end 'cloneValueIdArray'

// Rewrite fromBlock's terminator so the edge to `oldTarget` instead goes to
// `newTarget`, dropping that edge's phi args (they flow from the new edge
// block's `br`). The opposite edge of a condBr is untouched.
function rewriteTerminatorTarget(ctx RcContext, fromBlock IrBlock, oldTarget BlockId, newTarget BlockId)
	let term = try ctx.module.ops.get(fromBlock.terminatorIndex()) otherwise panic("rewriteTerminatorTarget: terminator not in module.ops")
	var rewrittenCf = StdControlOp.br(newTarget, argIds: ValueIdArray.create())
	match term 'dispatch'
		control(cf) then rewrittenCf = rewriteCfTarget(cf, oldTarget: oldTarget, newTarget: newTarget)
		arith then panic("rewriteTerminatorTarget: non-control terminator on block {fromBlock.id}")
		call then panic("rewriteTerminatorTarget: non-control terminator on block {fromBlock.id}")
		memory then panic("rewriteTerminatorTarget: non-control terminator on block {fromBlock.id}")
		system then panic("rewriteTerminatorTarget: non-control terminator on block {fromBlock.id}")
	end 'dispatch'
	let newIdx = ctx.module.ops.count()
	ctx.module.ops.push(StdOp.control(rewrittenCf))
	fromBlock.terminator = Terminator.opIndex(newIdx)
end 'rewriteTerminatorTarget'

function rewriteCfTarget(cf StdControlOp, oldTarget BlockId, newTarget BlockId) returns StdControlOp
	return match cf 'check'
		br(target, argIds) gives rewriteBrTarget(target, argIds: argIds, oldTarget: oldTarget, newTarget: newTarget)
		condBr(condId, thenTarget, thenArgIds, elseTarget, elseArgIds) gives rewriteCondBrTarget(condId, thenTarget: thenTarget, thenArgIds: thenArgIds, elseTarget: elseTarget, elseArgIds: elseArgIds, oldTarget: oldTarget, newTarget: newTarget)
	end 'check'
end 'rewriteCfTarget'

function rewriteBrTarget(target BlockId, argIds ValueIdArray, oldTarget BlockId, newTarget BlockId) returns StdControlOp
	if target == oldTarget 'hit'
		// Args now flow from the edge block; this br just transfers control.
		return StdControlOp.br(newTarget, argIds: ValueIdArray.create())
	end 'hit'
	return StdControlOp.br(target, argIds: argIds)
end 'rewriteBrTarget'

function rewriteCondBrTarget(condId ValueId, thenTarget BlockId, thenArgIds ValueIdArray, elseTarget BlockId, elseArgIds ValueIdArray, oldTarget BlockId, newTarget BlockId) returns StdControlOp
	var newThen = thenTarget
	var newThenArgs = thenArgIds
	var newElse = elseTarget
	var newElseArgs = elseArgIds
	if thenTarget == oldTarget 'thenHit'
		newThen = newTarget
		newThenArgs = ValueIdArray.create()
	end 'thenHit'
	if elseTarget == oldTarget 'elseHit'
		newElse = newTarget
		newElseArgs = ValueIdArray.create()
	end 'elseHit'
	return StdControlOp.condBr(condId, thenTarget: newThen, thenArgIds: newThenArgs, elseTarget: newElse, elseArgIds: newElseArgs)
end 'rewriteCondBrTarget'

// The set of block-target ids a terminator branches to.
function terminatorTargets(term StdOp) returns BlockIdArray
	var targets = BlockIdArray.create()
	match term 'dispatch'
		control(cf) then collectCfTargets(cf, targets: targets)
		arith then break 'dispatch'
		call then break 'dispatch'
		memory then break 'dispatch'
		system then break 'dispatch'
	end 'dispatch'
	return targets
end 'terminatorTargets'

function collectCfTargets(cf StdControlOp, targets BlockIdArray)
	match cf 'check'
		br(target, _) then targets.push(target)
		condBr(_, thenTarget, _, elseTarget, _) then pushCondBrTargets(thenTarget, elseTarget: elseTarget, targets: targets)
	end 'check'
end 'collectCfTargets'

function pushCondBrTargets(thenTarget BlockId, elseTarget BlockId, targets BlockIdArray)
	targets.push(thenTarget)
	targets.push(elseTarget)
end 'pushCondBrTargets'

// ============================================================
// Block lookup
// ============================================================

function findBlockById(ctx RcContext, blockId BlockId) returns IrBlock
	for blockRef in ctx.func.blockRefs 'each'
		let block = try ctx.module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("findBlockById: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		if block.id == blockId 'found'
			return block
		end 'found'
	end 'each'
	panic("findBlockById: no block with id {blockId} in func '{ctx.func.name}'")
end 'findBlockById'

function tryFindBlockById(ctx RcContext, blockId BlockId) returns EdgeBlockLookup
	for blockRef in ctx.func.blockRefs 'each'
		let block = try ctx.module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("tryFindBlockById: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		if block.id == blockId 'found'
			return EdgeBlockLookup.some(blockId)
		end 'found'
	end 'each'
	return EdgeBlockLookup.none()
end 'tryFindBlockById'
